WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:22.010 --> 00:00:23.310
:

00:00:23.310 --> 00:00:24.610
&gt;&gt; Robert Newlen: Good
morning, everyone.

00:00:24.610 --> 00:00:27.110
And on behalf of Dr.
Carla Hayden the librarian

00:00:27.110 --> 00:00:31.620
of Congress, it's my pleasure
to welcome you to the library.

00:00:31.620 --> 00:00:33.310
My name is Robert Newlen.

00:00:33.310 --> 00:00:34.810
I have the pleasure of serving

00:00:34.810 --> 00:00:38.150
as the deputy librarian
of Congress.

00:00:38.150 --> 00:00:40.010
We are delighted
to be partnering

00:00:40.010 --> 00:00:42.910
with the Kennedy Center and
Washington Performing Arts

00:00:42.910 --> 00:00:46.860
and co-hosting this special
symposium Leading the Change:

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:50.900
Orchestra Innovation
and the Shift Festival.

00:00:50.900 --> 00:00:54.230
There's been a wonderful
buzz about this excellent

00:00:54.230 --> 00:00:57.280
and exciting festival
around Washington this week,

00:00:57.280 --> 00:01:00.230
about the great concerts and
events like this one that reach

00:01:00.230 --> 00:01:02.850
out into the community
of music lovers.

00:01:02.850 --> 00:01:05.750
And we're really
pleased to be part of it.

00:01:05.750 --> 00:01:08.730
I would first like to
acknowledge our partners,

00:01:08.730 --> 00:01:12.440
the creators and presenters
of the Shift Festival.

00:01:12.440 --> 00:01:17.490
First, the -- and I can only
say the fabulous Debra Rutter,

00:01:17.490 --> 00:01:20.220
the president of the Kennedy
Center who was traveling

00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:22.600
with the National Symphony
Orchestra this week

00:01:22.600 --> 00:01:24.680
in its Russia trip.

00:01:24.680 --> 00:01:29.540
Robert van Leer the Center's
vice president for programming.

00:01:29.540 --> 00:01:33.230
And Jenny Bilfield,
president and CEO

00:01:33.230 --> 00:01:36.990
of Washington Performing Arts.

00:01:36.990 --> 00:01:39.740
I know that among our audience
this morning we have music

00:01:39.740 --> 00:01:43.630
lovers, composers,
arts professionals

00:01:43.630 --> 00:01:45.330
and representatives for several

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:49.300
of the very top orchestras
in the nation.

00:01:49.300 --> 00:01:53.180
And I would like to welcome
particularly Jesse Rosen,

00:01:53.180 --> 00:01:57.060
president and CEO of the
League of American Orchestras.

00:01:57.060 --> 00:02:00.180
It's very appropriate
for us to host you today

00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:04.360
because great music has a
very strong tradition here

00:02:04.360 --> 00:02:06.050
at the library.

00:02:06.050 --> 00:02:09.250
Many of you are probably aware
of our historic concert series,

00:02:09.250 --> 00:02:11.640
now over 90 years old.

00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:14.010
This wonderful auditorium
that you're sitting

00:02:14.010 --> 00:02:19.100
in that's a bit chilly this
morning, was built in 1925

00:02:19.100 --> 00:02:22.130
by Elizabeth Spregg Coolidge

00:02:22.130 --> 00:02:25.340
in a groundbreaking
public/private partnership.

00:02:25.340 --> 00:02:27.410
And it's been the home
of terrific concerts

00:02:27.410 --> 00:02:30.860
over the years, everything
from classical, jazz, pop,

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:32.160
country and much more.

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:34.800
Our stage has seen the premier

00:02:34.800 --> 00:02:37.420
of Aaron Copeland's
Appalachian Spring,

00:02:37.420 --> 00:02:42.260
now an icon of the repertoire,
along with performances

00:02:42.260 --> 00:02:48.070
by composers from Bartok to
Bernstein and Stevie Wonder.

00:02:48.070 --> 00:02:50.860
And I invite you to spend some
time looking at the display

00:02:50.860 --> 00:02:53.730
of manuscripts our curators
have prepared for you,

00:02:53.730 --> 00:02:59.040
just a few of the major
orchestral works in our vaults.

00:02:59.040 --> 00:03:02.400
Here at the library we share
your passion for creating superb

00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:07.270
and vibrant programs that open
all our doors to the widest,

00:03:07.270 --> 00:03:12.120
most diverse and most
engaged audiences possible.

00:03:12.120 --> 00:03:15.440
Like you, we are committed
to innovation and to outreach

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:20.430
and education and increased
access for young people.

00:03:20.430 --> 00:03:23.520
I should mention that a little
later you'll hear a stellar

00:03:23.520 --> 00:03:26.750
youth orchestra group from
Play On Philly which travelled

00:03:26.750 --> 00:03:30.520
down this morning just
to perform for you.

00:03:30.520 --> 00:03:34.900
On a personal note, I've been
reading a lot about Shift

00:03:34.900 --> 00:03:37.270
and the kinds of
outreach you do.

00:03:37.270 --> 00:03:40.980
As somebody that had virtually
no music education as a child

00:03:40.980 --> 00:03:43.730
or as a teenager, the kind
of work you're doing is

00:03:43.730 --> 00:03:48.450
so important, and I wish I'd had
the opportunity to be exposed

00:03:48.450 --> 00:03:51.790
to the kinds of things
you're doing.

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:55.440
Regarding our current
programs here at the library,

00:03:55.440 --> 00:03:59.490
I can't resist by leading
you with mention of something

00:03:59.490 --> 00:04:02.830
that you may have read about in
the New York Times yesterday.

00:04:02.830 --> 00:04:04.470
And that is something
that's coming

00:04:04.470 --> 00:04:06.990
to the library the
first week of May.

00:04:06.990 --> 00:04:10.130
It's called Biblio-Disco-Tech,

00:04:10.130 --> 00:04:14.470
and it's a library-wide
celebration of disco culture,

00:04:14.470 --> 00:04:16.520
music, dance and fashion.

00:04:16.520 --> 00:04:20.160
So over the week we're going to
have a number of music experts,

00:04:20.160 --> 00:04:22.660
panels that are all
open to the public.

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:25.200
Tim Gunn from Project
Runway will be here

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:27.880
to talk about '70's fashion.

00:04:27.880 --> 00:04:32.450
And the week will be
capped on Saturday,

00:04:32.450 --> 00:04:35.840
May 6th with a disco party

00:04:35.840 --> 00:04:41.730
in the great hall featuring
none other than Gloria Gaynor.

00:04:41.730 --> 00:04:46.280
So we are so excited.

00:04:46.280 --> 00:04:50.400
Miss Gaynor's song I
Will Survive was put

00:04:50.400 --> 00:04:54.150
on our song registry and
got lots of publicity,

00:04:54.150 --> 00:04:56.800
so we decided, let's
really celebrate this

00:04:56.800 --> 00:05:00.520
and bring Miss Gaynor
to the library.

00:05:00.520 --> 00:05:02.560
So she graciously agreed.

00:05:02.560 --> 00:05:05.270
So watch our website.

00:05:05.270 --> 00:05:10.140
It is a ticketed event, but
it's free so take a look

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:14.660
at our website, because I know
tickets will go very, very fast.

00:05:14.660 --> 00:05:19.100
So let me state finally that
the Library of Congress music

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:23.100
of all kinds is a crucial and
vital element in our mandate

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:27.250
to preserve and present the
best in our American culture.

00:05:27.250 --> 00:05:29.310
Thank you so much
for coming today.

00:05:29.310 --> 00:05:31.730
If this is your first
visit to the Library,

00:05:31.730 --> 00:05:33.840
I hope it won't be your last.

00:05:33.840 --> 00:05:36.550
Check out our website, LOC.gov.

00:05:36.550 --> 00:05:40.190
We have programs all
year long and music

00:05:40.190 --> 00:05:42.690
and every other topic
you can imagine.

00:05:42.690 --> 00:05:43.990
This is your library.

00:05:43.990 --> 00:05:46.390
It belongs to the United
States and to the world.

00:05:46.390 --> 00:05:49.060
So we're just delighted
to have you here.

00:05:49.060 --> 00:05:50.940
And please enjoy your day.

00:05:50.940 --> 00:05:53.510
Thanks again.

00:05:53.510 --> 00:06:02.040
[ Applause ]

00:06:02.040 --> 00:06:03.340
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Thank you.

00:06:03.340 --> 00:06:04.640
Good morning.

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:05.940
I'm Jenny Bilfield with
Washington Performing Arts.

00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:07.240
It's wonderful to
see you all today.

00:06:07.240 --> 00:06:08.860
Excuse me just one moment.

00:06:08.860 --> 00:06:10.280
And thank you so much, Robert,

00:06:10.280 --> 00:06:13.710
for the wonderful
introduction of our guests.

00:06:13.710 --> 00:06:15.360
We're so happy to be
here, very grateful

00:06:15.360 --> 00:06:16.810
to the Library of Congress.

00:06:16.810 --> 00:06:18.110
And I want to welcome
you on behalf

00:06:18.110 --> 00:06:19.410
of Washington Performing Arts,

00:06:19.410 --> 00:06:21.030
the League of American
Orchestras,

00:06:21.030 --> 00:06:22.450
and the Kennedy Center.

00:06:22.450 --> 00:06:24.790
I bring greetings from
Debra Rutter my friend

00:06:24.790 --> 00:06:26.970
and collaborator
who is traveling

00:06:26.970 --> 00:06:29.470
with the National Symphony
Orchestra this week in Russia

00:06:29.470 --> 00:06:31.000
and she couldn't be here.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:32.800
I know that she's
very disappointed

00:06:32.800 --> 00:06:34.960
to miss participating in
a festival that she has

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:37.300
so strongly believed
in and been committed

00:06:37.300 --> 00:06:39.430
to from the very,
very beginning.

00:06:39.430 --> 00:06:42.170
So after two and a half years
of planning, we have arrived

00:06:42.170 --> 00:06:45.440
at this week and it's very
exciting to start it here

00:06:45.440 --> 00:06:49.770
in a place that is of music and
has had such an important impact

00:06:49.770 --> 00:06:52.070
in the cultural life
of this country.

00:06:52.070 --> 00:06:55.420
I wanted to give you a little
bit of a background about Shift.

00:06:55.420 --> 00:07:00.060
And it was really founded
based upon a vantage point

00:07:00.060 --> 00:07:01.360
of optimism.

00:07:01.360 --> 00:07:03.890
Optimism about orchestras
and the sense

00:07:03.890 --> 00:07:07.000
that orchestras are the hubs
of culture and learning within

00:07:07.000 --> 00:07:08.800
and outside their institutions.

00:07:08.800 --> 00:07:12.010
You know, very often
orchestras make the news

00:07:12.010 --> 00:07:15.210
when there is some strife,
when there's a strike

00:07:15.210 --> 00:07:18.650
or a negotiation or
something is going poorly.

00:07:18.650 --> 00:07:21.460
And in contrast, Debra
and I felt very strongly

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:24.500
that there were wonderful
stories to be told,

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:27.670
and that orchestras were doing
some of the most creative,

00:07:27.670 --> 00:07:30.940
energizing and energized
work within the arts world.

00:07:30.940 --> 00:07:32.530
And we wanted to
tell that story.

00:07:32.530 --> 00:07:36.020
We also believed that if
audiences could experience this,

00:07:36.020 --> 00:07:39.360
they might actually shift their
perceptions of orchestras.

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:41.430
So for that reason,
Shift was the name.

00:07:41.430 --> 00:07:44.470
A shift in mindset, a
shift in perception,

00:07:44.470 --> 00:07:45.770
a shift in experience.

00:07:45.770 --> 00:07:48.360
So I hope if you travel
through the whole week with us,

00:07:48.360 --> 00:07:51.360
you will have that
experience yourself.

00:07:51.360 --> 00:07:53.440
We were inspired by
the multi-year series

00:07:53.440 --> 00:07:56.070
of orchestral performances
in New York under the name

00:07:56.070 --> 00:07:58.320
of Spring for Music that were
presented at Carnegie Hall

00:07:58.320 --> 00:08:01.820
by Tom Morris, Marylou Falconi
and David Foster, and designed

00:08:01.820 --> 00:08:03.800
to highlight creative
programming.

00:08:03.800 --> 00:08:06.470
We are very grateful for
their example and the impact

00:08:06.470 --> 00:08:10.550
of their work and their lifelong
commitment to orchestras.

00:08:10.550 --> 00:08:12.940
From the get-go,
Washington Performing Arts

00:08:12.940 --> 00:08:15.530
and the Kennedy Center
wanted to think expansively

00:08:15.530 --> 00:08:17.710
and to extend the
notion of a festival

00:08:17.710 --> 00:08:19.910
to many residencies
within a festival.

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:21.950
And that's what this
week is about.

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:25.560
We wanted to focus on orchestras
of all sizes, as you'll see.

00:08:25.560 --> 00:08:28.110
And we wanted to in some
way transpose the great work

00:08:28.110 --> 00:08:29.870
that orchestras do
in their hometowns

00:08:29.870 --> 00:08:32.510
and cities to our DC community.

00:08:32.510 --> 00:08:34.760
We believed that we had the
institutional commitment,

00:08:34.760 --> 00:08:37.690
scale and partners
to undertake this.

00:08:37.690 --> 00:08:39.200
And we thought of
course what better place

00:08:39.200 --> 00:08:41.870
to showcase this work than
in the nation's capital,

00:08:41.870 --> 00:08:43.170
the seat of government,

00:08:43.170 --> 00:08:45.510
the center of diplomacy
and policymaking?

00:08:45.510 --> 00:08:49.050
And quite an extraordinary
arts community as well.

00:08:49.050 --> 00:08:51.790
Orchestras that applied to our
national call for proposals rose

00:08:51.790 --> 00:08:54.820
to the occasion and the offered
programs and residency plans

00:08:54.820 --> 00:08:57.350
that were ambitious,
specific and completely

00:08:57.350 --> 00:08:59.430
and utterly reflective
of what they do well

00:08:59.430 --> 00:09:00.850
and what they value.

00:09:00.850 --> 00:09:04.010
The ideas leapt off the
page, and coincidentally,

00:09:04.010 --> 00:09:06.390
all seemed to express
their unique identity

00:09:06.390 --> 00:09:09.120
through very specific
collaborations, commissions,

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:13.060
partnerships and a healthy dose
of contemporary American music.

00:09:13.060 --> 00:09:15.180
American orchestras coming
to the nation's capital

00:09:15.180 --> 00:09:19.230
with a bumper crop of American
works, we were inspired.

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:21.240
Today's symposium
will give us a chance

00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:23.830
to discuss why Shift
is important not just

00:09:23.830 --> 00:09:26.200
in this hyper-focused lens
of a one-week festival,

00:09:26.200 --> 00:09:29.350
but more broadly in the
context of orchestras' value

00:09:29.350 --> 00:09:30.830
within their communities.

00:09:30.830 --> 00:09:32.990
We'll look at the risks
and rewards of innovation,

00:09:32.990 --> 00:09:35.880
explore what's gotten us to this
point, and we'll have a chance

00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:39.640
to actually hear music with a
Play On Philly chamber ensemble.

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:41.550
I'm very happy to have
music at the centerpiece

00:09:41.550 --> 00:09:43.800
of this festival
and the symposium.

00:09:43.800 --> 00:09:47.330
From the get-go, the Andrew W.
Mellon Foundation supported our

00:09:47.330 --> 00:09:49.190
vision and provided
generous seed funding

00:09:49.190 --> 00:09:50.820
that enabled us to
green-light Shift.

00:09:50.820 --> 00:09:53.390
And I'm very pleased that
Susan Fader can be here

00:09:53.390 --> 00:09:55.930
to see how this all unfolds.

00:09:55.930 --> 00:09:59.830
Mellon support was matched by
Tina and Gary Mather, Michael

00:09:59.830 --> 00:10:03.490
and Naomi Nidorf and the
Centine Charitable Foundation,

00:10:03.490 --> 00:10:05.460
the DC Commission on
Arts and Humanities

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:07.060
which is an agency
supported in part

00:10:07.060 --> 00:10:09.590
by the National Endowment
for the Arts.

00:10:09.590 --> 00:10:11.700
And also by the Abramson
Family Foundation,

00:10:11.700 --> 00:10:14.880
Betsy and Robert Fineburg,
Morton and Norma Lee Funger

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:17.050
and Daniel R. Lewis
among other donors.

00:10:17.050 --> 00:10:18.480
We're very grateful
for their support

00:10:18.480 --> 00:10:22.060
and we could not have done
it without them, literally.

00:10:22.060 --> 00:10:24.300
Huge thanks to our teams,
boards, our partners

00:10:24.300 --> 00:10:26.900
and to the participating
orchestras, the staff,

00:10:26.900 --> 00:10:28.830
musicians and their boards.

00:10:28.830 --> 00:10:30.820
A special shout-out
to Samantha Polluck

00:10:30.820 --> 00:10:33.950
from Washington Performing Arts,
and Jamie Brumus, counterparts

00:10:33.950 --> 00:10:36.540
who worked so closely and
really bore the lion's share

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:37.980
of organizing this.

00:10:37.980 --> 00:10:39.280
They are treasures.

00:10:39.280 --> 00:10:41.450
And when you see them, thank
them, give them a squeeze.

00:10:41.450 --> 00:10:45.030
They deserve every good wish
and our great appreciation

00:10:45.030 --> 00:10:46.700
for their efforts in
putting this together.

00:10:46.700 --> 00:10:49.830
And to Kathy French who
believed in this idea

00:10:49.830 --> 00:10:51.170
from the very beginning.

00:10:51.170 --> 00:10:53.740
She was part of Spring
for Music and she is here

00:10:53.740 --> 00:10:56.810
in Washington DC, and a
lifelong friend of the arts

00:10:56.810 --> 00:11:01.550
and a longtime CEO of the
League of American Orchestras.

00:11:01.550 --> 00:11:03.650
Jesse Rosen is her successor.

00:11:03.650 --> 00:11:07.670
We're very grateful, Kathy,
for your support early on.

00:11:07.670 --> 00:11:09.970
We're so happy that so many of
you who believed in this early

00:11:09.970 --> 00:11:12.790
on are here with us today
to see how this is launched.

00:11:12.790 --> 00:11:14.340
We're very grateful.

00:11:14.340 --> 00:11:18.100
So I'll play the role of MC
today, as you may have gathered.

00:11:18.100 --> 00:11:21.280
And very soon moderator
for the first panel.

00:11:21.280 --> 00:11:22.760
But right now it gives
me great pleasure

00:11:22.760 --> 00:11:26.370
to introduce Rhona Wolfe
Friedman who is commissioner

00:11:26.370 --> 00:11:29.910
on the DC Commission
of Arts and Humanities.

00:11:29.910 --> 00:11:32.570
She is one of our city's
most emphatic evangelists

00:11:32.570 --> 00:11:34.640
for the arts and she's
a cherished friend.

00:11:34.640 --> 00:11:36.580
She's an attorney
with master's degrees

00:11:36.580 --> 00:11:38.880
in clinical psychology
and decorative arts.

00:11:38.880 --> 00:11:41.220
She's hardly an underachiever.

00:11:41.220 --> 00:11:43.980
She's a remarkable and
accomplished woman.

00:11:43.980 --> 00:11:46.590
The focus of her advocacy and
commission tenure have been

00:11:46.590 --> 00:11:49.890
in arts education policy
and also around quantifying

00:11:49.890 --> 00:11:52.690
and growing the creative
economy in Washington DC.

00:11:52.690 --> 00:11:55.110
She is on the board of
THEARC, which is an acronym

00:11:55.110 --> 00:11:58.490
for the Town Hall Education
Arts and Recreation Center.

00:11:58.490 --> 00:11:59.790
And she served on the boards

00:11:59.790 --> 00:12:01.620
of the Washington
Ballet and Lab School.

00:12:01.620 --> 00:12:03.240
She is fiercely committed

00:12:03.240 --> 00:12:06.030
to this community
and to its citizens.

00:12:06.030 --> 00:12:07.880
We've asked her to open
our symposium by speaking

00:12:07.880 --> 00:12:10.030
about the importance
of Shift and orchestras

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:13.550
as an essential civic asset in
strengthening our communities.

00:12:13.550 --> 00:12:15.510
Please join me in welcoming
Rhona Wolfe Friedman.

00:12:15.510 --> 00:12:25.320
[ Applause ]

00:12:25.320 --> 00:12:26.760
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
Good morning.

00:12:26.760 --> 00:12:30.290
I'd like to thank the
Library of Congress

00:12:30.290 --> 00:12:32.870
for hosting this
wonderful symposium.

00:12:32.870 --> 00:12:36.560
And a huge debt of gratitude
to the Kennedy Center

00:12:36.560 --> 00:12:38.890
and Washington Performing
Arts and the League

00:12:38.890 --> 00:12:42.640
of American Orchestras for
their collaborative efforts

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:47.090
in presenting Shift, the
festival of American orchestras.

00:12:47.090 --> 00:12:51.420
How lucky we are in our nation's
capital to have a week-long,

00:12:51.420 --> 00:12:54.680
immersive musical experience.

00:12:54.680 --> 00:12:58.210
The concept of Shift
defines what is happening

00:12:58.210 --> 00:13:00.000
in the arts today.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.860
The Shift festival here
celebrates American music,

00:13:03.860 --> 00:13:06.910
highlights different
size orchestras,

00:13:06.910 --> 00:13:10.390
where they perform
and whom they serve.

00:13:10.390 --> 00:13:14.720
This focus on American
orchestras allows audiences

00:13:14.720 --> 00:13:17.470
and participants to
educate themselves

00:13:17.470 --> 00:13:21.300
about music perhaps
not familiar to them.

00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:25.420
At the same time, it affords
participating orchestras the

00:13:25.420 --> 00:13:28.670
chance to showcase
new compositions

00:13:28.670 --> 00:13:31.470
and perform their finest works.

00:13:31.470 --> 00:13:34.050
What a winning combination
we have here,

00:13:34.050 --> 00:13:37.600
music and distinctive
outreach programs.

00:13:37.600 --> 00:13:40.420
We think about the
shifting landscape.

00:13:40.420 --> 00:13:41.720
I would like you to think

00:13:41.720 --> 00:13:45.840
about President John F.
Kennedy's quote: "Art means more

00:13:45.840 --> 00:13:48.280
than the recitation of the past.

00:13:48.280 --> 00:13:52.650
It means the free and
unconfined search for new ways

00:13:52.650 --> 00:13:56.260
of expressing the
experience of the present

00:13:56.260 --> 00:13:58.530
and the vision of the future."

00:13:58.530 --> 00:14:03.450
In the broadest sense, the arts
including the humanities can be

00:14:03.450 --> 00:14:08.350
thought of as the four
C's: curiosity, creation,

00:14:08.350 --> 00:14:11.520
connection and communication.

00:14:11.520 --> 00:14:18.720
In 1943, Abraham Maslow proposed
a theory of human motivation,

00:14:18.720 --> 00:14:21.860
now called the hierarchy
of human needs.

00:14:21.860 --> 00:14:25.440
It encompassed eventually
innate curiosity.

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:29.740
He formed a pyramid with
base needs at the bottom.

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:33.280
Safety, moving up the
ladder to love, belonging,

00:14:33.280 --> 00:14:37.640
esteem and finally
self-actualization.

00:14:37.640 --> 00:14:41.620
I submit that the arts play
a vital role in meeting

00:14:41.620 --> 00:14:44.440
so many of our human needs.

00:14:44.440 --> 00:14:47.720
They help provide an
understanding of our emotions,

00:14:47.720 --> 00:14:50.950
increase our self-awareness
and bridge the gap

00:14:50.950 --> 00:14:53.030
between different cultures.

00:14:53.030 --> 00:14:58.190
How would a society be able to
preserve and share its culture,

00:14:58.190 --> 00:15:03.110
progress and valued
traditions if not for the arts?

00:15:03.110 --> 00:15:07.700
People connect, thrive and
prosper through the arts.

00:15:07.700 --> 00:15:11.670
In our complex world today,
the arts are a necessary tool

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:17.070
to help manage the shifting
dynamic issues we face.

00:15:17.070 --> 00:15:21.430
We cannot replace the arts, nor
allow them to be diminished.

00:15:21.430 --> 00:15:24.230
They are a lens from
which to look at the past

00:15:24.230 --> 00:15:27.070
and look forward to the future.

00:15:27.070 --> 00:15:31.670
Without the arts, we become
a silent society unable

00:15:31.670 --> 00:15:35.560
to accurately evaluate
our surroundings.

00:15:35.560 --> 00:15:42.530
Orchestras as an indispensable
art form play an important part

00:15:42.530 --> 00:15:43.830
in American life.

00:15:43.830 --> 00:15:48.060
They are part and parcel of
our life today in both large

00:15:48.060 --> 00:15:50.790
and small communities.

00:15:50.790 --> 00:15:54.510
They improve the quality of the
cultural fabric of a community

00:15:54.510 --> 00:15:58.410
and foster pride in
local neighborhoods.

00:15:58.410 --> 00:16:03.250
In 2016, Ian David
Moss discussed the arts

00:16:03.250 --> 00:16:06.720
in the Stanford Social
Innovation Review.

00:16:06.720 --> 00:16:11.130
He suggested using a holistic
approach, tying the arts

00:16:11.130 --> 00:16:14.220
into wellbeing and
quality of life.

00:16:14.220 --> 00:16:17.450
We can use this same approach
to expand the definition

00:16:17.450 --> 00:16:20.620
of what an orchestra
is: promoting wellbeing

00:16:20.620 --> 00:16:23.980
and enhancing the
quality of life.

00:16:24.990 --> 00:16:30.740
Orchestras are a critical
resource for arts education.

00:16:30.740 --> 00:16:32.470
Playing different instruments,

00:16:32.470 --> 00:16:37.170
they demonstrate teamwork
at its highest level.

00:16:37.170 --> 00:16:40.790
Older models of music
education are shifting today.

00:16:40.790 --> 00:16:44.230
Schools with orchestra-based
programs are demonstrating

00:16:44.230 --> 00:16:47.390
that their populations
have greater skills

00:16:47.390 --> 00:16:50.930
than students lacking
a musical education.

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:53.400
While students develop
musical talents,

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:56.780
they're also increasing
competencies in subjects

00:16:56.780 --> 00:16:59.950
such as math and reading.

00:16:59.950 --> 00:17:03.910
To be pragmatic,
the arts make money.

00:17:03.910 --> 00:17:05.960
They are a critical
economic driver

00:17:05.960 --> 00:17:08.480
and force in this country.

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:14.260
Orchestras play a key role
in an economy of a city.

00:17:14.260 --> 00:17:18.360
They help populations develop
skills that are transferrable

00:17:18.360 --> 00:17:22.680
and assist in the
revitalization of neighborhoods.

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:26.520
Both large and small orchestras
understand that they need

00:17:26.520 --> 00:17:29.460
to be relevant to
their communities.

00:17:29.460 --> 00:17:33.140
Today, they're engaging in
novel ways to include residents

00:17:33.140 --> 00:17:38.430
with varying economic, racial
and social backgrounds.

00:17:38.430 --> 00:17:41.980
A necessary shift is
transforming the way orchestras

00:17:41.980 --> 00:17:46.120
strengthen, broaden and
deepen their relationships.

00:17:46.120 --> 00:17:49.070
The shift is multidimensional.

00:17:49.070 --> 00:17:53.060
Orchestras are connecting
and serving the community not

00:17:53.060 --> 00:17:56.610
by exclusivity but
by inclusivity.

00:17:56.610 --> 00:18:01.100
Orchestras should keep
advancing a very basic concept:

00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:04.470
that a healthy community
must have an orchestra,

00:18:04.470 --> 00:18:08.370
and demonstrate that this
orchestra is a powerful tool

00:18:08.370 --> 00:18:12.570
to form connections and
promote vibrancy throughout

00:18:12.570 --> 00:18:13.870
the community.

00:18:13.870 --> 00:18:17.570
Some approaches an
orchestra may consider

00:18:17.570 --> 00:18:21.580
to remain relevant are
one, act with a purpose;

00:18:21.580 --> 00:18:25.270
one that's directed outside
of the orchestra itself.

00:18:25.270 --> 00:18:28.870
Pursue goals that
serve community needs.

00:18:28.870 --> 00:18:33.200
Evaluate; evaluate what
works and what's dead weight.

00:18:33.200 --> 00:18:38.710
Move ahead with strategies that
are working and stay focused.

00:18:38.710 --> 00:18:41.450
Play towards strength.

00:18:41.450 --> 00:18:43.210
Reality can bite.

00:18:43.210 --> 00:18:47.900
Lessen the sting with realistic
goals that allow for shifts.

00:18:47.900 --> 00:18:52.080
Leverage the power of
orchestra leaders and musicians

00:18:52.080 --> 00:18:56.730
to forge dynamic community
interactions through education,

00:18:56.730 --> 00:18:59.630
networking and engagement.

00:18:59.630 --> 00:19:01.800
And last, reboot.

00:19:01.800 --> 00:19:05.020
Reboot to help work
for a paradigm shift

00:19:05.020 --> 00:19:09.090
in the way a community
views orchestra.

00:19:09.090 --> 00:19:13.240
Encourage experimentation
in thought and action,

00:19:13.240 --> 00:19:15.930
which brings me back
to the Shift Festival.

00:19:15.930 --> 00:19:18.110
Focusing on orchestras

00:19:18.110 --> 00:19:21.990
in our nation's capital
is a powerful reminder

00:19:21.990 --> 00:19:23.610
of their importance.

00:19:23.610 --> 00:19:25.120
This does not detract

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:28.230
from non-orchestral
musical expression.

00:19:28.230 --> 00:19:33.510
This creative festival moves
forward with goals, purpose

00:19:33.510 --> 00:19:35.570
and community involvement.

00:19:35.570 --> 00:19:39.230
It demonstrates how music
can lift the human spirit,

00:19:39.230 --> 00:19:42.330
how orchestras are
involved in our community

00:19:42.330 --> 00:19:47.270
and for a $25 ticket, how people
can connect with an art form

00:19:47.270 --> 00:19:50.850
that has withstood
the test of time.

00:19:50.850 --> 00:19:53.640
And finally, I would
be remiss as the member

00:19:53.640 --> 00:19:55.730
of an arts commission
that receives money

00:19:55.730 --> 00:19:57.820
from the National
Endowment for the Arts

00:19:57.820 --> 00:20:02.650
if I did not offer a reminder
of how critical the NEA is

00:20:02.650 --> 00:20:04.060
for sustaining the arts.

00:20:04.060 --> 00:20:07.820
Not just here, but in every
community in this country.

00:20:07.820 --> 00:20:12.010
The NEA sends grants to
every congressional district

00:20:12.010 --> 00:20:13.310
in the nation.

00:20:13.310 --> 00:20:16.750
It's imperative to
fight for its survival.

00:20:16.750 --> 00:20:20.510
Thank you and please
enjoy the Shift Festival.

