00:23:12.660 --> 00:23:14.290
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson:
Good morning.

00:23:14.290 --> 00:23:20.650
[Laughs] I think for me it
goes back a little bit longer

00:23:20.650 --> 00:23:23.530
than just the past ten years.

00:23:23.530 --> 00:23:27.450
I think it's really important to
understand that the orchestras

00:23:27.450 --> 00:23:32.740
that we enjoy today were built
around a social mission back --

00:23:32.740 --> 00:23:37.240
gosh, starting in the
1880's, especially going

00:23:37.240 --> 00:23:40.780
into the beginning
of the next century.

00:23:40.780 --> 00:23:44.060
These were immigrants that
were coming to America.

00:23:44.060 --> 00:23:46.390
They were setting
up new communities.

00:23:46.390 --> 00:23:50.130
If it was Minneapolis or Chicago
or Boston or Philly or Baltimore

00:23:50.130 --> 00:23:54.830
or New York or Cincinnati or
Cleveland, what was important

00:23:54.830 --> 00:23:57.320
to keep those communities
together was their culture

00:23:57.320 --> 00:23:58.620
and their identity.

00:23:58.620 --> 00:23:59.920
And a lot of that revolved

00:23:59.920 --> 00:24:01.530
around classical
music and orchestras.

00:24:01.530 --> 00:24:04.150
The musicians played an
important role in making sure

00:24:04.150 --> 00:24:06.440
that community music
schools were set up,

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:08.170
that orchestras were established

00:24:08.170 --> 00:24:10.820
and that they were actually
working hand-in-hand.

00:24:10.820 --> 00:24:12.770
Philadelphia's a
perfect example.

00:24:12.770 --> 00:24:14.840
1900, the orchestras form.

00:24:14.840 --> 00:24:17.620
1904, the Settlement
Music School.

00:24:17.620 --> 00:24:21.830
They were teaching kids in the
community for a nickel or less.

00:24:21.830 --> 00:24:24.130
And then they found out
20 years after that,

00:24:24.130 --> 00:24:25.570
some of the kids
were pretty good.

00:24:25.570 --> 00:24:27.320
So they created the
Curtis Institute of Music.

00:24:27.320 --> 00:24:29.520
And for the first four years,

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:32.450
tuition was $500 a
year, a lot of money.

00:24:32.450 --> 00:24:35.150
And they thought that was pretty
crazy because of course a lot

00:24:35.150 --> 00:24:38.290
of the families could
not afford to pay it.

00:24:38.290 --> 00:24:39.700
So the woman who
founded the school,

00:24:39.700 --> 00:24:42.170
who also founded the Settlement
Music School and also helped

00:24:42.170 --> 00:24:46.240
to found the Philly Orchestra,
put down $12 million in 1928

00:24:46.240 --> 00:24:49.010
to make sure that there
was a tuition-free policy.

00:24:49.010 --> 00:24:53.020
And there is this connection
between the musicians

00:24:53.020 --> 00:24:56.940
that played and taught and
mentored, and it was all

00:24:56.940 --> 00:25:00.440
around trying to in many ways
keep body and soul together.

00:25:00.440 --> 00:25:02.780
So all of that stuff
just blossomed.

00:25:02.780 --> 00:25:04.190
In the '60's it was wonderful

00:25:04.190 --> 00:25:07.270
because then you had Wallace
Foundation and Ford Foundation,

00:25:07.270 --> 00:25:08.570
a couple of others
that said, "You know,

00:25:08.570 --> 00:25:11.610
I think that these musicians and
the music that they're providing

00:25:11.610 --> 00:25:15.750
to the community should
be made more available."

00:25:15.750 --> 00:25:18.980
So they turned orchestras
into full-time gigs, 52 weeks.

00:25:18.980 --> 00:25:20.710
And there was a shift.

00:25:20.710 --> 00:25:24.290
And the money shifted
towards those musicians.

00:25:24.290 --> 00:25:25.590
Endowments were created.

00:25:25.590 --> 00:25:27.220
Orchestras were more healthy.

00:25:27.220 --> 00:25:29.930
But the public, they
were picking up the cost

00:25:29.930 --> 00:25:31.600
and making sure that
kids had access

00:25:31.600 --> 00:25:33.130
to music in all the schools.

00:25:33.130 --> 00:25:36.320
And that worked,
until the early '80's.

00:25:36.320 --> 00:25:38.050
And of course that
infrastructure

00:25:38.050 --> 00:25:41.320
in the public schools
started to fall apart

00:25:41.320 --> 00:25:43.760
to what we are now experiencing.

00:25:43.760 --> 00:25:49.260
And it's at a point where
there's not enough public money,

00:25:49.260 --> 00:25:51.990
but sure these [inaudible]
have a bunch.

00:25:51.990 --> 00:25:53.720
And that's where the money is.

00:25:53.720 --> 00:25:57.020
And I work with organizations
where we're trying

00:25:57.020 --> 00:25:59.270
to I think collectively among
several of the boards that I'm

00:25:59.270 --> 00:26:01.400
on -- we're trying to raise
half a billion dollars

00:26:01.400 --> 00:26:02.700
for endowments.

00:26:02.700 --> 00:26:05.830
Now not to say that the
orchestras don't deserve them,

00:26:05.830 --> 00:26:08.900
and they do, but when we
watch the infrastructure

00:26:08.900 --> 00:26:11.410
for music falling
apart, knowing that used

00:26:11.410 --> 00:26:13.640
to be a really strong
connection,

00:26:13.640 --> 00:26:16.600
and it was important, then

00:26:16.600 --> 00:26:19.580
of course what will
the shift be now?

00:26:19.580 --> 00:26:24.990
So you know, I just think
that half a billion dollars

00:26:24.990 --> 00:26:29.240
in Philadelphia for
example, that organizations

00:26:29.240 --> 00:26:33.130
between the orchestra and Curtis
-- half a billion that they need

00:26:33.130 --> 00:26:37.500
for their endowments -- I think
half a billion invested in youth

00:26:37.500 --> 00:26:40.770
in the city would
definitely go a long way

00:26:40.770 --> 00:26:43.390
with of course making
classical music

00:26:43.390 --> 00:26:45.050
and orchestras much
more relevant.

00:26:45.050 --> 00:26:48.330
I think it would also open
up, and as we have found

00:26:48.330 --> 00:26:51.660
in even the money that we
have raised, a vast majority

00:26:51.660 --> 00:26:53.500
of that money comes
from education

00:26:53.500 --> 00:26:58.120
and social service
private funders that want

00:26:58.120 --> 00:26:59.770
to see something different.

00:26:59.770 --> 00:27:01.420
There's more money there.

00:27:01.420 --> 00:27:06.200
So when I look at the
Shift, I hope that the shift

00:27:06.200 --> 00:27:08.700
that we make is that we
can no longer divorce those

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:11.900
who play music and those
who teach the music.

00:27:11.900 --> 00:27:14.880
Because I think both of those
actually working together is

00:27:14.880 --> 00:27:18.270
exactly the infrastructure and
foundation that we really need

00:27:18.270 --> 00:27:22.170
to build and grow professional
orchestras in the country.

