And I want to come back
to some of the themes

00:27:24.770 --> 00:27:26.720
and give Tom a chance
to weight in too.

00:27:26.720 --> 00:27:28.400
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: There
was a time in my life

00:27:28.400 --> 00:27:32.870
when I was really irritated
by the word relevance.

00:27:32.870 --> 00:27:35.940
Because I believed
-- and to your point,

00:27:35.940 --> 00:27:39.650
it really goes back further
than the last ten years.

00:27:39.650 --> 00:27:43.140
We came with the word
relevant in our industry

00:27:43.140 --> 00:27:45.880
because we were losing traction.

00:27:45.880 --> 00:27:49.670
And we were indeed losing
traction of funders as well,

00:27:49.670 --> 00:27:53.180
but we were losing
interest in the population.

00:27:53.180 --> 00:27:58.170
And so we had to come up with
a way to justify our existence,

00:27:58.170 --> 00:28:01.260
and so we started using
this word relevant.

00:28:01.260 --> 00:28:02.960
But I'm not convinced

00:28:02.960 --> 00:28:06.150
that across the board we
were committed to relevance.

00:28:06.150 --> 00:28:12.020
I thought maybe a different
word would have been engagement

00:28:12.020 --> 00:28:14.240
or deeper connection.

00:28:14.240 --> 00:28:19.750
I've wanted to be a conductor
since I was eight years old.

00:28:19.750 --> 00:28:25.000
And I first heard an orchestra
when I was eight years old.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:27.270
And I was born to a
single mother on welfare,

00:28:27.270 --> 00:28:29.090
living in a housing project.

00:28:29.090 --> 00:28:33.100
And when I talk to funders
and leaders in communities

00:28:33.100 --> 00:28:36.040
about this, I say that music
literally saved my life.

00:28:36.040 --> 00:28:40.150
And so I come at music from
a different perspective.

00:28:40.150 --> 00:28:44.330
If I believe that it is
life-affirming and life altering

00:28:44.330 --> 00:28:48.320
in my case as it surely
is, why would I want

00:28:48.320 --> 00:28:50.970
to leave anyone behind
in a community?

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:54.100
I'm not worried about Mozart's
ability to take care of himself,

00:28:54.100 --> 00:28:56.350
or Beethoven's ability
to take care of himself.

00:28:56.350 --> 00:28:59.440
There's a reason why we still
listen to that music today.

00:28:59.440 --> 00:29:02.470
What I was worried about was
how we get that music to people

00:29:02.470 --> 00:29:06.260
so that it can be life-altering
and life-affirming.

00:29:06.260 --> 00:29:09.200
And so I have always
believed that relevance had

00:29:09.200 --> 00:29:14.570
to be earnest, and that meant
that we had to find ourselves

00:29:14.570 --> 00:29:16.490
in places other than
a concert hall.

00:29:16.490 --> 00:29:18.700
And we had to be okay with that.

00:29:18.700 --> 00:29:20.790
And we had to be
comfortable with that.

00:29:20.790 --> 00:29:23.330
Because if you can't get past
need, you'll never believe

00:29:23.330 --> 00:29:26.100
that this music is as
transformative as it is.

00:29:26.100 --> 00:29:32.520
And so I would like to think
that this idea of Shift means

00:29:32.520 --> 00:29:37.170
that orchestras all across
this nation are really figuring

00:29:37.170 --> 00:29:41.910
out that if this music is
as life-changing as it is,

00:29:41.910 --> 00:29:46.570
it is incumbent upon us to
get it to as many entities

00:29:46.570 --> 00:29:48.920
and people groups as possible.

00:29:48.920 --> 00:29:53.350
I often say that I try to
take my music more seriously

00:29:53.350 --> 00:29:54.730
than I take myself.

00:29:54.730 --> 00:29:56.830
So I don't mind if I'm
sitting in a community center

00:29:56.830 --> 00:30:00.410
at the Omaha Housing Authority
with kazoos and a room full

00:30:00.410 --> 00:30:02.460
of people who don't
have any options.

00:30:02.460 --> 00:30:07.040
But now all of a sudden, here
is one that they do have.

00:30:07.040 --> 00:30:09.590
And it's the only one
that we have to offer,

00:30:09.590 --> 00:30:10.890
but it's the best one.

00:30:10.890 --> 00:30:12.190
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Rhona,

00:30:12.190 --> 00:30:14.540
is there something
you'd like to add?

00:30:14.540 --> 00:30:15.840
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
Well, I know that as part

00:30:15.840 --> 00:30:17.370
of the commission,
that's our goal,

00:30:17.370 --> 00:30:19.460
is to reach out into
the communities,

00:30:19.460 --> 00:30:22.600
especially in DC
east of the river

00:30:22.600 --> 00:30:25.280
which is the underserved
communities in DC.

00:30:25.280 --> 00:30:28.460
And as a board member,
that's what we do.

00:30:28.460 --> 00:30:33.830
We bring music, art,
theater across the river.

00:30:33.830 --> 00:30:35.550
And I agree with
you wholeheartedly.

00:30:35.550 --> 00:30:39.630
I think if you don't reach out
into the community and connect,

00:30:39.630 --> 00:30:46.150
and connect, not just reach out,
that music endeavors will fail.

00:30:46.150 --> 00:30:47.450
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Yeah.

00:30:47.450 --> 00:30:48.900
I think that part of it was --

00:30:48.900 --> 00:30:53.710
I gave a speech to MOLA which
is the Major Orchestra Libraries

00:30:53.710 --> 00:30:55.400
Association, because
my librarian

00:30:55.400 --> 00:30:56.850
in Omaha hosted it one year.

00:30:56.850 --> 00:30:59.710
And it was called No
Excuses Necessary.

00:30:59.710 --> 00:31:03.910
And what I did just for fun
was I played three recordings.

00:31:03.910 --> 00:31:12.540
One was Tchaikovsky and
another was something by Grieg.

00:31:12.540 --> 00:31:15.840
And when I played
those excerpts,

00:31:15.840 --> 00:31:18.300
you could see all the
librarians in the room

00:31:18.300 --> 00:31:20.860
and they were going, "Oh yeah."

00:31:20.860 --> 00:31:23.000
And then I played the last

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:26.020
of Bernstein's Three
Dances from on the Town.

00:31:26.020 --> 00:31:28.020
Ba-ba-ba-ba-de-ba-da-ba-do-da.

00:31:28.020 --> 00:31:31.030
And you could see them
all kind of looking

00:31:31.030 --> 00:31:32.330
at each other and smiling.

00:31:32.330 --> 00:31:33.630
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield:
Guilty pleasure.

00:31:33.630 --> 00:31:35.000
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: And
my point was, you know,

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:37.390
the Tchaikovsky is
actually a drinking song.

00:31:37.390 --> 00:31:40.430
"I found a coin,
I want a drink."

00:31:40.430 --> 00:31:43.050
Forgive me, I don't know
what the exact title is.

00:31:43.050 --> 00:31:45.160
I Have a Coin, I Want a Drink.

00:31:45.160 --> 00:31:50.050
Those composers like
Tchaikovsky and Beethoven --

00:31:50.050 --> 00:31:53.890
not so much Beethoven,
but Mozart for sure,

00:31:53.890 --> 00:31:55.190
Marlor for sure --

00:31:55.190 --> 00:31:56.900
they understood that if
their music was going

00:31:56.900 --> 00:32:00.400
to have a mass appeal
to the general public,

00:32:00.400 --> 00:32:01.860
it had to relate to them.

00:32:01.860 --> 00:32:04.060
And that's why we have
Klesber and Marlor

00:32:04.060 --> 00:32:05.360
and that's why we
have folk music

00:32:05.360 --> 00:32:10.310
and the whole nationalistic
sort of school of composition.

00:32:10.310 --> 00:32:15.120
But we in America almost feel
as if we have to apologize

00:32:15.120 --> 00:32:17.770
when Americanism finds
itself in our music.

00:32:17.770 --> 00:32:21.400
We come up with words like,
"It's a synthesis of jazz."

00:32:21.400 --> 00:32:23.900
You know, so that it
sounds intellectual.

00:32:23.900 --> 00:32:27.660
And I'm thinking, "Why should
we apologize for that?"

00:32:27.660 --> 00:32:31.510
Why? Because we have always
believed that we operate

00:32:31.510 --> 00:32:34.490
in basically a western
European tradition.

00:32:34.490 --> 00:32:37.030
And we believe that if
we don't live our lives,

00:32:37.030 --> 00:32:41.660
speak our language and carry
our attitudes in that tradition,

00:32:41.660 --> 00:32:44.490
that people aren't going
to take us seriously.

00:32:44.490 --> 00:32:45.790
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Right.

00:32:45.790 --> 00:32:47.090
And you've hit on so many
interesting things here.

00:32:47.090 --> 00:32:49.970
The first I want to
touch upon is this shift

00:32:49.970 --> 00:32:55.090
from the let's call it
relevance from the purview

00:32:55.090 --> 00:32:57.430
of one department, the
education community outreach

00:32:57.430 --> 00:32:58.730
is responsible.

00:32:58.730 --> 00:33:00.030
And then the rest of
the orchestra does this

00:33:00.030 --> 00:33:04.840
to actually shifting the
institutional DNA to be one

00:33:04.840 --> 00:33:08.900
that is much more porous and
has that sense of excitement

00:33:08.900 --> 00:33:11.020
from the top, from the
directors, the founders,

00:33:11.020 --> 00:33:16.630
leaders, to feel and to be
very present with the community

00:33:16.630 --> 00:33:19.280
and in the community and
to have the community feel

00:33:19.280 --> 00:33:20.580
as if it's monolithic.

00:33:20.580 --> 00:33:21.880
But to have members

00:33:21.880 --> 00:33:24.960
of the community feel very
part of the orchestra.

00:33:24.960 --> 00:33:30.630
And it's not simply to secure
that grant or to check a box.

00:33:30.630 --> 00:33:33.660
It's actually to
fundamentally rearrange the DNA

00:33:33.660 --> 00:33:37.560
of an orchestra to be a
community, a living, breathing,

00:33:37.560 --> 00:33:39.860
evolving community institution.

00:33:39.860 --> 00:33:41.540
So that's a very
big shift as well.

00:33:41.540 --> 00:33:45.210
Ironically, in speaking
with European orchestras

00:33:45.210 --> 00:33:46.510
which are the ones

00:33:46.510 --> 00:33:50.150
that theoretically
American orchestras have

00:33:50.150 --> 00:33:54.210
in the past tried to emulate,
some of the most adventuresome,

00:33:54.210 --> 00:33:56.690
well-resourced education
programs

00:33:56.690 --> 00:34:00.300
and community-based
programs, are on display

00:34:00.300 --> 00:34:01.680
with European orchestras.

00:34:01.680 --> 00:34:04.660
So as American orchestras,
our building that sense

00:34:04.660 --> 00:34:08.410
of porousness -- so many
European orchestras have been

00:34:08.410 --> 00:34:11.910
in the vanguard of that through
very imaginative collaborations.

00:34:11.910 --> 00:34:15.060
I would love it if both of
you would speak about some

00:34:15.060 --> 00:34:19.050
of the things that have
excited you most musically

00:34:19.050 --> 00:34:23.440
when you have really been at
sort of the most open, engaging,

00:34:23.440 --> 00:34:29.670
porous, as music directors, as
creative innovators yourselves.

00:34:29.670 --> 00:34:33.690
What are examples of moments
when that's come together

00:34:33.690 --> 00:34:35.820
and just been so satisfying?

00:34:35.820 --> 00:34:38.630
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson: Oh wow,
we shared one in Detroit.

00:34:38.630 --> 00:34:40.270
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield:
Okay, tell us.

00:34:40.270 --> 00:34:41.570
Perfect.

00:34:41.570 --> 00:34:42.870
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson:
This last month?

00:34:42.870 --> 00:34:44.170
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: I think so.

00:34:44.170 --> 00:34:45.470
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson: Right.

00:34:45.470 --> 00:34:46.770
Wow, yeah, last month.

00:34:46.770 --> 00:34:50.240
This was at the SINCS
Conference and Competition.

00:34:50.240 --> 00:34:53.500
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield:
Explain what SINCS is.

00:34:53.500 --> 00:34:57.730
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson: It's a
20-year-old organization founded

00:34:57.730 --> 00:35:04.260
by Aaron Dorkin who is now
the dean of the music school,

00:35:04.260 --> 00:35:06.360
art school at University
of Michigan.

00:35:06.360 --> 00:35:10.000
But they've been focused over
the past 20 years in really kind

00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:14.300
of pushing the diversity
and inclusion conversation

00:35:14.300 --> 00:35:16.390
in the field of classical music.

00:35:16.390 --> 00:35:19.400
So a lot of success that they
have seen over that amount

00:35:19.400 --> 00:35:23.450
of time, but they host
every year a competition

00:35:23.450 --> 00:35:27.890
for string players, both
pretty much high school

00:35:27.890 --> 00:35:29.610
and college age students.

00:35:29.610 --> 00:35:35.680
And they also run side by side a
conference called SINCS Connect.

00:35:35.680 --> 00:35:40.570
And at the competition, after
the competitors were there,

00:35:40.570 --> 00:35:45.770
we performed a piece by
Gerald Thomson, The Last Words

00:35:45.770 --> 00:35:49.880
of the Unarmed, which literally
took the last words of people

00:35:49.880 --> 00:35:52.900
like Trayvon Martin,
Eric Garner.

00:35:52.900 --> 00:35:56.930
But there were I believe seven
people that were highlighted.

00:35:56.930 --> 00:36:01.730
But it literally took the last
two or three words and put it

00:36:01.730 --> 00:36:05.340
into a really, really
powerful 15-minute piece.

00:36:05.340 --> 00:36:10.380
And I will say it was the most
powerful experience I've ever

00:36:10.380 --> 00:36:11.710
had on a stage.

00:36:11.710 --> 00:36:15.900
We all have been around
the conversations.

00:36:15.900 --> 00:36:17.410
We've seen everything
on the news.

00:36:17.410 --> 00:36:19.790
We've heard all the
arguments from all sides.

00:36:19.790 --> 00:36:23.530
But to have that
artistic display --

00:36:23.530 --> 00:36:25.720
I'll never forget
the first rehearsal.

00:36:25.720 --> 00:36:32.470
I was playing the
trumpet in the orchestra.

00:36:32.470 --> 00:36:36.190
But sitting there,
I mean it was tough.

00:36:36.190 --> 00:36:38.080
I mean, that first
rehearsal for everybody

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:41.310
in the orchestra was really
difficult to get through.

00:36:41.310 --> 00:36:44.350
And I believe the
connection that we made

00:36:44.350 --> 00:36:46.980
at that performance was
something I've never felt,

00:36:46.980 --> 00:36:48.280
I've never seen.

00:36:48.280 --> 00:36:53.100
And I just think when something
is -- to not use relevant,

00:36:53.100 --> 00:36:56.980
but something that is that
engaging, that puts a spotlight

00:36:56.980 --> 00:37:00.520
on a really big problem that
we're having and that we've done

00:37:00.520 --> 00:37:02.810
that through the
medium of an orchestra,

00:37:02.810 --> 00:37:06.030
I believe that we made a
really powerful connection

00:37:06.030 --> 00:37:08.260
that I think a lot of people
that were in that hall

00:37:08.260 --> 00:37:12.390
that day will be
able to build upon.

00:37:12.390 --> 00:37:14.520
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: There
are several that I think of,

00:37:14.520 --> 00:37:19.330
but we have in Omaha what
we call community partners,

00:37:19.330 --> 00:37:23.080
and they range anywhere
from Nebraska Medical Center

00:37:23.080 --> 00:37:25.870
to Girls, Inc., the
Omaha Housing Authority.

00:37:25.870 --> 00:37:27.610
So there are a lot
of things that we do

00:37:27.610 --> 00:37:30.850
that are less attached to a
performance and more attached

00:37:30.850 --> 00:37:36.450
to either delivering music or
delivering access to music.

00:37:36.450 --> 00:37:39.290
But for me, I still
have to go back

00:37:39.290 --> 00:37:43.290
to this Omaha Housing Authority
example where we send musicians

00:37:43.290 --> 00:37:46.390
out -- there's a retirement
center that exists there,

00:37:46.390 --> 00:37:50.280
and these are indeed people
who have no options left.

00:37:50.280 --> 00:37:55.600
And most are elderly,
but some are not.

00:37:55.600 --> 00:37:57.840
This is just where they land.

00:37:57.840 --> 00:38:01.230
And so we send musicians
out on a regular basis

00:38:01.230 --> 00:38:04.360
and our education person asked
if I would be willing to go out.

00:38:04.360 --> 00:38:06.750
I said, "Yeah, but
let's do something fun."

00:38:06.750 --> 00:38:10.320
And we literally
brought in kazoos.

00:38:10.320 --> 00:38:11.780
I'm not kidding.

00:38:11.780 --> 00:38:17.300
And my job was to conduct
this now kazoo orchestra.

00:38:17.300 --> 00:38:21.090
And I must say that we
spent more time laughing

00:38:21.090 --> 00:38:26.680
because there was nothing more
ridiculous than that scene.

00:38:26.680 --> 00:38:31.380
But what really sort of blessed
my heart was when they got

00:38:31.380 --> 00:38:33.370
to come to my concert.

00:38:33.370 --> 00:38:37.060
Now in Omaha we have now
-- it's ten years old,

00:38:37.060 --> 00:38:42.140
but at the time it was newer
-- $100 million concert hall.

00:38:42.140 --> 00:38:45.780
And these people didn't
even know where it was,

00:38:45.780 --> 00:38:47.840
let alone walk in the building.

00:38:47.840 --> 00:38:50.260
And so not only were
they at the concert,

00:38:50.260 --> 00:38:52.090
but then we closed
the hall afterwards

00:38:52.090 --> 00:38:56.190
and we spent time together
in the room in the hall.

00:38:56.190 --> 00:39:02.630
And what was so poetic was that
here was this group of people

00:39:02.630 --> 00:39:06.290
with no predisposition
to this music.

00:39:06.290 --> 00:39:09.740
All of a sudden,
this room was theirs

00:39:09.740 --> 00:39:13.000
and this orchestra was theirs,
and this conductor was theirs.

00:39:13.000 --> 00:39:15.720
And in fact, one
of the ladies said,

00:39:15.720 --> 00:39:18.010
"I feel as if this is all ours."

00:39:18.010 --> 00:39:19.470
I mean, she literally said that.

00:39:19.470 --> 00:39:24.160
And you know, are they going
to buy a ticket down the road?

00:39:24.160 --> 00:39:25.460
No, they're not.

00:39:25.460 --> 00:39:26.760
But we have done our job

00:39:26.760 --> 00:39:29.110
in making sure that
they understand.

00:39:29.110 --> 00:39:32.090
I mean, one of the great gifts
of music is that it tells us

00:39:32.090 --> 00:39:34.300
that we were built for something
greater than the despair

00:39:34.300 --> 00:39:37.120
that we probably experience
on a regular basis.

00:39:37.120 --> 00:39:38.650
And this was one
of those moments

00:39:38.650 --> 00:39:40.900
when they could say,
"You know what?

00:39:40.900 --> 00:39:42.930
I was made for something
better than this."

00:39:42.930 --> 00:39:47.100
So for me that was my
best memory to date.

00:39:47.100 --> 00:39:49.530
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Yeah, I
mean two very profound moments

00:39:49.530 --> 00:39:52.840
around music and shared space.

00:39:52.840 --> 00:39:56.200
And through the eloquence
of kazoo.

00:39:56.200 --> 00:39:59.090
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Or some
maybe even more profound, right.

00:39:59.090 --> 00:40:00.390
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Or
a commissioned work,

00:40:00.390 --> 00:40:04.160
but in a very different
context, different repertoire,

00:40:04.160 --> 00:40:07.150
but with a sense of
vision and leadership

00:40:07.150 --> 00:40:09.670
that helped define that.

00:40:09.670 --> 00:40:13.800
And how well equipped are
orchestras to initiate

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:18.830
that conversation or
comfortable, confident reaching

00:40:18.830 --> 00:40:22.770
out to partners who are perhaps
better equipped than they are?

00:40:22.770 --> 00:40:29.660
Because not every institution
has a smooth transition

00:40:29.660 --> 00:40:33.050
to new leadership,
to partnerships.

00:40:33.050 --> 00:40:36.510
Especially if an orchestra
is a dominant institution

00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:39.240
in a community, sometimes
the messiness

00:40:39.240 --> 00:40:43.180
of partnership can
be unfamiliar.

00:40:43.180 --> 00:40:45.760
So how do orchestras
embrace that?

00:40:45.760 --> 00:40:49.780
And you've created an orchestra
and we would love these sort

00:40:49.780 --> 00:40:52.370
of different perspectives
as you're starting up

00:40:52.370 --> 00:40:57.900
and asserting a vision and
a presence and a mission.

00:40:57.900 --> 00:40:59.200
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Sure.

00:40:59.200 --> 00:41:01.930
Yeah, I think there's
a lot of fear.

00:41:01.930 --> 00:41:05.300
I mean, I remember when we
started, people were like,

00:41:05.300 --> 00:41:06.600
"Are kids going to sign up?

00:41:06.600 --> 00:41:08.130
Are they going to show up?

00:41:08.130 --> 00:41:10.970
Are they going to drop
out in big numbers?

00:41:10.970 --> 00:41:14.770
Why would they want to in our
program spend three hours every

00:41:14.770 --> 00:41:18.620
day after school learning music,
especially classical music?"

00:41:18.620 --> 00:41:25.540
And the same thing goes for our
I think partnerships all around.

00:41:25.540 --> 00:41:29.340
For example, what the
Philly orchestra does is

00:41:29.340 --> 00:41:32.420
that they present
groups from the community

00:41:32.420 --> 00:41:35.480
in the lobby before
performances.

00:41:35.480 --> 00:41:38.080
And there was some interest
from Simon Rattle to work

00:41:38.080 --> 00:41:39.830
with our kids five years ago,

00:41:39.830 --> 00:41:42.860
four and five years ago
when he was in town.

00:41:42.860 --> 00:41:45.890
And instead of having him
come up to the school,

00:41:45.890 --> 00:41:48.820
he agreed to put the
kids on the stage right

00:41:48.820 --> 00:41:50.930
at the beginning of the concert.

00:41:50.930 --> 00:41:53.940
The orchestra wasn't
going to play an overture,

00:41:53.940 --> 00:41:55.780
but the kids were going to play.

00:41:55.780 --> 00:41:59.050
And it was a really scary thing
to go back and forth between,

00:41:59.050 --> 00:42:01.600
"Should they be in the lobby or
should they be on the stage?"

00:42:01.600 --> 00:42:06.030
The patrons did not pay to
hear students from west Philly

00:42:06.030 --> 00:42:08.280
that had only been
playing a year and a half.

00:42:08.280 --> 00:42:10.850
What would the union do?

00:42:10.850 --> 00:42:13.030
And of course the musicians
have to warm up on the stage

00:42:13.030 --> 00:42:14.480
for a certain period of time.

00:42:14.480 --> 00:42:16.790
And then what happens
if there's overtime?

00:42:16.790 --> 00:42:19.300
And there were all
these questions.

00:42:19.300 --> 00:42:21.830
But I mean, it was
wrapped in a lot of fear.

00:42:21.830 --> 00:42:25.060
Like how would the
kids handle that?

00:42:25.060 --> 00:42:26.900
How would the audience
handle that?

00:42:26.900 --> 00:42:28.720
Would it be uncomfortable?

00:42:28.720 --> 00:42:31.820
Not to say the kids were
playing perfectly in tune.

00:42:31.820 --> 00:42:33.460
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: All the
negatives of fear, yeah.

00:42:33.460 --> 00:42:34.760
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Right.

00:42:34.760 --> 00:42:36.060
And what ended up happening is

00:42:36.060 --> 00:42:37.970
that actually it was a
very magical experience.

00:42:37.970 --> 00:42:39.750
We even talked about
concert tickets.

00:42:39.750 --> 00:42:41.910
The orchestra makes
a lot of money

00:42:41.910 --> 00:42:43.960
when Simon Rattle's in town.

00:42:43.960 --> 00:42:49.620
But parents bought tickets at
$90, $130 to be in the room.

00:42:49.620 --> 00:42:52.080
When that sold out, we
opened up an overflow room.

00:42:52.080 --> 00:42:54.920
We set up a TV so that more
families could come in,

00:42:54.920 --> 00:42:57.290
and that room was packed.

00:42:57.290 --> 00:42:59.580
And in many ways there
was this connection

00:42:59.580 --> 00:43:03.550
between the parents see
how hard their kids work.

00:43:03.550 --> 00:43:04.850
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Yeah.

00:43:04.850 --> 00:43:06.450
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: And of
course being able to now connect

00:43:06.450 --> 00:43:08.800
that to a professional
orchestra and put that work

00:43:08.800 --> 00:43:11.650
into perspective of what's
going on that's powerful.

00:43:11.650 --> 00:43:16.990
The other part of it, to be
completely honest and candid,

00:43:16.990 --> 00:43:22.530
there are not many opportunities
where a room full of people

00:43:22.530 --> 00:43:28.650
who typically look like the
typical white audience in a city

00:43:28.650 --> 00:43:31.760
like Philadelphia are ever on
their feet clapping for a group

00:43:31.760 --> 00:43:34.190
of kids in west Philly.

00:43:34.190 --> 00:43:35.490
Honestly.

00:43:35.490 --> 00:43:36.790
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Yep.

00:43:36.790 --> 00:43:38.090
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: And
to see that connection

00:43:38.090 --> 00:43:39.390
between kids standing up,
accepting that applause

00:43:39.390 --> 00:43:41.680
at the end, saying, "They're
all clapping for me,"

00:43:41.680 --> 00:43:45.180
and watching the parents
feel, "They're all clapping

00:43:45.180 --> 00:43:48.420
for my kid," you know, I mean
that was a really powerful bond

00:43:48.420 --> 00:43:51.760
that was connected and I think
has allowed our relationship

00:43:51.760 --> 00:43:53.060
and partnership with
the orchestra

00:43:53.060 --> 00:43:54.360
and many others to flourish.

00:43:54.360 --> 00:43:59.090
So a lot of it is we also both
organizations received big

00:43:59.090 --> 00:44:02.220
donations after that.

00:44:02.220 --> 00:44:03.520
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Yes.

00:44:03.520 --> 00:44:04.820
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins:
In the seven figures.

00:44:04.820 --> 00:44:07.470
And it just was a
good thing to do.

00:44:07.470 --> 00:44:09.420
It was a great experience.

00:44:09.420 --> 00:44:10.850
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: We've
done some of that here too

00:44:10.850 --> 00:44:13.080
at Washington Performing Arts.

00:44:13.080 --> 00:44:17.300
We don't have the ensemble of
an orchestra on a regular basis,

00:44:17.300 --> 00:44:18.600
but when there's an opportunity

00:44:18.600 --> 00:44:23.260
to showcase either our
gospel choirs or some

00:44:23.260 --> 00:44:26.520
of the young performers in our
education programs, we do it

00:44:26.520 --> 00:44:28.210
and we do think about that.

00:44:28.210 --> 00:44:30.820
Because we'll get
the nasty-gram --

00:44:30.820 --> 00:44:34.820
I will usually get the
nasty-gram from someone who paid

00:44:34.820 --> 00:44:36.120
for one thing, they got another.

00:44:36.120 --> 00:44:38.320
And my response is
always, "You know what,

00:44:38.320 --> 00:44:40.080
I'm so glad that you
came to the performance

00:44:40.080 --> 00:44:43.620
and had the opportunity to
hear some of the young artists

00:44:43.620 --> 00:44:46.590
who are working towards
perhaps being in the audience

00:44:46.590 --> 00:44:48.030
or onstage in the future.

00:44:48.030 --> 00:44:49.330
It's part of our mission."

00:44:49.330 --> 00:44:53.090
If there has been a residency
activity in the community,

00:44:53.090 --> 00:44:56.120
I speak about it from the
stage every single time

00:44:56.120 --> 00:44:59.240
because I think people
understand the finished product

00:44:59.240 --> 00:45:01.290
because they come and
the lights and the stands

00:45:01.290 --> 00:45:02.590
and everything is set.

00:45:02.590 --> 00:45:05.060
They don't necessarily
understand the granularity

00:45:05.060 --> 00:45:06.360
of the process.

00:45:06.360 --> 00:45:10.310
They don't understand or they're
not even aware of the role

00:45:10.310 --> 00:45:14.470
of the teachers in the classroom
playing side-by-side, the buses,

00:45:14.470 --> 00:45:17.300
the parents driving,
the catering,

00:45:17.300 --> 00:45:19.880
the kids taking time off
from studying, you know,

00:45:19.880 --> 00:45:22.410
coming out early in the
morning, staying late at night.

00:45:22.410 --> 00:45:25.630
There's a process and
in some ways I worry

00:45:25.630 --> 00:45:29.470
that we have orchestrated such
a polished finished product

00:45:29.470 --> 00:45:33.040
that we've done it at
our own disservice.

00:45:33.040 --> 00:45:37.780
Because it's hard
to make the urgency

00:45:37.780 --> 00:45:41.640
of supporting the finished
product really articulate

00:45:41.640 --> 00:45:44.470
without showing the
process where the real time

00:45:44.470 --> 00:45:47.250
and cost and investment are.

00:45:47.250 --> 00:45:50.390
And so I think with the question
of how all of this is going

00:45:50.390 --> 00:45:54.300
to happen, we simply have
to say it is going to happen

00:45:54.300 --> 00:45:56.050
and it's going to be awesome.

00:45:56.050 --> 00:45:59.670
And you're going to be really
sad that you missed it.

00:45:59.670 --> 00:46:01.270
And it's that sort
of confidence.

00:46:01.270 --> 00:46:05.530
There will be cranky people,
people and organizations

00:46:05.530 --> 00:46:07.230
that are insecure about it.

00:46:07.230 --> 00:46:10.270
But it's the leaders of the
organizations who have to take

00:46:10.270 --> 00:46:13.030
that deep breath and do it.

00:46:13.030 --> 00:46:15.450
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: We
at the Hollywood Bowl,

00:46:15.450 --> 00:46:19.780
we on a regular basis are
joined by YOLA, Youth Orchestra

00:46:19.780 --> 00:46:21.200
of Los Angeles, on stage.

00:46:21.200 --> 00:46:22.500
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Yes.

00:46:22.500 --> 00:46:25.340
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: I have had
them several times playing

00:46:25.340 --> 00:46:28.950
by themselves and also
playing with the orchestra.

00:46:28.950 --> 00:46:31.980
And we spoke in our
sort of pre-meeting,

00:46:31.980 --> 00:46:34.320
we talked about this a little
bit, about how important it is

00:46:34.320 --> 00:46:38.390
for us to give words to people
who are not in our business,

00:46:38.390 --> 00:46:39.830
because they don't
know our language.

00:46:39.830 --> 00:46:41.550
They're not supposed
to know our language.

00:46:41.550 --> 00:46:42.850
We shouldn't expect them to

00:46:42.850 --> 00:46:45.110
and we shouldn't feel
bad that they don't.

00:46:45.110 --> 00:46:46.410
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Yes.

00:46:46.410 --> 00:46:47.710
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: It is our
job to teach them our words.

00:46:47.710 --> 00:46:52.640
And I will often say to the
audience, to the audience,

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:57.230
when they applaud for those
kids, how grateful I am

00:46:57.230 --> 00:46:59.480
that they took the time
to say to these kids,

00:46:59.480 --> 00:47:01.040
"We are surrounding you.

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:03.530
We believe in you and we want
nothing but the best for you."

00:47:03.530 --> 00:47:07.940
And at that moment the audience
has nothing better to do

00:47:07.940 --> 00:47:09.780
than to take that
responsibility.

00:47:09.780 --> 00:47:12.030
And they sit up a little
taller in their seats and go,

00:47:12.030 --> 00:47:13.330
"Oh yeah, that's right.

00:47:13.330 --> 00:47:14.630
That's what we're doing."

00:47:14.630 --> 00:47:15.930
Therefore it is now
important to them

00:47:15.930 --> 00:47:18.000
and now they understand
why YOLA is there.

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:19.300
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Right.

00:47:19.300 --> 00:47:20.600
And consistently.

00:47:20.600 --> 00:47:21.900
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Right.

00:47:21.900 --> 00:47:23.200
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: It's
not just a one-off.

00:47:23.200 --> 00:47:24.500
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Right.

00:47:24.500 --> 00:47:25.800
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: It
becomes a regular diet

00:47:25.800 --> 00:47:27.100
so that it's integral
to the organization.

00:47:27.100 --> 00:47:28.400
Rhona, I would love if you
would speak about the role

00:47:28.400 --> 00:47:30.650
of the commission in supporting
so many important arts programs

00:47:30.650 --> 00:47:35.400
that reach schools and kids
and professional musicians.

00:47:35.400 --> 00:47:37.040
It's a very wide
range of support

00:47:37.040 --> 00:47:39.690
that the commission
provides to do much

00:47:39.690 --> 00:47:41.770
of this sort of activity.

00:47:41.770 --> 00:47:43.070
&gt;&gt; RWJ: We do.

00:47:43.070 --> 00:47:45.800
We started with a very small
budget in a couple of millions.

00:47:45.800 --> 00:47:47.780
And we went up to $18
million and we're hoping

00:47:47.780 --> 00:47:49.510
to go up to $25 million.

00:47:49.510 --> 00:47:51.510
Do you hear that?

00:47:51.510 --> 00:47:54.160
[ Laughter ]

00:47:54.160 --> 00:47:58.040
And we support a whole range
of different programming

00:47:58.040 --> 00:47:59.450
through our granting program.

00:47:59.450 --> 00:48:02.000
We're a granting organization.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:06.010
And what we do is we have
different categories of grants.

00:48:06.010 --> 00:48:07.770
We have startup organizations.

00:48:07.770 --> 00:48:10.270
We have large, we have a
heritage grant for those

00:48:10.270 --> 00:48:12.520
that have been in existence.

00:48:12.520 --> 00:48:17.530
And people apply and through
a panel grants are awarded

00:48:17.530 --> 00:48:18.830
throughout the city.

00:48:18.830 --> 00:48:21.950
And we have a separate program
as I mentioned before for east

00:48:21.950 --> 00:48:26.240
of the river to help empower
underserved communities.

00:48:26.240 --> 00:48:29.700
And you were mentioning
before about how you reach

00:48:29.700 --> 00:48:31.630
out into the community.

00:48:31.630 --> 00:48:38.370
And I want to take your point
of those of us, me included,

00:48:38.370 --> 00:48:43.740
who were not raised in a musical
background, you do have to reach

00:48:43.740 --> 00:48:46.580
out to the audience
and make them feel

00:48:46.580 --> 00:48:51.010
that they're important despite
the fact that they know nothing

00:48:51.010 --> 00:48:55.700
about the musical
instrument, the composition,

00:48:55.700 --> 00:48:57.240
the notes on the page.

00:48:57.240 --> 00:49:00.860
And with that I think comes
-- and I call it connection.

00:49:00.860 --> 00:49:02.190
I don't call it relevancy.

00:49:02.190 --> 00:49:06.700
I think it becomes a partnership
and I think it's important

00:49:06.700 --> 00:49:10.710
for audiences to
partner with orchestras

00:49:10.710 --> 00:49:14.170
and with musical events too.

00:49:14.170 --> 00:49:16.320
And that's what WPA
does so well.

00:49:16.320 --> 00:49:21.170
They go out into the
community and they reach

00:49:21.170 --> 00:49:24.350
to all different
types of populations,

00:49:24.350 --> 00:49:26.370
and they bring them
into their fold.

00:49:26.370 --> 00:49:28.110
Welcome them into their fold,

00:49:28.110 --> 00:49:31.600
and that to me is why
WPA is so successful.

00:49:31.600 --> 00:49:32.900
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Thank you.

00:49:32.900 --> 00:49:34.200
I mean one of the things --

00:49:34.200 --> 00:49:35.580
and this was the
mantra of our founder.

00:49:35.580 --> 00:49:36.970
And I was very pleased
to hear that the Library

00:49:36.970 --> 00:49:38.270
of Congress actually has some

00:49:38.270 --> 00:49:40.950
of Patrick Hayes' archives
on display outside.

00:49:40.950 --> 00:49:42.770
I'm looking forward
to seeing them myself.

00:49:42.770 --> 00:49:45.580
But Mr. Hayes is remembered
for intoning the phrase

00:49:45.580 --> 00:49:47.500
of "Everybody in, nobody out."

00:49:47.500 --> 00:49:49.840
And so when we began to
design this festival,

00:49:49.840 --> 00:49:53.690
we wanted the musicians
to be very visible

00:49:53.690 --> 00:49:55.740
and accessible to the audience.

00:49:55.740 --> 00:49:58.020
We wanted the price of
course to be accessible.

00:49:58.020 --> 00:49:59.600
We wanted to present
an experience

00:49:59.600 --> 00:50:00.900
that would be really different

00:50:00.900 --> 00:50:03.580
in the Kennedy center concert
hall and on our series.

00:50:03.580 --> 00:50:07.060
And all of that agency
went to the orchestras.

00:50:07.060 --> 00:50:09.240
But interestingly, as you'll
see throughout the week,

00:50:09.240 --> 00:50:11.900
you're going to find
musicians at the title basin,

00:50:11.900 --> 00:50:16.380
at the Hamilton, coaching at
schools, in galleries of art.

00:50:16.380 --> 00:50:22.320
The sense of finished product,
of accessibility is going

00:50:22.320 --> 00:50:25.020
to be teased out in
very different ways.

00:50:25.020 --> 00:50:27.190
And every orchestra
and the musicians

00:50:27.190 --> 00:50:28.620
who are making those commitments

00:50:28.620 --> 00:50:31.060
to doing the residency
events were really excited

00:50:31.060 --> 00:50:32.930
about doing it because
it's a way for them to get

00:50:32.930 --> 00:50:35.500
to know our public,
to get to know you,

00:50:35.500 --> 00:50:37.460
and to be very much themselves.

00:50:37.460 --> 00:50:40.070
This is something that the
orchestras do organically

00:50:40.070 --> 00:50:41.370
and well.

00:50:41.370 --> 00:50:45.570
&gt;&gt; RWJ: And to build on
that is, in this city,

00:50:45.570 --> 00:50:49.040
performing in different
venues is critical.

00:50:49.040 --> 00:50:53.780
As opposed to maybe smaller
cities or different cities.

00:50:53.780 --> 00:50:55.530
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: And different
neighborhoods and communities.

00:50:55.530 --> 00:51:00.710
&gt;&gt; RWJ: Theaters, clubs, concert
halls, not just in a large,

00:51:00.710 --> 00:51:05.890
expensive, ticket-based event.

00:51:05.890 --> 00:51:07.320
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield:
Yeah, and to your point,

00:51:07.320 --> 00:51:10.940
there are many audiences who
come to an outdoor stroll-to

00:51:10.940 --> 00:51:14.080
who might not wander
inside to a performance.

00:51:14.080 --> 00:51:15.380
&gt;&gt; RWJ: That's right.

00:51:15.380 --> 00:51:16.680
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: But
they've had an experience

00:51:16.680 --> 00:51:17.980
that they might like to.

00:51:17.980 --> 00:51:20.890
And we certainly see that
with our summer camps.

00:51:20.890 --> 00:51:23.040
Kids have a first-time
experience with people who come

00:51:23.040 --> 00:51:25.270
to some of our outdoor
performances.

00:51:25.270 --> 00:51:27.120
We never know who's
in the audience

00:51:27.120 --> 00:51:30.690
and when there's a chance
to get them excited.

00:51:30.690 --> 00:51:33.930
And that's something we think
about a lot as a presenter.

00:51:33.930 --> 00:51:38.250
That experience has to compete
with what people experience

00:51:38.250 --> 00:51:42.120
on TV, the radio, what
they can dial up at home.

00:51:42.120 --> 00:51:45.520
So it's about the musicians,
the creativity, the connection

00:51:45.520 --> 00:51:48.000
that drives people to
experience this together.

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:52.840
So when you said sharing the
space, I think that's something

00:51:52.840 --> 00:51:56.510
that even more than relevant is
perhaps the most profound thing.

00:51:56.510 --> 00:52:00.360
It's the sharing of space
whether it's indoors

00:52:00.360 --> 00:52:01.660
or outdoors.

00:52:01.660 --> 00:52:02.960
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson: Right.

00:52:02.960 --> 00:52:04.760
I also want to add to that,
I think there are needs

00:52:04.760 --> 00:52:08.870
of the community that also
need to be listened to.

00:52:08.870 --> 00:52:11.920
And I think some of
that is people's voices.

00:52:11.920 --> 00:52:13.220
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Right.

00:52:13.220 --> 00:52:14.520
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson:
When I think about --

00:52:14.520 --> 00:52:16.280
I just don't understand
this blue team

00:52:16.280 --> 00:52:18.550
versus red team,
urban versus rural.

00:52:18.550 --> 00:52:20.980
I mean, schools are
bad in both places.

00:52:20.980 --> 00:52:23.390
Kids don't have what
they need in both places.

00:52:23.390 --> 00:52:26.040
There are not enough jobs
or opportunities to grow.

00:52:26.040 --> 00:52:28.590
We're all in the same
boat and we're paddling

00:52:28.590 --> 00:52:30.100
in different directions.

00:52:30.100 --> 00:52:31.890
And it's really easy
to say, "Well,

00:52:31.890 --> 00:52:33.690
I think we need another
youth orchestra.

00:52:33.690 --> 00:52:35.420
We need another music camp.

00:52:35.420 --> 00:52:38.560
We need to curate
another performance."

00:52:38.560 --> 00:52:44.030
And quite frankly what I'm
hearing from my parents

00:52:44.030 --> 00:52:48.500
and from the kids is that
you, kids need an opportunity.

00:52:48.500 --> 00:52:51.530
I mean, their kids need
opportunities to grow,

00:52:51.530 --> 00:52:53.870
to be challenged, to
be in an environment

00:52:53.870 --> 00:52:56.220
where the bar is set
really high for them.

00:52:56.220 --> 00:52:57.520
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Right.

00:52:57.520 --> 00:52:58.820
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson:
Kids want activities.

00:52:58.820 --> 00:53:00.120
They want to connect
with one another.

00:53:00.120 --> 00:53:02.530
They want to feel
proud about something

00:53:02.530 --> 00:53:04.300
that they have really
accomplished as a team.

00:53:04.300 --> 00:53:08.860
And I think that they want to
be seen in a positive light.

00:53:08.860 --> 00:53:10.270
They want their voices
to be heard.

00:53:10.270 --> 00:53:13.300
That was powerful about
that performance in Detroit.

00:53:13.300 --> 00:53:18.050
We're saying we are
important in many ways.

00:53:18.050 --> 00:53:19.350
We gave voice to that.

00:53:19.350 --> 00:53:20.650
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Right.

00:53:20.650 --> 00:53:21.950
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson: And we
did that through the orchestra.

00:53:21.950 --> 00:53:23.310
Then you have everybody
that sure --

00:53:23.310 --> 00:53:25.390
I mean, we need more taxpayers.

00:53:25.390 --> 00:53:28.450
And we need safer
streets and we need people

00:53:28.450 --> 00:53:29.750
that are more responsible

00:53:29.750 --> 00:53:31.790
and that are contributing
back to society.

00:53:31.790 --> 00:53:33.980
And we can give that back.

00:53:33.980 --> 00:53:38.350
But I just feel that when I
look at my Facebook news feed,

00:53:38.350 --> 00:53:41.420
the big problem is what a
lot of artists are having.

00:53:41.420 --> 00:53:47.480
And I just think that that's
not necessarily the solution.

00:53:47.480 --> 00:53:50.670
It's really to say, what do
the people around us need?

00:53:50.670 --> 00:53:53.470
And if we take care
of that first,

00:53:53.470 --> 00:53:55.500
I know that we will be okay.

00:53:55.500 --> 00:53:57.940
It's just, do we have
the will to do it?

00:53:57.940 --> 00:54:00.820
Do we even have the
will to listen?

00:54:00.820 --> 00:54:02.120
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Right.

00:54:02.120 --> 00:54:05.210
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson: If not,
we will continue to create stuff

00:54:05.210 --> 00:54:07.130
that folks just don't need.

00:54:07.130 --> 00:54:10.480
And they're not even there in
the audience to even hear it.

00:54:10.480 --> 00:54:13.470
And then we rely on
a very small group

00:54:13.470 --> 00:54:16.200
of people to keep this afloat.

00:54:16.200 --> 00:54:21.760
And I just don't think that
that's going to really get us

00:54:21.760 --> 00:54:24.870
into the next 20 years
thinking that we're going

00:54:24.870 --> 00:54:27.500
to be even more healthy.

00:54:27.500 --> 00:54:28.800
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Yeah.

00:54:28.800 --> 00:54:30.100
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: May I say,
just because I want to make sure

00:54:30.100 --> 00:54:33.030
that it gets said, almost
to both of your points.

00:54:33.030 --> 00:54:36.390
But you said something that made
me think of it, and that is --

00:54:36.390 --> 00:54:39.420
it was actually your
notion about being willing

00:54:39.420 --> 00:54:40.860
to play in different places.

00:54:40.860 --> 00:54:44.180
What I say to my orchestra
is that we're not going

00:54:44.180 --> 00:54:45.730
to run away from
our versatility.

00:54:45.730 --> 00:54:47.660
We're going to run
towards that versatility.

00:54:47.660 --> 00:54:48.960
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Yes, yes.

00:54:48.960 --> 00:54:50.460
&gt;&gt; Thomas Wilkins: Because you
mentioned in our phone meeting

00:54:50.460 --> 00:54:52.400
that the orchestra
is like a community.

00:54:52.400 --> 00:54:53.700
It's a diverse group

00:54:53.700 --> 00:54:55.700
of individuals working
together for a common good.

00:54:55.700 --> 00:54:58.120
But at least in the
orchestra world,

00:54:58.120 --> 00:54:59.660
we can become one
thing one night --

00:54:59.660 --> 00:55:03.390
two weeks ago, we did Ben
Folds the first night,

00:55:03.390 --> 00:55:06.240
Pete Martini the second night
and Chasiko the third night.

00:55:06.240 --> 00:55:09.020
Now those weren't all the same
people groups, but we were able

00:55:09.020 --> 00:55:11.400
to be this for this
people, this for this people

00:55:11.400 --> 00:55:13.230
and this for these people.

00:55:13.230 --> 00:55:16.450
And we sacrificed
nothing in the process.

00:55:16.450 --> 00:55:20.090
And sometimes that finds
itself away from the stage,

00:55:20.090 --> 00:55:24.690
but in any case, it really is
more about us being willing

00:55:24.690 --> 00:55:26.810
to be different things
at different times.

00:55:26.810 --> 00:55:29.400
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: So ultimately
we want our organizations

00:55:29.400 --> 00:55:30.700
to thrive.

00:55:30.700 --> 00:55:33.860
And you know, every generation
would say they're at sort

00:55:33.860 --> 00:55:38.490
of an existential crossroads of
doubling down and understanding

00:55:38.490 --> 00:55:41.700
and articulating what
they can do uniquely.

00:55:41.700 --> 00:55:45.890
There's a very different
level of engagement

00:55:45.890 --> 00:55:47.560
and frankly I think it's one

00:55:47.560 --> 00:55:50.390
of the most exciting parts
certainly of our work here,

00:55:50.390 --> 00:55:52.850
is that there are so
many fantastic musicians

00:55:52.850 --> 00:55:56.460
and creative people living
and working in Washington DC.

00:55:56.460 --> 00:55:59.180
As a former music publisher,
I knew from the numbers

00:55:59.180 --> 00:56:02.260
that it had one of the highest
musical populations per capita

00:56:02.260 --> 00:56:03.950
of any place in the country.

00:56:03.950 --> 00:56:05.250
So many choirs here.

00:56:05.250 --> 00:56:06.990
So many people making music.

00:56:06.990 --> 00:56:09.640
And as I moved here and heard

00:56:09.640 --> 00:56:12.290
and saw what people were
creating in clubs, the bands,

00:56:12.290 --> 00:56:17.090
the ensembles, the culturally
specific community performances,

00:56:17.090 --> 00:56:19.190
I was blown away
and I thought, "Wow,

00:56:19.190 --> 00:56:21.740
that could really inform
what we choose to program

00:56:21.740 --> 00:56:23.180
and what we do together."

00:56:23.180 --> 00:56:26.190
So we created a whole program
called the Mars Urban Art

00:56:26.190 --> 00:56:30.370
Initiative where local artists
and visiting artists connect

00:56:30.370 --> 00:56:34.070
and make music together, are
featured on our main stage,

00:56:34.070 --> 00:56:37.760
are featured in free
performances, paid performances.

00:56:37.760 --> 00:56:42.900
It's something that
it's not contrived.

00:56:42.900 --> 00:56:47.770
It's a way for us
to be more fully --

00:56:47.770 --> 00:56:50.280
a fuller, more dynamic
organization.

00:56:50.280 --> 00:56:54.420
Because we have local
artists who are fantastic

00:56:54.420 --> 00:56:56.760
and who we can discover
and grow through.

00:56:56.760 --> 00:57:01.230
I mean the whole Go Go movement
here, we had David Harrington

00:57:01.230 --> 00:57:05.660
with the string quartet
visiting a couple weeks ago.

00:57:05.660 --> 00:57:07.510
And he's traveled
all over the world.

00:57:07.510 --> 00:57:09.980
I think many of us have
discovered new music

00:57:09.980 --> 00:57:14.010
through his sort of cultural
anthropological lens.

00:57:14.010 --> 00:57:17.370
And one of the little
girls in the class

00:57:17.370 --> 00:57:20.500
that the quartet played
for raised her hand

00:57:20.500 --> 00:57:24.440
after they had played music
from Armenia and Azerbaijan,

00:57:24.440 --> 00:57:27.530
and she said, "Do you
play any Go Go music?"

00:57:27.530 --> 00:57:29.380
And he said, "Well,
what's Go Go music?"

00:57:29.380 --> 00:57:30.980
And she described it.

00:57:30.980 --> 00:57:32.720
And then he came into my
office afterwards, he said,

00:57:32.720 --> 00:57:34.500
"I have to hear about
this Go Go music."

00:57:34.500 --> 00:57:37.880
And so we played
some Chuck Brown

00:57:37.880 --> 00:57:40.930
and some covers and
he said, "Okay.

00:57:40.930 --> 00:57:42.370
I'm always learning.

00:57:42.370 --> 00:57:43.670
I'm always learning.

00:57:43.670 --> 00:57:46.540
And of course it would be a
10-year-old in the class."

00:57:46.540 --> 00:57:50.710
And he had that sense of
curiosity and sense of curiosity

00:57:50.710 --> 00:57:53.850
about place and the
specificity of communities,

00:57:53.850 --> 00:57:55.850
and learned something
at that moment.

00:57:55.850 --> 00:57:59.120
And that little girl who had
the courage to raise her hand

00:57:59.120 --> 00:58:02.160
and push him perhaps pushed
him in a creative direction

00:58:02.160 --> 00:58:03.680
that will inform
a future program

00:58:03.680 --> 00:58:07.010
that we will bring
to our stages.

00:58:07.010 --> 00:58:09.800
And we presented the Go
Go symphony in the past,

00:58:09.800 --> 00:58:12.680
but this could be an
interesting new collaboration.

00:58:12.680 --> 00:58:15.540
So I think that's a
wonderful sense of discovery,

00:58:15.540 --> 00:58:17.330
if you feel it authentically.

00:58:17.330 --> 00:58:18.720
We're always learning.

00:58:18.720 --> 00:58:21.450
Communities change,
evolve in different ways.

00:58:21.450 --> 00:58:27.360
And I love that you're finding
resonant ways to support

00:58:27.360 --> 00:58:29.640
that in your own
programming and work.

00:58:29.640 --> 00:58:30.940
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
I wanted to say something

00:58:30.940 --> 00:58:32.620
about arts and arts education,

00:58:32.620 --> 00:58:34.700
which is very near
and dear to my heart.

00:58:34.700 --> 00:58:37.650
You mentioned about bringing
opportunities to youth.

00:58:37.650 --> 00:58:41.100
When the ARC was built as a
$28 million beautiful glass

00:58:41.100 --> 00:58:45.270
structure in southeast, and it
houses Living School of Music,

00:58:45.270 --> 00:58:49.080
Washington Ballet -- it was
the Corkrane, now it's going

00:58:49.080 --> 00:58:52.880
to be the Philips Boys and Girls
Clubs, and just a whole host.

00:58:52.880 --> 00:58:56.850
And I was on the board of a
dance company at that time

00:58:56.850 --> 00:59:03.040
and we were really worried, if
we build it, will they come?

00:59:03.040 --> 00:59:04.340
And we built it.

00:59:04.340 --> 00:59:08.530
And they opened it and we said,
"Oh God, if we have ten kids

00:59:08.530 --> 00:59:12.050
to start in music and if we
have five kids in dance,"

00:59:12.050 --> 00:59:15.860
especially we wanted some
boys, not just all girls.

00:59:15.860 --> 00:59:21.980
We opened the doors and had
like 200 people the first day,

00:59:21.980 --> 00:59:24.100
400 within the first week.

00:59:24.100 --> 00:59:26.350
And it's of course
pay what you can.

00:59:26.350 --> 00:59:28.360
But it was bringing
the opportunity

00:59:28.360 --> 00:59:32.820
and giving people a
chance to do something

00:59:32.820 --> 00:59:36.570
and introducing an art
form to them, music, dance.

00:59:36.570 --> 00:59:41.990
And it really changed the
landscape of the community.

00:59:41.990 --> 00:59:43.460
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Yeah.

00:59:43.460 --> 00:59:46.050
So I know that we have a
performance to look forward to.

00:59:46.050 --> 00:59:48.830
Are there sort of some final
words you'd like to share?

00:59:48.830 --> 00:59:52.800
Or should we jump into your
introduction of Play On Philly?

00:59:52.800 --> 00:59:54.320
&gt;&gt; Rhona Wolfe Friedman:
Jump into music.

00:59:54.320 --> 00:59:58.510
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: Well, thank
you for a wonderful discussion.

00:59:58.510 --> 01:00:08.040
[ Applause ]

01:00:08.040 --> 01:00:09.340
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson:
So we are really excited

01:00:09.340 --> 01:00:11.470
to perform a brief
piece for you.

01:00:11.470 --> 01:00:15.020
First of all, I am
really, really proud of all

01:00:15.020 --> 01:00:17.520
of our students at
Play On Philly.

01:00:17.520 --> 01:00:20.470
We brought about 50
or so down yesterday.

01:00:20.470 --> 01:00:23.610
They performed at the
ARC and also made a stop

01:00:23.610 --> 01:00:27.900
at Howard University, and
then I believe were running

01:00:27.900 --> 01:00:30.770
around the monuments
late at night, till 11:00

01:00:30.770 --> 01:00:32.210
or midnight or something.

01:00:32.210 --> 01:00:34.450
I can't remember what it was.

01:00:34.450 --> 01:00:38.840
But I'm really, really
proud of our students.

01:00:38.840 --> 01:00:44.040
They represent -- you'll see
about 20 or so on this stage.

01:00:44.040 --> 01:00:45.520
There's about 50 that came.

01:00:45.520 --> 01:00:47.940
There's several of our
students here on the front row

01:00:47.940 --> 01:00:49.330
and several in the back.

01:00:49.330 --> 01:00:52.180
So if you all could
give all of our kids

01:00:52.180 --> 01:00:55.510
that are here today a
big round of applause.

01:00:55.510 --> 01:01:08.120
[ Applause ]

01:01:08.120 --> 01:01:11.750
And also very, very thankful
for our teaching artists

01:01:11.750 --> 01:01:14.440
that are here, and our staff.

01:01:14.440 --> 01:01:18.200
Especially Ryan Crump who
runs our high school program

01:01:18.200 --> 01:01:21.300
and Chris Santentasio
who will be the conductor

01:01:21.300 --> 01:01:23.790
of this ensemble.

01:01:23.790 --> 01:01:30.410
So they will perform Therondel
from Bizet's L'Arlesienne.

01:01:30.410 --> 01:01:34.030
I grew up in Atlanta.

01:01:34.030 --> 01:01:36.040
[ Laughter ]

01:01:36.040 --> 01:01:37.340
I'm sorry.

01:01:37.340 --> 01:01:41.070
Yeah, I'm not built
for all that stuff.

01:01:41.070 --> 01:01:43.200
But they'll perform
that for you.

01:01:43.200 --> 01:01:46.320
I'm pretty sure that we'll
need about two minutes

01:01:46.320 --> 01:01:49.700
to kind of get the stage set.

01:01:49.700 --> 01:01:52.240
And if I am correct,
after their performance,

01:01:52.240 --> 01:01:54.200
I believe we'll take
a short break.

01:01:54.200 --> 01:01:55.500
Or do we?

01:01:55.500 --> 01:01:56.800
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield: We
have one more speaker,

01:01:56.800 --> 01:01:58.100
then we'll take a break.

01:01:58.100 --> 01:01:59.400
Yes.

01:01:59.400 --> 01:02:00.700
&gt;&gt; Stanford Thompson: Okay.

01:02:00.700 --> 01:02:02.000
So just sit tight
for a little bit.

01:02:02.000 --> 01:02:03.300
But thank you for having our
students here to perform.

01:02:03.300 --> 01:02:04.600
So enjoy that.

01:02:04.600 --> 01:02:05.900
&gt;&gt; Chris Santentasio:
Good afternoon.

01:02:05.900 --> 01:02:07.750
My name is Chris Santentasio.

01:02:07.750 --> 01:02:10.980
I'm the conductor of the Play
On Philly Symphony Orchestra.

01:02:10.980 --> 01:02:12.280
Thank you for having us today.

01:02:12.280 --> 01:02:15.050
And we'll just begin.

