01:13:51.040 --> 01:13:52.340
&gt;&gt; Jenny Bilfield:
Hello, everyone,

01:13:52.340 --> 01:13:53.640
Jenny Bilfield back again

01:13:53.640 --> 01:13:55.760
to introduce our
wonderful second panel.

01:13:55.760 --> 01:13:58.150
Hope that you enjoyed your break
and had a chance to look at some

01:13:58.150 --> 01:14:00.120
of the archives that library has

01:14:00.120 --> 01:14:04.120
so generously set
out for us to enjoy.

01:14:04.120 --> 01:14:06.300
It's my great pleasure
to introduce Karen Dillon

01:14:06.300 --> 01:14:09.940
who will then introduce her
panel for risk and innovation.

01:14:09.940 --> 01:14:12.940
Karen Dillon is a former editor
of the Harvard Business Review

01:14:12.940 --> 01:14:15.390
and has long chronicled
the successes and failures

01:14:15.390 --> 01:14:17.490
of businesses and their leaders.

01:14:17.490 --> 01:14:19.540
She's currently a
contributing editor

01:14:19.540 --> 01:14:21.530
to the Harvard Business
Review focusing on topics

01:14:21.530 --> 01:14:23.380
of leadership, managing people,

01:14:23.380 --> 01:14:26.190
managing yourself
and entrepreneurship.

01:14:26.190 --> 01:14:27.490
She's a coauthor

01:14:27.490 --> 01:14:29.670
of the bestselling How Will
You Measure Your Life?,

01:14:29.670 --> 01:14:30.970
Competing Against Luck:

01:14:30.970 --> 01:14:33.540
The Story of Innovation
and Customer Choice.

01:14:33.540 --> 01:14:35.860
And she was previously
the deputy editor of Inc.

01:14:35.860 --> 01:14:37.910
Magazine and served as
editor and publisher

01:14:37.910 --> 01:14:40.310
of the critically-acclaimed
American lawyer magazine,

01:14:40.310 --> 01:14:42.300
the London-based Legal Business.

01:14:42.300 --> 01:14:44.850
She is currently a global
ambassador for Legal 500,

01:14:44.850 --> 01:14:47.640
providing in-depth analysis
of the global legal market.

01:14:47.640 --> 01:14:48.940
She's a graduate of Cornell

01:14:48.940 --> 01:14:52.200
and Northwestern University's
Medill School of Journalism.

01:14:52.200 --> 01:14:53.830
And she was named
by Ashoka as one

01:14:53.830 --> 01:14:58.360
of the world's most influential
and inspiring women in 2011.

01:14:58.360 --> 01:15:00.340
Please join me as she
makes a presentation

01:15:00.340 --> 01:15:02.010
and then invites
her panel to join.

01:15:02.010 --> 01:15:04.510
Thank you.

01:15:04.510 --> 01:15:12.040
[ Applause ]

01:15:12.040 --> 01:15:13.670
&gt;&gt; Karen Dillon: Thank you
very much for the introduction.

01:15:13.670 --> 01:15:15.090
Good morning.

01:15:15.090 --> 01:15:17.740
Very happy to be here around
all these creative people.

01:15:17.740 --> 01:15:19.040
It's very exciting to me,

01:15:19.040 --> 01:15:21.150
especially talking
about innovation.

01:15:21.150 --> 01:15:23.420
Innovation, I come
with a business hat on,

01:15:23.420 --> 01:15:25.580
but I know it is
a global problem.

01:15:25.580 --> 01:15:28.070
It's a problem for
organizations of all sizes

01:15:28.070 --> 01:15:30.350
and types literally
around the world.

01:15:30.350 --> 01:15:32.030
And it's something
that in the pages

01:15:32.030 --> 01:15:35.350
of Harvard Business Review we've
been writing about for decades

01:15:35.350 --> 01:15:38.010
without showing much
signs of progress.

01:15:38.010 --> 01:15:40.990
It turns out we may be
innovative people and we think

01:15:40.990 --> 01:15:42.510
of ourselves that way,

01:15:42.510 --> 01:15:46.640
but by and large companies
stink at innovation.

01:15:46.640 --> 01:15:48.970
Let me show you why.

01:15:48.970 --> 01:15:53.240
This is data from Neilson which
scans all consumer goods sold,

01:15:53.240 --> 01:15:55.560
things you might buy at
Target or the grocery store.

01:15:55.560 --> 01:15:57.660
And over a four-year period,

01:15:57.660 --> 01:15:59.860
there were 20,000 new
products launched --

01:15:59.860 --> 01:16:01.520
these are in the
past four years --

01:16:01.520 --> 01:16:03.810
all of which had smart people.

01:16:03.810 --> 01:16:05.630
They were good ideas, they
were things that seemed

01:16:05.630 --> 01:16:07.350
like they had all the
data and information

01:16:07.350 --> 01:16:09.320
to be sure these would be hits.

01:16:09.320 --> 01:16:12.460
Only 92 of them were
any definition of a hit.

01:16:12.460 --> 01:16:14.400
Most of the other
ones disappeared.

01:16:14.400 --> 01:16:16.360
That's a terrible
investment rate

01:16:16.360 --> 01:16:19.950
for a company that's invested
time, money and energy in,

01:16:19.950 --> 01:16:21.900
trying to create
something, a new innovation

01:16:21.900 --> 01:16:23.270
that would bring
them more customers

01:16:23.270 --> 01:16:26.730
or make their customers
more loyal to them.

01:16:26.730 --> 01:16:33.340
The global consulting firm
McKenzie recently surveyed

01:16:33.340 --> 01:16:36.070
global leaders, and 84%
of global leaders said

01:16:36.070 --> 01:16:38.120
that innovation was
extremely important

01:16:38.120 --> 01:16:39.730
to the success of their company.

01:16:39.730 --> 01:16:43.310
If you look at the Fortune 500
from say 20 years ago and now,

01:16:43.310 --> 01:16:44.610
that will become very obvious.

01:16:44.610 --> 01:16:48.330
Many companies that were Fortune
500 staples then are gone

01:16:48.330 --> 01:16:49.630
from the Fortune 500 now.

01:16:49.630 --> 01:16:51.970
It's critical to
growth and staying alive

01:16:51.970 --> 01:16:53.540
and staying competitive.

01:16:53.540 --> 01:16:56.810
But of those 84% who said
it was extremely important,

01:16:56.810 --> 01:16:59.590
94% of them were very unhappy

01:16:59.590 --> 01:17:02.270
with their company's
performance in innovation.

01:17:02.270 --> 01:17:04.420
For some reason,
really smart people

01:17:04.420 --> 01:17:07.980
with good ideas keep
getting innovation wrong.

01:17:07.980 --> 01:17:11.740
What is it that we're not asking
or doing or knowing that means

01:17:11.740 --> 01:17:13.040
that we haven't gotten better?

01:17:13.040 --> 01:17:15.250
Organizations have not
gotten better at innovating

01:17:15.250 --> 01:17:19.140
over the past decades, even
with all the data we have now.

01:17:19.140 --> 01:17:23.220
The technology we can employ,
the way we can analyze things,

01:17:23.220 --> 01:17:25.610
we're still not improving
our strike rate.

01:17:25.610 --> 01:17:26.910
Well, I will submit to you

01:17:26.910 --> 01:17:30.520
that maybe we're asking
for the wrong things.

01:17:30.520 --> 01:17:32.750
How do you know what is going

01:17:32.750 --> 01:17:35.970
to make an innovation
successful in advance?

01:17:35.970 --> 01:17:37.750
Mostly, that 92 hits

01:17:37.750 --> 01:17:39.680
out of 20,000 will tell
you it's a little bit

01:17:39.680 --> 01:17:41.070
of a crap shoot, hit or miss.

01:17:41.070 --> 01:17:42.370
Try a lot of things.

01:17:42.370 --> 01:17:43.670
You hope you get it right.

01:17:43.670 --> 01:17:45.010
You think you understand
your customers

01:17:45.010 --> 01:17:46.310
or prospective customers

01:17:46.310 --> 01:17:47.740
and you're going to
create something.

01:17:47.740 --> 01:17:50.630
But is that really a
strategy: try, hit and miss?

01:17:50.630 --> 01:17:51.930
Is that good enough?

01:17:51.930 --> 01:17:54.180
Especially when you have limited
resources as I'm guessing some

01:17:54.180 --> 01:17:57.060
of your companies
and organizations do.

01:17:57.060 --> 01:17:58.650
Well, I'm going to
tell you a story

01:17:58.650 --> 01:18:01.330
about successful innovation
that has nothing to do

01:18:01.330 --> 01:18:04.540
with technology, has nothing
to do with focus groups.

01:18:04.540 --> 01:18:05.840
It has everything to do

01:18:05.840 --> 01:18:08.610
with understanding the
right questions to ask.

01:18:08.610 --> 01:18:10.690
This is a story where the hero

01:18:10.690 --> 01:18:14.380
of our tale is a humble
dining room table.

01:18:14.380 --> 01:18:18.260
So there was a Detroit-area
construction and housing company

01:18:18.260 --> 01:18:22.280
that built two-bedroom condos
on the outskirts of Detroit.

01:18:22.280 --> 01:18:23.580
And they were really lovely.

01:18:23.580 --> 01:18:25.540
They priced them
competitively compared

01:18:25.540 --> 01:18:28.110
to other condo types and things.

01:18:28.110 --> 01:18:29.920
They create all kinds
of features

01:18:29.920 --> 01:18:31.900
that they knew people
would like:

01:18:31.900 --> 01:18:34.240
granite countertops,
chrome appliances.

01:18:34.240 --> 01:18:37.270
They aimed at downsizers,
people who were probably looking

01:18:37.270 --> 01:18:40.780
to move from their house into
a nicer, more upscale community

01:18:40.780 --> 01:18:42.080
that would make them
feel special

01:18:42.080 --> 01:18:46.070
about the condo they were buying
and the life they were living.

01:18:46.070 --> 01:18:49.700
They had many, many people
come and look at those condos.

01:18:49.700 --> 01:18:52.840
And yet very few of them
converted to a sale.

01:18:52.840 --> 01:18:54.140
They didn't understand it.

01:18:54.140 --> 01:18:58.370
They convened focus groups and
they asked prospective buyers,

01:18:58.370 --> 01:19:02.720
"What could we add to make
this a more attractive condo

01:19:02.720 --> 01:19:05.170
for you to buy?"

01:19:05.170 --> 01:19:07.520
And those focus group
prospective buyers had no

01:19:07.520 --> 01:19:09.300
shortage of ideas.

01:19:09.300 --> 01:19:12.710
Bay windows, squeakless floors.

01:19:12.710 --> 01:19:14.460
"I want more options
and cabinets

01:19:14.460 --> 01:19:15.760
and the pulls on the cabinets."

01:19:15.760 --> 01:19:17.060
They had a lot of ideas.

01:19:17.060 --> 01:19:20.480
So they created the
showrooms to do that and show

01:19:20.480 --> 01:19:22.170
that they could create
all of those options.

01:19:22.170 --> 01:19:25.120
Everything the focus
group participants wanted,

01:19:25.120 --> 01:19:28.550
they created a show house,
show condo to demonstrate

01:19:28.550 --> 01:19:30.950
that that was all possible.

01:19:30.950 --> 01:19:32.470
That didn't work either.

01:19:32.470 --> 01:19:34.280
Sales did not improve.

01:19:34.280 --> 01:19:37.160
And they were literally giving
prospective buyers everything

01:19:37.160 --> 01:19:39.180
they said they wanted.

01:19:39.180 --> 01:19:40.480
Then they brought
in a consultant,

01:19:40.480 --> 01:19:43.530
a guy called Bob Mesta who was
asked to try to figure out,

01:19:43.530 --> 01:19:45.060
how can we improve sales?

01:19:45.060 --> 01:19:47.070
They blamed everything:
bad weather,

01:19:47.070 --> 01:19:48.440
salespeople weren't good enough.

01:19:48.440 --> 01:19:49.740
Maybe the hours were bad.

01:19:49.740 --> 01:19:51.820
They tried to fix
all of those things.

01:19:51.820 --> 01:19:54.430
And so Bob decided to
take a different approach.

01:19:54.430 --> 01:19:58.690
Instead of asking prospective
buyers what would make them buy,

01:19:58.690 --> 01:20:02.480
he asked people who had
already bought a condo,

01:20:02.480 --> 01:20:03.780
"Tell me about the journey

01:20:03.780 --> 01:20:06.640
to make the decision
to buy this condo."

01:20:06.640 --> 01:20:08.510
They thought from that
they might be able

01:20:08.510 --> 01:20:12.500
to piece together the ideal
demographic or psychographic

01:20:12.500 --> 01:20:13.800
of a prospective buyer.

01:20:13.800 --> 01:20:15.340
Did they all come from
certain zip codes?

01:20:15.340 --> 01:20:17.110
Were they all certain income?

01:20:17.110 --> 01:20:20.070
Could you tell by the
car the actual age?

01:20:20.070 --> 01:20:22.920
As they went through
interview after interview,

01:20:22.920 --> 01:20:24.690
they couldn't see a pattern.

01:20:24.690 --> 01:20:26.100
It was really random.

01:20:26.100 --> 01:20:29.670
They could not predict based
on any data about that person

01:20:29.670 --> 01:20:32.650
if they were going
to be a buyer or not.

01:20:32.650 --> 01:20:36.750
But this one very strange
clue kept coming up.

01:20:36.750 --> 01:20:40.970
People oddly kept mentioning
their dining room table.

01:20:40.970 --> 01:20:42.410
"As soon as they
figured out what to do

01:20:42.410 --> 01:20:45.880
with the dining room
table, I was free to move."

01:20:45.880 --> 01:20:47.570
That was sort of an odd thing,

01:20:47.570 --> 01:20:49.950
because in most cases they
were dining room tables

01:20:49.950 --> 01:20:52.970
from the 1970's,
well worn, dinged up,

01:20:52.970 --> 01:20:55.100
chunky old style
furniture, not something

01:20:55.100 --> 01:20:57.390
that would even make sense
to bring into these lovely,

01:20:57.390 --> 01:20:59.390
sleek, two-bedroom condos.

01:20:59.390 --> 01:21:03.300
It was only as Bob
Mesta was sitting

01:21:03.300 --> 01:21:05.920
at his own dining room
table over Christmas

01:21:05.920 --> 01:21:08.330
that he had a revelation.

01:21:08.330 --> 01:21:12.520
What does a dining
room table stand for?

01:21:12.520 --> 01:21:14.750
Think about your own.

01:21:14.750 --> 01:21:17.960
Family. Sitting at
a dining room table,

01:21:17.960 --> 01:21:20.170
you've probably had
family celebrations,

01:21:20.170 --> 01:21:22.310
birthdays, Christmas, Hanukah.

01:21:22.310 --> 01:21:25.530
In my house we did homework
on it, we made forts under it.

01:21:25.530 --> 01:21:28.680
The dining room table was a
visual reminder of the life

01:21:28.680 --> 01:21:30.550
that these people had built.

01:21:30.550 --> 01:21:32.100
Getting rid of it,
just throwing it out

01:21:32.100 --> 01:21:34.380
or giving it to charity
felt hard.

01:21:34.380 --> 01:21:37.400
It was giving away something
that meant so much to them.

01:21:37.400 --> 01:21:39.700
It was really a powerful
indicator

01:21:39.700 --> 01:21:43.060
of the significance of the move.

01:21:43.060 --> 01:21:46.510
With that insight, we
call that the aha insight,

01:21:46.510 --> 01:21:52.050
they realized something
else was going on.

01:21:52.050 --> 01:21:56.000
They weren't in the business
of helping people just move

01:21:56.000 --> 01:21:58.400
to a new condo or buy a condo.

01:21:58.400 --> 01:22:02.900
They were in the business of
helping people move their lives.

01:22:02.900 --> 01:22:05.480
So when you think about
innovating, what did they need

01:22:05.480 --> 01:22:09.120
to do to those condos to
help people move their lives,

01:22:09.120 --> 01:22:11.040
not just buy a new
place to live?

01:22:11.040 --> 01:22:13.460
That changes the way you think
about what you need to add

01:22:13.460 --> 01:22:16.940
or subtract to make
it more appealing.

01:22:16.940 --> 01:22:19.080
They might have cared
about chrome appliances,

01:22:19.080 --> 01:22:21.680
but that wasn't going
to trigger them to move.

01:22:21.680 --> 01:22:23.800
But when they figured
out, "Okay,

01:22:23.800 --> 01:22:26.970
we need to take something away,
20% of the second bedroom,

01:22:26.970 --> 01:22:29.640
to make room for the dining
room table," that allowed people

01:22:29.640 --> 01:22:32.400
to not have to make that
decision about whether

01:22:32.400 --> 01:22:34.300
or not they were actually
going to leave behind

01:22:34.300 --> 01:22:35.600
that memory of family.

01:22:35.600 --> 01:22:38.000
They could choose to take
it if they wanted to.

01:22:38.000 --> 01:22:41.760
They actually raised the
prices of the condos,

01:22:41.760 --> 01:22:43.940
made the second bedroom smaller

01:22:43.940 --> 01:22:45.820
and then they added
a few small things

01:22:45.820 --> 01:22:48.430
in that made a powerful
difference to people.

01:22:48.430 --> 01:22:52.840
They created on-side storage
so that people didn't have

01:22:52.840 --> 01:22:55.150
to get rid of everything
at one fell swoop

01:22:55.150 --> 01:22:56.470
when they were ready to move.

01:22:56.470 --> 01:22:59.780
They created a sorting
room on sight as well

01:22:59.780 --> 01:23:02.930
so they didn't have to go
through every piece of artwork

01:23:02.930 --> 01:23:06.430
from their children's childhood
or calendars and cards,

01:23:06.430 --> 01:23:07.730
things they had saved.

01:23:07.730 --> 01:23:09.450
You could take two
years to do that.

01:23:09.450 --> 01:23:11.850
They increased the price a
little bit, added those services

01:23:11.850 --> 01:23:17.450
in and they were able to improve
their sales by 25% at a time

01:23:17.450 --> 01:23:19.580
when the Detroit area market
was having a very hard

01:23:19.580 --> 01:23:20.880
time otherwise.

01:23:20.880 --> 01:23:23.350
They were growing when
everybody else was shrinking.

01:23:23.350 --> 01:23:27.300
The aha is in what they
realized: people wanted

01:23:27.300 --> 01:23:30.570
to move lives, not
just buy a condo.

01:23:30.570 --> 01:23:33.600
Now what is the significance
of this?

01:23:33.600 --> 01:23:35.400
This illustrates
something I've been working

01:23:35.400 --> 01:23:38.480
on with Harvard Business School
professor Clayton Christianson.

01:23:38.480 --> 01:23:40.420
He's been working
on it for 20 years.

01:23:40.420 --> 01:23:43.520
Clayton Christianson has been
called multiple times the most

01:23:43.520 --> 01:23:45.920
influential management
thinker in the world.

01:23:45.920 --> 01:23:48.420
And he's been struggling
for 20 years with the idea

01:23:48.420 --> 01:23:51.500
of why are companies so
hit or miss at innovation?

01:23:51.500 --> 01:23:53.470
Why are they so bad at it?

01:23:53.470 --> 01:23:57.420
And that moving company
illustrates his answer

01:23:57.420 --> 01:23:59.300
to the question.

01:23:59.300 --> 01:24:03.570
People don't just buy
products or services.

01:24:03.570 --> 01:24:07.300
They hire them, in his
language, to do a job for them.

01:24:07.300 --> 01:24:11.370
And what we mean by that is what
we call the causal mechanism

01:24:11.370 --> 01:24:12.670
in academia.

01:24:12.670 --> 01:24:16.270
What causes what to happen is
not anything about the specifics

01:24:16.270 --> 01:24:20.930
of the product; it's about
how it helps them do that job

01:24:20.930 --> 01:24:23.150
that they're hiring it to do.

01:24:23.150 --> 01:24:25.430
Now this may just sound like
a simple language change,

01:24:25.430 --> 01:24:29.050
but we think it's a really
profound and significant change

01:24:29.050 --> 01:24:31.310
in the way you think
about innovation

01:24:31.310 --> 01:24:34.890
so that people will actually
hire your product or service,

01:24:34.890 --> 01:24:37.180
in your case your organization.

01:24:37.180 --> 01:24:38.720
We mean something very specific.

01:24:38.720 --> 01:24:40.200
We call it the job to be done.

01:24:40.200 --> 01:24:43.960
People are looking to bring a
product or service in their life

01:24:43.960 --> 01:24:45.990
to help them make
progress on something

01:24:45.990 --> 01:24:48.280
that they're struggling with.

01:24:48.280 --> 01:24:51.250
It's usually surrounded
with complex social

01:24:51.250 --> 01:24:53.970
and emotional components
as well, and it's always

01:24:53.970 --> 01:24:56.480
in particular circumstances.

01:24:56.480 --> 01:25:00.030
You can innovate successfully
if you understand the job

01:25:00.030 --> 01:25:02.060
to be done for people
who are your customers

01:25:02.060 --> 01:25:06.070
or prospective customers and
offer a solution that does

01:25:06.070 --> 01:25:09.030
that job better than
anything else does.

01:25:09.030 --> 01:25:11.300
Now let me illustrate so
that you know this isn't just

01:25:11.300 --> 01:25:13.210
different language
talking about it.

01:25:13.210 --> 01:25:15.390
Thinking about innovation
through the lens of jobs

01:25:15.390 --> 01:25:18.240
to be done changes everything.

01:25:20.410 --> 01:25:22.410
Table equals family.

01:25:22.410 --> 01:25:24.240
You can see the powerful social

01:25:24.240 --> 01:25:26.680
and emotional pieces
of that ugly table.

01:25:26.680 --> 01:25:28.880
That's fine, it is
an ugly table.

01:25:28.880 --> 01:25:30.660
But that had nothing to do
with the function or meaning

01:25:30.660 --> 01:25:32.150
of a table to dine on.

01:25:32.150 --> 01:25:37.160
It had to do with the emotional
and social pieces of that.

01:25:37.160 --> 01:25:41.100
Help me make progress -- that is
what people are looking to do.

01:25:41.100 --> 01:25:44.580
And if your product or
service helps them do that,

01:25:44.580 --> 01:25:47.400
then you will successfully
bring people to your product

01:25:47.400 --> 01:25:50.130
or service and keep them there.

01:25:50.130 --> 01:25:54.420
So what changes if you put on
the lenses of jobs to be done?

01:25:54.420 --> 01:25:58.160
Look at the problem through
that distinct point of view.

01:25:58.160 --> 01:26:00.640
Everything changes.

01:26:00.640 --> 01:26:03.340
This is a Sony Playstation.

01:26:03.340 --> 01:26:06.750
Who's the competition
for Sony Playstation?

01:26:06.750 --> 01:26:11.440
Xbox, maybe Wii in the old days.

01:26:11.440 --> 01:26:12.740
Makes sense, right?

01:26:12.740 --> 01:26:14.040
And I know that they're
often compared side

01:26:14.040 --> 01:26:15.340
by side in sales and prices.

01:26:15.340 --> 01:26:17.780
That's how you look at it
and decide which one to buy.

01:26:17.780 --> 01:26:21.370
What if I told you this
was the competition?

01:26:22.770 --> 01:26:24.070
How about this?

01:26:24.070 --> 01:26:26.030
This is my solution.

01:26:26.030 --> 01:26:28.040
[ Laughter ]

01:26:28.040 --> 01:26:30.190
These are these adult coloring
books, a new innovation.

01:26:30.190 --> 01:26:32.310
Have you seen those?

01:26:32.310 --> 01:26:35.300
These are all competing
for a different job

01:26:35.300 --> 01:26:36.600
than you might have imagined

01:26:36.600 --> 01:26:38.000
when I showed the
Sony Playstation.

01:26:38.000 --> 01:26:41.110
They're competing for
the job of help me relax.

01:26:41.110 --> 01:26:43.150
Maybe when I get home from
work or on the weekends,

01:26:43.150 --> 01:26:45.460
help me do something that
will take my mind off

01:26:45.460 --> 01:26:48.080
of whatever else is
stressing me at the moment.

01:26:48.080 --> 01:26:50.280
Now okay, competing with those,

01:26:50.280 --> 01:26:53.140
that sounds like a theoretical
thing, but is that really true?

01:26:53.140 --> 01:26:56.060
That's exactly what
Netflix understands.

01:26:56.060 --> 01:26:57.410
Reed Hastings who's the founder

01:26:57.410 --> 01:27:00.370
of Netflix was asked how he
saw the competition with Amazon

01:27:00.370 --> 01:27:01.670
and their videos recently.

01:27:01.670 --> 01:27:05.080
And he said, "We compete with
everything you do to relax.

01:27:05.080 --> 01:27:07.460
A bottle of wine may be
our toughest competitor."

01:27:07.460 --> 01:27:11.180
If you realize you're not
just competing with things

01:27:11.180 --> 01:27:13.260
that are exactly like you,

01:27:13.260 --> 01:27:16.090
you completely broaden your
opportunities to innovate

01:27:16.090 --> 01:27:17.860
and bring more people to you.

01:27:17.860 --> 01:27:20.630
You are a solution
to a job to be done.

01:27:20.630 --> 01:27:23.300
If it's only something that's
exactly like you that you think

01:27:23.300 --> 01:27:24.840
of as your competition,

01:27:24.840 --> 01:27:28.020
you probably haven't fully
understood the reason people are

01:27:28.020 --> 01:27:30.740
choosing to hire your service

01:27:30.740 --> 01:27:32.430
over any other possible
solution.

01:27:32.430 --> 01:27:35.940
The job to be done is complex
and the solution is complex

01:27:35.940 --> 01:27:40.080
and does not line up along
specific category lines.

01:27:40.080 --> 01:27:41.600
And if you can just
begin to think

01:27:41.600 --> 01:27:44.750
about what you're competing
with and open your mind to that,

01:27:44.750 --> 01:27:47.500
you'll be able to offer a
better solution than some

01:27:47.500 --> 01:27:50.670
of those competitions that you
may not realize you're competing

01:27:50.670 --> 01:27:53.410
with in the first place.

01:27:53.410 --> 01:27:54.910
What does better mean?

01:27:54.910 --> 01:27:56.930
I said you'll be able to
offer a better solution?

01:27:56.930 --> 01:28:01.100
This is a little hard to see,
but there's an air mattress

01:28:01.100 --> 01:28:04.400
up against the wall
in an empty room.

01:28:04.400 --> 01:28:09.580
This is not better than a hotel
room by most standards, right?

01:28:09.580 --> 01:28:11.270
You probably know
where this is going.

01:28:11.270 --> 01:28:13.320
This is Air BnB.

01:28:13.320 --> 01:28:16.640
Air BnB was founded not to
compete with hotel rooms,

01:28:16.640 --> 01:28:18.210
which is what you might think.

01:28:18.210 --> 01:28:21.460
It was competing with not
making that trip at all,

01:28:21.460 --> 01:28:23.830
or staying with friends.

01:28:23.830 --> 01:28:27.100
And the people who hired Air
BnB in the beginning wanted

01:28:27.100 --> 01:28:29.030
to be part of something
and feel local.

01:28:29.030 --> 01:28:31.420
They wanted to be able to attend
a conference or they wanted

01:28:31.420 --> 01:28:34.390
to feel like they lived in the
city of Paris for a few days.

01:28:34.390 --> 01:28:36.550
It was competing with
something entirely different.

01:28:36.550 --> 01:28:38.660
It was competing with nothing.

01:28:38.660 --> 01:28:42.290
Competing against nothing
is a really good place to be

01:28:42.290 --> 01:28:43.590
when all other solutions

01:28:43.590 --> 01:28:46.250
for that job are not
better or nonexistent.

01:28:46.250 --> 01:28:48.310
The field is wide open for you.

01:28:48.310 --> 01:28:54.470
You probably know, Air BnB
is now valued at $30 billion.

01:28:54.470 --> 01:28:57.990
It's worth more than the top
several hotel chains combined.

01:28:57.990 --> 01:29:00.510
And maybe now they're competing
with some higher-end offerings,

01:29:00.510 --> 01:29:02.120
but the innovation came

01:29:02.120 --> 01:29:05.410
from recognizing a
different job to be done.

01:29:05.410 --> 01:29:09.190
You would never have thought
that possible ten years ago.

01:29:09.190 --> 01:29:11.320
So okay, you might buy it.

01:29:11.320 --> 01:29:12.770
I like the idea of
job to be done.

01:29:12.770 --> 01:29:15.460
Well, how do I find
a job to be done?

01:29:15.460 --> 01:29:17.450
How do I locate it in my
community or the people

01:29:17.450 --> 01:29:19.660
that we want to deal with?

01:29:19.660 --> 01:29:22.740
What you're looking for is what
people are struggling with.

01:29:22.740 --> 01:29:24.840
You're looking for
struggles to make progress.

01:29:24.840 --> 01:29:26.380
It's always about
making progress

01:29:26.380 --> 01:29:28.450
in particular circumstances.

01:29:28.450 --> 01:29:32.640
And there are clues that people
give off without even realizing.

01:29:32.640 --> 01:29:35.200
Good innovations are
ones that solve problems

01:29:35.200 --> 01:29:39.910
that have bad solutions now or
don't have a solution at all.

01:29:39.910 --> 01:29:44.160
If your solution to a job to
be done is slightly better,

01:29:44.160 --> 01:29:46.220
even a little bit more
than slightly better

01:29:46.220 --> 01:29:49.420
than other solutions to the
problem, you're not likely

01:29:49.420 --> 01:29:51.410
to win people over to you.

01:29:51.410 --> 01:29:54.990
Slightly better does not
cause people to switch.

01:29:54.990 --> 01:29:57.380
We know from Nobel
Prize-winner Daniel Kahneman

01:29:57.380 --> 01:30:00.760
that people's risk aversion
of loss is so powerful

01:30:00.760 --> 01:30:04.310
that they're far more likely
to accept the devil they know

01:30:04.310 --> 01:30:07.040
than to risk losing
that for something else

01:30:07.040 --> 01:30:09.390
that may be slightly better.

01:30:09.390 --> 01:30:13.180
You have to be wildly better
or again, find an opportunity

01:30:13.180 --> 01:30:14.520
to compete with nothing.

01:30:14.520 --> 01:30:18.350
That's where you'll find
innovation opportunities.

01:30:18.350 --> 01:30:22.380
You're looking for workarounds,
things people are doing to try

01:30:22.380 --> 01:30:25.400
to make an existing
solution work for them;

01:30:25.400 --> 01:30:27.860
that may give you a clue
that there's an opportunity

01:30:27.860 --> 01:30:29.710
to develop something
better here.

01:30:29.710 --> 01:30:32.060
This is a quick example
everyone's probably familiar

01:30:32.060 --> 01:30:34.670
with, Quicken's personal
financial software

01:30:34.670 --> 01:30:36.910
which has been around
for a couple decades.

01:30:36.910 --> 01:30:41.490
That was on the market for
four years before the founders

01:30:41.490 --> 01:30:43.840
realized that something
funny was going on.

01:30:43.840 --> 01:30:46.590
They got feedback every year
for those first four year

01:30:46.590 --> 01:30:49.540
that people were kind of
creating weird ways to use it

01:30:49.540 --> 01:30:53.010
for small business software,
to use Quicken for that.

01:30:53.010 --> 01:30:56.140
Funny ways, but they were
buying it for that and using it

01:30:56.140 --> 01:30:57.530
for their small business.

01:30:57.530 --> 01:30:59.470
And they ignored
it for four years

01:30:59.470 --> 01:31:02.700
because they thought there is
really good accounting software

01:31:02.700 --> 01:31:04.920
out there that they can buy
that makes your books pristine

01:31:04.920 --> 01:31:08.350
and it's like having a
small accountant on staff.

01:31:08.350 --> 01:31:11.730
Then they kind of realized that
wasn't what people wanted to do.

01:31:11.730 --> 01:31:15.530
They wanted to not have to worry
about doing their books at all.

01:31:15.530 --> 01:31:16.980
They wanted it to be simple.

01:31:16.980 --> 01:31:19.240
They weren't competing
with that small business

01:31:19.240 --> 01:31:20.740
accounting software.

01:31:20.740 --> 01:31:22.760
They were competing with
hiring your brother-in-law

01:31:22.760 --> 01:31:26.020
to do your books or stuffing
all your receipts in a shoebox

01:31:26.020 --> 01:31:28.580
and kind of getting around to
it at the end of the month.

01:31:28.580 --> 01:31:31.430
They quickly realized
that and corrected it.

01:31:31.430 --> 01:31:35.020
QuickBooks was launched
at twice the price

01:31:35.020 --> 01:31:38.140
of the best small
business accounting process

01:31:38.140 --> 01:31:41.660
and it was the market leader
within months and it still is.

01:31:41.660 --> 01:31:44.680
That whole company Intuit
focuses on the job to be done

01:31:44.680 --> 01:31:46.920
with all of their
product innovations now.

01:31:46.920 --> 01:31:49.660
Non-consumption.

01:31:49.660 --> 01:31:51.300
Basically you're
looking for something

01:31:51.300 --> 01:31:53.760
where people would
rather do nothing than try

01:31:53.760 --> 01:31:55.270
to solve their problems
because they don't like any

01:31:55.270 --> 01:31:57.630
of the solutions out there.

01:31:57.630 --> 01:31:59.730
Have any of you seen
those commercials on TV

01:31:59.730 --> 01:32:01.210
for Southern New
Hampshire University?

01:32:01.210 --> 01:32:03.710
There's a blue bus that's going
around the country handing

01:32:03.710 --> 01:32:05.780
out diplomas to people.

01:32:05.780 --> 01:32:08.430
If you haven't heard of Southern
New Hampshire University,

01:32:08.430 --> 01:32:09.730
SNHU I think they
call themselves

01:32:09.730 --> 01:32:11.120
in the commercials, you should.

01:32:11.120 --> 01:32:12.560
It's one of the biggest
success stories

01:32:12.560 --> 01:32:15.010
in education in the past decade.

01:32:15.010 --> 01:32:17.430
Southern New Hampshire
University was the small,

01:32:17.430 --> 01:32:20.640
nondescript liberal arts
college it is in New Hampshire

01:32:20.640 --> 01:32:22.110
that realized they
were in trouble

01:32:22.110 --> 01:32:23.520
like so many other small,

01:32:23.520 --> 01:32:26.540
nondescript liberal arts
colleges not competing

01:32:26.540 --> 01:32:29.950
at the top level
about ten years ago.

01:32:29.950 --> 01:32:33.310
They knew every year exactly how
many students they would get,

01:32:33.310 --> 01:32:34.610
how many they'd compete

01:32:34.610 --> 01:32:36.230
with from these three
other local universities.

01:32:36.230 --> 01:32:38.120
The win and loss rate was
almost always the same.

01:32:38.120 --> 01:32:40.690
There was no prospect of growth.

01:32:40.690 --> 01:32:43.640
And financial survival
was in question.

01:32:43.640 --> 01:32:46.880
Then they kind of realized they
did have this sleepy beginning

01:32:46.880 --> 01:32:49.150
arm that was doing what
they call distance learning

01:32:49.150 --> 01:32:51.070
for people who didn't want
to come to campus but wanted

01:32:51.070 --> 01:32:53.170
to make progress
towards a degree.

01:32:53.170 --> 01:32:55.230
Their big aha insight was

01:32:55.230 --> 01:32:58.700
that that distance learning
wasn't competing with Harvard

01:32:58.700 --> 01:33:02.510
or Yale or even the local
universities around them.

01:33:02.510 --> 01:33:04.660
It was competing with nothing.

01:33:04.660 --> 01:33:06.960
Those people who were doing
distance learning were trying

01:33:06.960 --> 01:33:10.920
to decide if it was worth going
back to school to get a degree

01:33:10.920 --> 01:33:12.380
when they perhaps had avoided it

01:33:12.380 --> 01:33:14.210
or never had it in
the first place.

01:33:14.210 --> 01:33:16.310
Maybe I should just stick in
this job for two more years

01:33:16.310 --> 01:33:18.110
and try to get promotions.

01:33:18.110 --> 01:33:19.520
They would rather do nothing

01:33:19.520 --> 01:33:21.950
than accept a really difficult
solution that would require them

01:33:21.950 --> 01:33:24.720
to drive to campus or
take weekends and nights

01:33:24.720 --> 01:33:26.020
that they didn't have to work

01:33:26.020 --> 01:33:28.500
on extra credit projects
and things like that.

01:33:28.500 --> 01:33:30.890
With that insight, you're
competing with "It's better

01:33:30.890 --> 01:33:34.210
to do nothing than to pursue
your education further,"

01:33:34.210 --> 01:33:35.710
they made sure that everything

01:33:35.710 --> 01:33:38.230
about their online
program worked for people

01:33:38.230 --> 01:33:41.600
who were working long days,
weekends, maybe sitting

01:33:41.600 --> 01:33:43.660
down at the computer
at 11:00 at night.

01:33:43.660 --> 01:33:46.110
They didn't need to be as
good as Harvard in many ways.

01:33:46.110 --> 01:33:48.800
They needed to be good for the
job people were hiring them

01:33:48.800 --> 01:33:52.050
to do, which was
make my life better.

01:33:52.050 --> 01:33:53.560
They've been wildly successful.

01:33:53.560 --> 01:33:57.590
They stage on campus I think
five separate graduation

01:33:57.590 --> 01:33:58.890
ceremonies now.

01:33:58.890 --> 01:34:01.230
Not on campus, the town's
biggest place, Verizon Arena.

01:34:01.230 --> 01:34:02.990
Because so many people
who have never set foot

01:34:02.990 --> 01:34:05.380
on campus all their
years towards a degree,

01:34:05.380 --> 01:34:07.360
come for that moment of
getting the cap and gown

01:34:07.360 --> 01:34:08.660
and getting their degree.

01:34:08.660 --> 01:34:10.430
And it's a huge success story.

01:34:10.430 --> 01:34:14.600
They were competing with people
who were choosing to do nothing.

01:34:19.710 --> 01:34:23.230
Oops. My clicker's
not advancing.

01:34:23.230 --> 01:34:24.530
There we go.

01:34:24.530 --> 01:34:26.910
Look for unusual uses.

01:34:26.910 --> 01:34:30.800
Any of you ever knocked back a
couple of spoonfuls of Nyquil

01:34:30.800 --> 01:34:33.780
when you really just
wanted a good night's sleep?

01:34:33.780 --> 01:34:35.080
Lots of people do that.

01:34:35.080 --> 01:34:38.640
It turns out the company
finally recognized it.

01:34:38.640 --> 01:34:41.030
They didn't need Nyquil, all
the ingredients in Nyquil.

01:34:41.030 --> 01:34:42.400
They needed sleep.

01:34:42.400 --> 01:34:44.960
Thus, the birth of
Zquil which has none

01:34:44.960 --> 01:34:48.340
of those cold medicine
things in it.

01:34:48.340 --> 01:34:49.640
That was a clue.

01:34:49.640 --> 01:34:52.940
There was an innovation
opportunity to be had here.

01:34:52.940 --> 01:34:54.300
Jobs in our own lives.

01:34:54.300 --> 01:34:56.380
Most of us actually
know, if you think

01:34:56.380 --> 01:34:57.930
about things you're
struggling with,

01:34:57.930 --> 01:35:00.150
things that you wish
there were solutions for.

01:35:00.150 --> 01:35:03.790
You may be the best beginning
germ of an idea for a job

01:35:03.790 --> 01:35:05.270
to be done that you
can share with others.

01:35:05.270 --> 01:35:07.190
If you have it, others
might too.

01:35:07.190 --> 01:35:09.070
This is an illustration
of Care.com

01:35:09.070 --> 01:35:13.280
which is the online babysitter
matchmaking service for parents,

01:35:13.280 --> 01:35:15.490
and elder care and dog
care now as it turns out.

01:35:15.490 --> 01:35:17.560
That was founded by a
woman called Sheila Marcela

01:35:17.560 --> 01:35:19.720
who was having trouble
finding a solution

01:35:19.720 --> 01:35:21.440
for her own day care needs.

01:35:21.440 --> 01:35:27.200
And she created what is now I
think a $65 million company.

01:35:27.200 --> 01:35:30.610
Negative jobs, things we
do not want to have to do.

01:35:30.610 --> 01:35:32.990
People don't want to do
this, so any solution

01:35:32.990 --> 01:35:35.680
that makes it easier for
them to not fully do that.

01:35:35.680 --> 01:35:38.040
Think of the last
time you woke up

01:35:38.040 --> 01:35:40.500
and your kid says they
have a sore throat.

01:35:40.500 --> 01:35:43.290
You know it's probably
strep throat, but man,

01:35:43.290 --> 01:35:44.600
going to the doctor,
what a pain.

01:35:44.600 --> 01:35:47.080
You have to call, wait
till the office opens.

01:35:47.080 --> 01:35:49.090
You can't go in to
work for a few hours.

01:35:49.090 --> 01:35:50.660
You sit there and you know
they're just going to say,

01:35:50.660 --> 01:35:52.810
"Antibiotics," or whatever.

01:35:52.810 --> 01:35:56.420
Well, CVS Minute Clinic
was born when a dad sat

01:35:56.420 --> 01:35:58.000
in the emergency room
with his daughter

01:35:58.000 --> 01:36:00.510
for just a little too long and
got a little too annoyed having

01:36:00.510 --> 01:36:03.110
to wait for what ended up
being a simple prescription

01:36:03.110 --> 01:36:04.410
of antibiotics.

01:36:04.410 --> 01:36:05.710
That was what we
call negative job.

01:36:05.710 --> 01:36:07.790
I don't want to have to do that.

01:36:07.790 --> 01:36:09.780
There's a solution
that is way better

01:36:09.780 --> 01:36:13.390
than having to do it, found.

01:36:13.390 --> 01:36:15.090
This is really important
to know.

01:36:15.090 --> 01:36:16.640
Jobs are not just tasks.

01:36:16.640 --> 01:36:18.700
They're not just
something functional.

01:36:18.700 --> 01:36:21.950
They involve experiences
and that's really important

01:36:21.950 --> 01:36:23.480
to understand, the experience.

01:36:23.480 --> 01:36:24.780
This is where the social

01:36:24.780 --> 01:36:26.730
and emotional components
of it come in.

01:36:26.730 --> 01:36:28.550
You can't successfully innovate

01:36:28.550 --> 01:36:30.620
if you just served
the functional need

01:36:30.620 --> 01:36:33.510
of whatever it is, because the
other things are actually far

01:36:33.510 --> 01:36:35.350
more powerful.

01:36:35.350 --> 01:36:38.190
We believe that if you
actually understand the job

01:36:38.190 --> 01:36:42.180
to be done properly, customers
will pay a premium price

01:36:42.180 --> 01:36:45.500
for a solution that does it
better than anything else.

01:36:45.500 --> 01:36:48.700
So this is not a race to the
bottom; this is actually a race

01:36:48.700 --> 01:36:52.280
to give people what they most
value and most care about.

01:36:52.280 --> 01:36:54.410
Here's my favorite
case in point.

01:36:54.410 --> 01:36:56.580
American Girl Doll,

01:36:56.580 --> 01:36:59.880
the company's been
around for 30 years.

01:36:59.880 --> 01:37:02.340
Many, many people have
tried to compete with it

01:37:02.340 --> 01:37:03.850
by creating similar dolls.

01:37:03.850 --> 01:37:05.150
You'll see them in
Target, you'll see them

01:37:05.150 --> 01:37:07.690
in the Disney Store, Wal-Mart.

01:37:07.690 --> 01:37:11.360
Have any of you ever paid the
current price, I think is $120,

01:37:11.360 --> 01:37:13.150
for an American Girl Doll?

01:37:13.150 --> 01:37:15.340
Me. I've bought several of them.

01:37:15.340 --> 01:37:17.660
And then the wardrobe
on top of that

01:37:17.660 --> 01:37:19.960
which you could buy
an outfit for yourself

01:37:19.960 --> 01:37:21.700
for some of what you pay.

01:37:21.700 --> 01:37:24.880
Do you think we're paying $120
for a doll because the dolls are

01:37:24.880 --> 01:37:28.080
so special, the individual doll?

01:37:28.080 --> 01:37:30.520
They're nice dolls, but I
don't think there's anything

01:37:30.520 --> 01:37:33.440
incredibly special
or unique about them.

01:37:33.440 --> 01:37:36.260
We're paying for something else.

01:37:36.260 --> 01:37:39.310
What's the real job of
the American Girl Doll?

01:37:39.310 --> 01:37:42.490
It's a chance to connect
with our pre-teen daughters

01:37:42.490 --> 01:37:45.020
and nieces and children in a way

01:37:45.020 --> 01:37:46.970
that we didn't think
we could before.

01:37:46.970 --> 01:37:49.300
People said there
was no doll market.

01:37:49.300 --> 01:37:51.010
Girls aged out of dolls

01:37:51.010 --> 01:37:54.920
at age seven before American
Girl Dolls were invented.

01:37:54.920 --> 01:37:58.730
And Pleasant Rowland the
woman who started it was told,

01:37:58.730 --> 01:38:00.690
"There's no chance that
this will succeed."

01:38:00.690 --> 01:38:03.030
The only options at
that age and stage

01:38:03.030 --> 01:38:06.460
up to age seven were Cabbage
Patch dolls in those days

01:38:06.460 --> 01:38:08.820
and really hyper-sexualized
Barbies

01:38:08.820 --> 01:38:10.300
and Bratz and things like that.

01:38:10.300 --> 01:38:12.520
And that wasn't a good
enough answer for her wanting

01:38:12.520 --> 01:38:14.100
to connect with her nieces.

01:38:14.100 --> 01:38:17.990
American Girl Dolls not only
come in a very special box,

01:38:17.990 --> 01:38:20.450
the experience of going
with your mom or your dad

01:38:20.450 --> 01:38:22.350
to get your doll --
this is a sample.

01:38:22.350 --> 01:38:24.280
I actually took this
off someone's blog

01:38:24.280 --> 01:38:25.580
where they were doing highlights

01:38:25.580 --> 01:38:26.880
of their cross-country
trip with their family.

01:38:26.880 --> 01:38:28.180
This is one of their highlights.

01:38:28.180 --> 01:38:30.450
This is the American
Girl Doll restaurant

01:38:30.450 --> 01:38:31.750
where if you don't have a doll,

01:38:31.750 --> 01:38:33.850
you can babysit one
while you're there.

01:38:33.850 --> 01:38:36.150
They have birthday
parties there.

01:38:36.150 --> 01:38:38.490
There's something about
having that special experience

01:38:38.490 --> 01:38:41.580
with your mom and your dad
that people remember forever.

01:38:41.580 --> 01:38:43.550
And the dolls all
have backstories,

01:38:43.550 --> 01:38:44.850
historical backstories.

01:38:44.850 --> 01:38:47.240
There's something that makes
us feel good as parents

01:38:47.240 --> 01:38:48.970
about giving our children
American Girl Dolls

01:38:48.970 --> 01:38:50.280
because they're substantial

01:38:50.280 --> 01:38:51.710
and maybe we'll have
conversations

01:38:51.710 --> 01:38:53.010
about the feelings.

01:38:53.010 --> 01:38:57.180
$120. I can't think of any
product that you willingly put

01:38:57.180 --> 01:38:58.880
up that kind of money for.

01:38:58.880 --> 01:39:02.100
But this one absolutely
understands the job to be done

01:39:02.100 --> 01:39:04.690
and everything about the
American Girl Experience is

01:39:04.690 --> 01:39:06.100
tailored to that.

01:39:06.100 --> 01:39:09.010
Again, you put on the lenses
of seeing a job to be done

01:39:09.010 --> 01:39:11.930
and not just the function
of a product or service.

01:39:11.930 --> 01:39:14.030
Everything about
what goes into that

01:39:14.030 --> 01:39:15.990
and how you treat your
customers, how you talk

01:39:15.990 --> 01:39:18.420
to your customers, changes.

01:39:18.420 --> 01:39:20.740
So I'm going to ask you --

01:39:20.740 --> 01:39:22.420
I heard a lot of interesting
things this morning

01:39:22.420 --> 01:39:25.030
at the panel discussion
about what job --

01:39:25.030 --> 01:39:27.380
you didn't use those words,
but that's what it was --

01:39:27.380 --> 01:39:30.370
what job orchestras
have to do now,

01:39:30.370 --> 01:39:32.510
or people want to
hire them to do.

01:39:32.510 --> 01:39:34.340
It's changed, clearly,
from the old days

01:39:34.340 --> 01:39:36.920
where perhaps it was clearer.

01:39:36.920 --> 01:39:39.830
Are you selling a product?

01:39:39.830 --> 01:39:42.560
Or are you solving
a job for people?

01:39:42.560 --> 01:39:46.140
One of them will give you
ample opportunity to innovate

01:39:46.140 --> 01:39:48.430
and potentially charge
premium prices

01:39:48.430 --> 01:39:49.730
and competitive advantage,

01:39:49.730 --> 01:39:51.830
all things all organizations
want to have.

01:39:51.830 --> 01:39:53.130
Because people will know

01:39:53.130 --> 01:39:56.040
that you've helped them make the
progress that you want to make.

01:39:56.040 --> 01:39:58.760
The other one is just as good;

01:39:58.760 --> 01:40:01.970
the next competitor will
be compared side by side.

01:40:01.970 --> 01:40:05.510
You've reached success when
people don't shop around.

01:40:05.510 --> 01:40:08.350
They just know that they want
to go straight to your service.

01:40:08.350 --> 01:40:10.060
They want to go straight
to what you offer,

01:40:10.060 --> 01:40:11.960
because it does the job
better than anybody else.

01:40:11.960 --> 01:40:13.790
That's what we call
a purpose brand.

01:40:13.790 --> 01:40:15.320
You want to be a purpose brand

01:40:15.320 --> 01:40:17.940
for what job you're
solving best.

01:40:17.940 --> 01:40:19.690
And I'm going to illustrate
this, the difference

01:40:19.690 --> 01:40:23.350
between talking about the
product you're selling

01:40:23.350 --> 01:40:26.790
and selling your
response to a job.

01:40:26.790 --> 01:40:28.160
If you could show
the first video --

01:40:28.160 --> 01:40:30.840
this is an old Snicker's
commercial.

01:40:30.840 --> 01:40:35.980
&gt;&gt; Can I help you
enjoy that Snicker's?

01:40:38.660 --> 01:40:40.610
&gt;&gt; [Singing] Happy peanuts soar

01:40:40.610 --> 01:40:43.310
over chocolate covered
mountaintops

01:40:43.310 --> 01:40:46.140
and waterfalls of caramel.

01:40:46.140 --> 01:40:51.960
Prancing nougat in the
meadow sings a song

01:40:51.960 --> 01:40:53.720
of satisfaction to the world.

01:40:53.720 --> 01:40:55.020
&gt;&gt; The world!

01:40:55.020 --> 01:40:56.320
&gt;&gt; That's right.

01:40:56.320 --> 01:41:05.320
&gt;&gt; Karen Dillon: Okay, we
heard about prancing nougat

01:41:05.320 --> 01:41:07.070
and waterfalls of caramel.

01:41:07.070 --> 01:41:08.790
Those are all the
features and benefits

01:41:08.790 --> 01:41:12.410
and the quality ingredients
that go into Snicker's.

01:41:12.410 --> 01:41:13.990
Is that exciting
as a commercial?

01:41:13.990 --> 01:41:16.490
Do you think that makes
anybody want to go?

01:41:16.490 --> 01:41:18.840
Put on your own lenses
for your own organization?

01:41:18.840 --> 01:41:20.770
Are you doing a version of this?

01:41:20.770 --> 01:41:23.790
Talking about the
ingredients and the quality

01:41:23.790 --> 01:41:26.990
and all the components
that you know are superior,

01:41:26.990 --> 01:41:30.710
but maybe just add up to a
list of things to offer people.

01:41:30.710 --> 01:41:33.110
Now from a different
perspective, if you put on a job

01:41:33.110 --> 01:41:35.680
to be done lens and you think
about, how are you talking

01:41:35.680 --> 01:41:39.260
to your customer, how are
they seeing you as a solution

01:41:39.260 --> 01:41:40.560
to their job to be done,

01:41:40.560 --> 01:41:42.880
you'll approach it
entirely differently.

01:41:42.880 --> 01:41:45.120
Snicker's now is one
of the bestselling --

01:41:45.120 --> 01:41:48.070
I think it is the bestselling
candy bar in the United States.

01:41:48.070 --> 01:41:52.010
And one critical insight I
think led to that development:

01:41:52.010 --> 01:41:57.730
they recognized when and how
and why -- the job to be done --

01:41:57.730 --> 01:42:00.840
people actually hired
a Snicker's bar.

01:42:00.840 --> 01:42:04.520
It turns out a lot of us hire
it when we're hungry and angry,

01:42:04.520 --> 01:42:07.570
a concept they call
hangry, right?

01:42:07.570 --> 01:42:09.070
It's not necessarily competing

01:42:09.070 --> 01:42:13.020
with Three Musketeers
or any of the others.

01:42:13.020 --> 01:42:15.950
It's competing with
peanuts or food or a meal.

01:42:15.950 --> 01:42:17.660
You're hungry and you
want to be fed quickly

01:42:17.660 --> 01:42:20.360
and you want something that's
going to stop that hangry thing

01:42:20.360 --> 01:42:22.040
from taking over really quickly.

01:42:22.040 --> 01:42:24.610
If you watch in airports, you'll
see lots of people buy Snicker's

01:42:24.610 --> 01:42:25.980
and they think it's
people who are racing

01:42:25.980 --> 01:42:27.740
for planes and haven't had food.

01:42:27.740 --> 01:42:31.340
It's a very different job to be
done than just something sweet

01:42:31.340 --> 01:42:34.150
to fill me with joy
at the moment.

01:42:34.150 --> 01:42:36.090
So this is the approach
they've taken.

01:42:36.090 --> 01:42:38.780
It's a very clear job
to be done communication

01:42:38.780 --> 01:42:41.450
about hiring a Snicker's
bar when you're hangry.

01:42:41.450 --> 01:42:43.960
If you could play the next one.

01:42:43.960 --> 01:42:45.760
&gt;&gt; Hut!

01:42:45.760 --> 01:42:51.240
[ Grunting ]

01:42:51.240 --> 01:42:52.540
&gt;&gt; Come on.

01:42:52.540 --> 01:42:54.570
&gt;&gt; Mike, what is your deal, man?

01:42:54.570 --> 01:42:56.510
&gt;&gt; Oh come on, many, you've
been riding me all day.

01:42:56.510 --> 01:42:57.970
&gt;&gt; Mike, you're playing
like Betty White out there.

01:42:57.970 --> 01:42:59.420
&gt;&gt; That's not what
your girlfriends says.

01:42:59.420 --> 01:43:00.720
&gt;&gt; Betty.

01:43:00.720 --> 01:43:02.020
&gt;&gt; Oh.

01:43:02.020 --> 01:43:03.960
&gt;&gt; Eat a Snicker's.

01:43:03.960 --> 01:43:05.630
Better?

01:43:05.630 --> 01:43:06.930
&gt;&gt; Better.

01:43:06.930 --> 01:43:08.230
&gt;&gt; Hut.

01:43:08.230 --> 01:43:09.530
&gt;&gt; I'm open.

01:43:09.530 --> 01:43:11.040
[ Grunting ]

01:43:11.040 --> 01:43:12.340
&gt;&gt; That hurt.

01:43:12.340 --> 01:43:13.640
&gt;&gt; You're not you
when you're hungry.

01:43:13.640 --> 01:43:15.510
Snicker's satisfies.

01:43:15.510 --> 01:43:18.120
[ Laughter ]

01:43:18.120 --> 01:43:19.420
&gt;&gt; Karen Dillon:
See the difference?

01:43:19.420 --> 01:43:20.890
The fact that we all respond
to that second commercial means

01:43:20.890 --> 01:43:22.430
that we understand that concept

01:43:22.430 --> 01:43:25.140
and we might hire a
Snicker's when we're hangry.

01:43:25.140 --> 01:43:27.440
How are you talking
to your customers?

01:43:27.440 --> 01:43:29.790
And your prospective
customers, and the customers

01:43:29.790 --> 01:43:31.190
that are hiring nothing rather

01:43:31.190 --> 01:43:32.850
than solving their
job to be done?

01:43:32.850 --> 01:43:35.630
Do you know what the
job to be done is

01:43:35.630 --> 01:43:36.930
that you've been hired to do?

01:43:36.930 --> 01:43:39.310
If you don't, I would urge you

01:43:39.310 --> 01:43:40.810
to think long and
hard about that.

01:43:40.810 --> 01:43:43.610
Talk to the people who
already have hired you and talk

01:43:43.610 --> 01:43:47.650
to people who haven't hired you
at all to try to identify that.

01:43:47.650 --> 01:43:49.600
Because once you
have that in mind,

01:43:49.600 --> 01:43:51.690
it can become a real
guiding beacon for all

01:43:51.690 --> 01:43:53.520
of your innovation
efforts and one

01:43:53.520 --> 01:43:56.500
that we believe is far
more likely to succeed

01:43:56.500 --> 01:44:00.840
and not leave you vulnerable to
the hit or miss of innovation.

01:44:00.840 --> 01:44:02.640
Thank you very much.

01:44:02.640 --> 01:44:31.090
[ Applause ]

01:44:31.090 --> 01:44:32.390
Okay.

01:44:32.390 --> 01:44:33.690
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Karen, thank you
for that fantastic presentation.

01:44:33.690 --> 01:44:34.990
&gt;&gt; Karen Dillon: You're welcome.

01:44:34.990 --> 01:44:37.070
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Entertaining,
and you kind of drove us right

01:44:37.070 --> 01:44:41.120
to the intersection
of art and business.

01:44:41.120 --> 01:44:42.420
&gt;&gt; Karen Dillon:

01:44:42.420 --> 01:44:43.720
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: And we're
going to get right to that

01:44:43.720 --> 01:44:45.060
in a second, but let me
introduce our panel first.

01:44:45.060 --> 01:44:47.580
And I'm Jesse Rosen,
president of the League

01:44:47.580 --> 01:44:49.950
of American Orchestras.

01:44:49.950 --> 01:44:53.080
Kevin Shuck runs the
Boulder Philharmonic.

01:44:53.080 --> 01:44:56.590
He is a molecular
biologist by training

01:44:56.590 --> 01:44:58.410
and avid outdoorsperson.

01:44:58.410 --> 01:45:00.160
We'll hear more about that soon.

01:45:00.160 --> 01:45:03.090
Sandi runs the North Carolina
Symphony, also has worked

01:45:03.090 --> 01:45:04.390
with the Seattle Symphony,

01:45:04.390 --> 01:45:06.240
Cleveland Orchestra,
great colleague.

01:45:06.240 --> 01:45:10.990
And Sarah Kirkland Snider, a
composer whose biography reads

01:45:10.990 --> 01:45:13.300
like a Lifetime Achievement
Award.

01:45:13.300 --> 01:45:16.330
She has been performed by every
major orchestra, collaborated

01:45:16.330 --> 01:45:18.060
with every major
artist, commissioned

01:45:18.060 --> 01:45:22.020
by every commissioning source
and an extraordinary talent.

01:45:22.020 --> 01:45:24.900
Thank you and welcome, panel.

01:45:24.900 --> 01:45:26.200
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

01:45:26.200 --> 01:45:28.000
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Yeah.

01:45:28.000 --> 01:45:31.420
[ Applause ]

01:45:31.420 --> 01:45:35.410
Gosh, there's so many
places to jump into this.

01:45:35.410 --> 01:45:38.330
The Snicker's commercial,
the first one

01:45:38.330 --> 01:45:41.640
with the guy singing
actually reminds me

01:45:41.640 --> 01:45:47.260
of orchestra press releases and
brochures from not too long ago.

01:45:47.260 --> 01:45:49.780
Where they just heaped
praise and praise

01:45:49.780 --> 01:45:51.560
and praise upon themselves

01:45:51.560 --> 01:45:54.500
in describing all the ways they
were wonderful in the same way

01:45:54.500 --> 01:45:56.680
that guy was singing
about the Snicker's bar.

01:45:56.680 --> 01:46:00.310
And now of course orchestras
communicate about themselves

01:46:00.310 --> 01:46:02.630
and express themselves
very differently.

01:46:02.630 --> 01:46:04.560
And maybe it's a place
to jump in to pick

01:46:04.560 --> 01:46:09.920
up with Karen's last
question, which is, you know,

01:46:09.920 --> 01:46:12.120
how has our job changed?

01:46:12.120 --> 01:46:16.450
And there was certainly a
time I think when we thought

01:46:16.450 --> 01:46:20.380
about orchestras were doing
products and services.

01:46:20.380 --> 01:46:23.050
We created concerts
and people came.

01:46:23.050 --> 01:46:25.600
Now we kind of think we
maybe have a different job.

01:46:25.600 --> 01:46:28.200
And Sandi, why don't you start
us off, maybe with a reflection

01:46:28.200 --> 01:46:30.500
on where we've been and
where we're going to?

01:46:30.500 --> 01:46:32.010
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: Actually I'd

01:46:32.010 --> 01:46:33.830
like to reflect on
the presentation.

01:46:33.830 --> 01:46:36.500
What business am I in?

01:46:36.500 --> 01:46:39.130
Or what's the job
I'm trying to sell?

01:46:39.130 --> 01:46:43.450
So I believe that in the case
of the North Carolina Symphony,

01:46:43.450 --> 01:46:47.750
we are not seeking to
be the Chicago Symphony

01:46:47.750 --> 01:46:51.030
or the Cleveland Orchestra
or the Berlin Philharmonic.

01:46:51.030 --> 01:46:55.440
We are seeking to be the
orchestra of our community.

01:46:55.440 --> 01:46:59.000
In our case, we serve the
entire state of North Carolina

01:46:59.000 --> 01:47:01.560
through orchestral
performance as well

01:47:01.560 --> 01:47:05.330
as our music education series.

01:47:05.330 --> 01:47:14.570
And so we want to provide music
that is unique to our area,

01:47:14.570 --> 01:47:19.540
to our orchestra, because you
can get the greatest Beethoven

01:47:19.540 --> 01:47:23.240
symphony performed by the
Berlin Philharmonic --

01:47:23.240 --> 01:47:24.860
they do that really well.

01:47:24.860 --> 01:47:29.800
But what we do very, very
well is produce concerts

01:47:29.800 --> 01:47:33.220
that are meaningful to a North
Carolinian, and you will hear

01:47:33.220 --> 01:47:36.350
that tomorrow night
at our performances

01:47:36.350 --> 01:47:38.170
at the Kennedy Center.

01:47:38.170 --> 01:47:40.630
So my job is to find
those tentacles,

01:47:40.630 --> 01:47:45.580
to find those opportunities
to connect with our community

01:47:45.580 --> 01:47:47.520
in unique and different ways.

01:47:47.520 --> 01:47:48.820
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: And is

01:47:48.820 --> 01:47:51.550
that a relatively new
development in orchestras?

01:47:51.550 --> 01:47:53.700
We've been in the field a while.

01:47:53.700 --> 01:47:57.710
Has it kind of been
that way for a bit?

01:47:57.710 --> 01:47:59.250
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: I
came to North Carolina

01:47:59.250 --> 01:48:00.550
from the Cleveland Orchestra.

01:48:00.550 --> 01:48:06.460
I don't know that we spent a lot
of time talking about connecting

01:48:06.460 --> 01:48:09.190
to the musical DNA
of our community.

01:48:09.190 --> 01:48:10.520
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Right.

01:48:10.520 --> 01:48:12.180
And Kevin, how about you?

01:48:12.180 --> 01:48:15.820
How do you think about the
job of orchestras today?

01:48:15.820 --> 01:48:17.120
&gt;&gt; Kevin Shuck: Sure.

01:48:17.120 --> 01:48:18.750
I think there's a lot of
resonance in how we think

01:48:18.750 --> 01:48:20.510
about it at the Boulder
Philharmonic

01:48:20.510 --> 01:48:22.360
with what Sandi just
said in North Carolina.

01:48:22.360 --> 01:48:26.260
It's that well, in our case,
about eight years ago --

01:48:26.260 --> 01:48:30.000
so you're asking how
recently these kinds

01:48:30.000 --> 01:48:32.860
of thoughts have been
in the orchestra field.

01:48:32.860 --> 01:48:35.280
About eight years ago our board
had done a strategic planning

01:48:35.280 --> 01:48:38.610
exercise, whereas our
goal as an orchestra was

01:48:38.610 --> 01:48:40.050
to reflect those qualities

01:48:40.050 --> 01:48:42.990
that make our community
unique and special.

01:48:42.990 --> 01:48:45.630
Every community is
unique in different ways.

01:48:45.630 --> 01:48:49.990
And so I think in our case we
were just looking to tie music

01:48:49.990 --> 01:48:54.700
into in our case what
makes Boulder unique.

01:48:54.700 --> 01:48:58.400
And you know, I think that's
very much part of the Zeitgeist.

01:48:58.400 --> 01:49:01.460
It's what at League of American
Orchestras conference we're

01:49:01.460 --> 01:49:03.210
talking about a lot these days.

01:49:03.210 --> 01:49:05.610
And it's good to see
orchestras like this week

01:49:05.610 --> 01:49:08.800
that are having some
success in those areas.

01:49:08.800 --> 01:49:10.320
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald:
We also codified --

01:49:10.320 --> 01:49:13.650
our board codified our
point of view on programing

01:49:13.650 --> 01:49:18.250
to be uniquely North
Carolina-focused

01:49:18.250 --> 01:49:20.370
and of national significance.

01:49:20.370 --> 01:49:25.290
But we've been doing this
work in the early 2000's.

01:49:25.290 --> 01:49:31.960
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: And Sarah,
a different kind of person

01:49:31.960 --> 01:49:34.140
than Sandy and Kevin
and Karen and myself.

01:49:34.140 --> 01:49:35.680
You're a creator.

01:49:35.680 --> 01:49:39.240
And so how do you
think about this?

01:49:39.240 --> 01:49:40.850
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider:
How do I feel about --

01:49:40.850 --> 01:49:42.150
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: How do you think

01:49:42.150 --> 01:49:43.820
about the job you
do as a composer?

01:49:43.820 --> 01:49:45.990
And has that changed for you?

01:49:45.990 --> 01:49:47.290
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider: Yeah.

01:49:47.290 --> 01:49:53.320
Well, as a composer, I
think what drew me to music

01:49:53.320 --> 01:49:56.790
from the very beginning
was the power of music

01:49:56.790 --> 01:49:59.570
to communicate and
express emotion.

01:49:59.570 --> 01:50:03.190
And as a child, I was just
utterly fascinated by that.

01:50:03.190 --> 01:50:06.010
And still to this day
I feel that my job is

01:50:06.010 --> 01:50:11.570
to communicate something with
an audience to put something,

01:50:11.570 --> 01:50:15.410
a feeling that you
can't put into words.

01:50:15.410 --> 01:50:19.240
That's what music
can accomplish.

01:50:19.240 --> 01:50:23.730
So yeah, I really see my job
as being one of communication,

01:50:23.730 --> 01:50:27.150
and that's not necessarily
true for every composer,

01:50:27.150 --> 01:50:29.940
but for me it definitely
feels that way.

01:50:29.940 --> 01:50:31.240
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Great.

01:50:31.240 --> 01:50:35.150
And I'm kind of curious,
thinking about some

01:50:35.150 --> 01:50:38.810
of these changes that
are taking place.

01:50:38.810 --> 01:50:41.410
The question Karen poses
in her presentation

01:50:41.410 --> 01:50:44.420
about how do you know,
and how do you come

01:50:44.420 --> 01:50:48.140
to understand your
constituents, your public?

01:50:48.140 --> 01:50:51.130
And in the arts, this
is kind of a little bit

01:50:51.130 --> 01:50:52.890
of a different question
than it is in business,

01:50:52.890 --> 01:50:56.010
because after all, we're
not exactly prepared to give

01:50:56.010 --> 01:50:59.380
up everything we do in order
to become something else

01:50:59.380 --> 01:51:00.680
because it's more profitable.

01:51:00.680 --> 01:51:02.450
That's not our thing.

01:51:02.450 --> 01:51:06.540
So Kevin, talk a little
bit about this question

01:51:06.540 --> 01:51:08.920
of how do we balance
what we come

01:51:08.920 --> 01:51:10.220
to know an audience is looking

01:51:10.220 --> 01:51:14.580
for with what we feel is
somehow defining of who we are.

01:51:14.580 --> 01:51:15.880
What can change?

01:51:15.880 --> 01:51:17.180
What can't change?

01:51:17.180 --> 01:51:18.480
&gt;&gt; Kevin Shuck: Sure.

01:51:18.480 --> 01:51:20.980
Well, the first thing about
the job that is to be done,

01:51:20.980 --> 01:51:25.100
I think with orchestra concerts,
I think it's a challenge

01:51:25.100 --> 01:51:27.650
because there are
different segments coming

01:51:27.650 --> 01:51:31.010
with different jobs to be
done in a single concert.

01:51:31.010 --> 01:51:34.020
So that makes it difficult to
balance all of these things

01:51:34.020 --> 01:51:37.630
and to come up with a
satisfying experience.

01:51:37.630 --> 01:51:40.090
But it is also I think
a great potential

01:51:40.090 --> 01:51:41.930
for a very rich experience.

01:51:41.930 --> 01:51:44.640
And what I mean by that is
there are people that are coming

01:51:44.640 --> 01:51:46.660
for the sole purpose
that they want

01:51:46.660 --> 01:51:50.350
to hear the great live jukebox
for this music they know,

01:51:50.350 --> 01:51:51.940
they've learned and they love.

01:51:51.940 --> 01:51:54.060
And I think that's the
traditional job that we think

01:51:54.060 --> 01:51:55.360
of orchestras as doing.

01:51:55.360 --> 01:51:58.290
Well, you can still do that and
at the same time be thinking

01:51:58.290 --> 01:52:02.080
about what are the social
reasons that people are there.

01:52:02.080 --> 01:52:06.480
And I think there's
a lot of resonance

01:52:06.480 --> 01:52:07.780
to what Sarah was saying

01:52:07.780 --> 01:52:11.550
about the emotional
resonance of music.

01:52:11.550 --> 01:52:15.630
I think orchestras are uniquely
positioned to create community.

01:52:15.630 --> 01:52:20.470
In our current world where it
is highway, suburbia, fast food,

01:52:20.470 --> 01:52:23.160
these things, people are looking
for a place where you can come

01:52:23.160 --> 01:52:25.220
and there is an authentic
connection.

01:52:25.220 --> 01:52:28.760
Orchestras are uniquely
positioned to do this

01:52:28.760 --> 01:52:31.600
because we are bringing together
people in a shared space

01:52:31.600 --> 01:52:33.180
for a shared experience.

01:52:33.180 --> 01:52:36.020
It's something very
different from the day-to-day,

01:52:36.020 --> 01:52:40.070
and I think that that is
something that we can harness

01:52:40.070 --> 01:52:45.530
as organizations to really
create something very special.

01:52:45.530 --> 01:52:50.710
And so as far as the job to be
done, I think that you know,

01:52:50.710 --> 01:52:52.910
certainly there's
this relaxation

01:52:52.910 --> 01:52:54.590
or leisure time bubble.

01:52:54.590 --> 01:52:56.740
And so we think, who are
we competing against?

01:52:56.740 --> 01:52:58.600
We're competing against Netflix,

01:52:58.600 --> 01:53:00.430
we're competing against
the couch.

01:53:00.430 --> 01:53:03.500
So really when you look
at this leisure bubble,

01:53:03.500 --> 01:53:05.990
you're really talking about
there's a subset of that

01:53:05.990 --> 01:53:08.280
which is in some way
people are looking

01:53:08.280 --> 01:53:11.030
for something that's more
fulfilling or enriching

01:53:11.030 --> 01:53:14.340
or special or has a night
out component to it.

01:53:14.340 --> 01:53:18.100
And so I always think that our
biggest struggle is growing the

01:53:18.100 --> 01:53:20.930
piece of that leisure
time relaxation pie

01:53:20.930 --> 01:53:24.670
that people are looking for
those kind of quality outlets.

01:53:24.670 --> 01:53:27.930
And so I think that leads a
lot of the thinking that we do

01:53:27.930 --> 01:53:30.410
about how are we going to
get people into concerts.

01:53:30.410 --> 01:53:32.020
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: So I
know a lot of people

01:53:32.020 --> 01:53:36.170
who would violently disagree
with the idea that going

01:53:36.170 --> 01:53:37.610
to an orchestra concert's
a great way

01:53:37.610 --> 01:53:38.910
to be together with
other people.

01:53:38.910 --> 01:53:40.670
I mean after all,
it's a terrible time.

01:53:40.670 --> 01:53:41.970
It's 8:00 at night.

01:53:41.970 --> 01:53:43.680
You have to rush through
dinner, you get home late,

01:53:43.680 --> 01:53:45.650
you have to listen to music,
some of it you might like

01:53:45.650 --> 01:53:47.750
and some of it you
might not like.

01:53:47.750 --> 01:53:51.340
And it's really expensive and
you can't talk, you can't drink

01:53:51.340 --> 01:53:55.040
and it's formal and
rigid and uncomfortable,

01:53:55.040 --> 01:53:57.380
unlike most other
performing arts experiences.

01:53:57.380 --> 01:53:59.350
So unless I'm --

01:53:59.350 --> 01:54:03.050
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: Where
do I buy a ticket for this?

01:54:03.050 --> 01:54:05.090
[ Laughter ]

01:54:05.090 --> 01:54:06.390
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: I think
there might be more than one

01:54:06.390 --> 01:54:07.690
or two people who feel that way.

01:54:07.690 --> 01:54:10.300
So how does an orchestra
confront some

01:54:10.300 --> 01:54:13.550
of these very changing
ways that people feel

01:54:13.550 --> 01:54:16.180
about going to concerns?

01:54:16.180 --> 01:54:18.510
&gt;&gt; Kevin Shuck: Well, you've
ticked off a lot of barriers

01:54:18.510 --> 01:54:21.510
that we are always looking
at and talking about.

01:54:21.510 --> 01:54:25.020
I think one way we
think about it is,

01:54:25.020 --> 01:54:27.010
how can you put out
the welcome mat.

01:54:27.010 --> 01:54:30.940
Because yes, if a newcomer
to the performing arts,

01:54:30.940 --> 01:54:33.170
orchestras in particular,
is just looking at it,

01:54:33.170 --> 01:54:36.950
all of those negatives are
just too easy to think of.

01:54:36.950 --> 01:54:38.970
So instead we try
to think about,

01:54:38.970 --> 01:54:41.080
what are the entry points, what
are the doorways we can create,

01:54:41.080 --> 01:54:43.920
what are the welcome
mats we can put out?

01:54:43.920 --> 01:54:46.560
And so in our case at
the Boulder Philharmonic

01:54:46.560 --> 01:54:50.850
in Colorado, I mentioned
that we are trying

01:54:50.850 --> 01:54:53.250
to reflect the qualities that
make our community special.

01:54:53.250 --> 01:54:57.650
And so a lot of times that means
meeting people where they are.

01:54:57.650 --> 01:55:00.710
In Boulder, that usually
means on a trail somewhere.

01:55:00.710 --> 01:55:04.870
I think last week it was the
city with the highest rate

01:55:04.870 --> 01:55:07.000
of exercising or
something in the country.

01:55:07.000 --> 01:55:09.790
It's very overachieving
in many dimensions.

01:55:09.790 --> 01:55:16.470
And so in our case, we thought,
okay, well how do we meet people

01:55:16.470 --> 01:55:19.870
on their turf so to speak and
create a welcome mat there?

01:55:19.870 --> 01:55:26.450
And in our 2013-2014 season
we were exploring works

01:55:26.450 --> 01:55:28.330
that were inspired
by the natural world.

01:55:28.330 --> 01:55:31.250
When you come to Boulder,
that's one of the first things

01:55:31.250 --> 01:55:34.250
that you notice is we have
this very scenic backdrop,

01:55:34.250 --> 01:55:36.290
and that's what draws
a lot of people there

01:55:36.290 --> 01:55:38.560
and that's what people
are actively enjoying.

01:55:38.560 --> 01:55:40.030
So that's part of your
culture and that's

01:55:40.030 --> 01:55:41.980
where people are spending
their leisure time

01:55:41.980 --> 01:55:43.330
and that's what their
interests are.

01:55:43.330 --> 01:55:46.050
How can you then convert that
into a welcome mat to get people

01:55:46.050 --> 01:55:47.760
into the concert hall?

01:55:47.760 --> 01:55:52.310
So since we had a list or
repertoire of composers

01:55:52.310 --> 01:55:53.700
that were inspired by music,

01:55:53.700 --> 01:55:57.020
we were commissioning new
works along this vein as well,

01:55:57.020 --> 01:55:58.800
we had the crazy idea to reach

01:55:58.800 --> 01:56:01.170
out to our city open
space department

01:56:01.170 --> 01:56:02.920
which is a big deal in town.

01:56:02.920 --> 01:56:05.580
And I wrote them a
letter basically saying,

01:56:05.580 --> 01:56:08.010
"We're performing music
inspired by nature.

01:56:08.010 --> 01:56:09.310
I think we should collaborate."

01:56:09.310 --> 01:56:13.750
And I went ahead and mentioned
a few possibilities for this,

01:56:13.750 --> 01:56:16.890
thinking that they'd either
just laugh me aside --

01:56:16.890 --> 01:56:18.440
but within two days
I was meeting

01:56:18.440 --> 01:56:21.280
with the entire senior staff
of the open space department.

01:56:21.280 --> 01:56:22.780
Because they said,
"That's exactly what we're

01:56:22.780 --> 01:56:24.080
interested in."

01:56:24.080 --> 01:56:27.050
So we've been using our
collaboration with them

01:56:27.050 --> 01:56:28.710
to create that welcome mat,

01:56:28.710 --> 01:56:32.610
to kind of put all
those negatives aside

01:56:32.610 --> 01:56:36.430
and actually show that it can
be something that is social.

01:56:36.430 --> 01:56:41.570
People on the trail are enjoying
conversations, sharing music.

01:56:41.570 --> 01:56:43.120
And when they come
to the concert hall,

01:56:43.120 --> 01:56:44.420
it's the same as well.

01:56:44.420 --> 01:56:47.280
During intermission,
people are buzzing.

01:56:47.280 --> 01:56:52.040
I met people that I met
on a hike that we do.

01:56:52.040 --> 01:56:53.730
Then I'll see them at the
concert hall and it's like,

01:56:53.730 --> 01:56:55.030
"Oh that's just amazing.

01:56:55.030 --> 01:56:58.720
When I heard that piece, I
could just see the geese flying

01:56:58.720 --> 01:57:03.270
over the Sawhill
Pond," for example.

01:57:03.270 --> 01:57:05.130
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: Kevin
mentioned collaboration

01:57:05.130 --> 01:57:11.210
and I think that is an area
where we invest a good amount

01:57:11.210 --> 01:57:16.110
of our time to create
programs where we collaborate

01:57:16.110 --> 01:57:18.130
with another organization.

01:57:18.130 --> 01:57:24.120
One example is the Museum of
Natural Sciences in Raleigh.

01:57:24.120 --> 01:57:30.120
The museum created visuals that
celebrated the 100th anniversary

01:57:30.120 --> 01:57:34.230
of the state parks
of North Carolina.

01:57:34.230 --> 01:57:37.470
We performed the four seasons.

01:57:37.470 --> 01:57:42.060
And together, this performance
which couldn't resonate

01:57:42.060 --> 01:57:46.200
in any other state
than North Carolina,

01:57:46.200 --> 01:57:48.110
our audience members --

01:57:48.110 --> 01:57:51.990
which expanded to the museum's
audience members as well

01:57:51.990 --> 01:57:54.930
and those people just
interested in the state parks --

01:57:54.930 --> 01:57:57.400
brought together the sum of all
those parts, something bigger

01:57:57.400 --> 01:58:02.640
than any one of us could have
been, and create a performance

01:58:02.640 --> 01:58:05.400
that can't be replicated
by something else.

01:58:05.400 --> 01:58:11.050
Listening on the radio -- how
old of me to mention a radio.

01:58:11.050 --> 01:58:13.090
[ Laughter ]

01:58:13.090 --> 01:58:15.400
Or you know, watching
Netflix or doing nothing.

01:58:15.400 --> 01:58:17.290
You had to be there
in that space

01:58:17.290 --> 01:58:20.760
to see those three critical
elements brought together

01:58:20.760 --> 01:58:22.120
in performance.

01:58:22.120 --> 01:58:23.730
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: I love it.

01:58:23.730 --> 01:58:25.540
And Sarah, you've
created a piece

01:58:25.540 --> 01:58:28.350
that the North Carolina Symphony
is going to play in a couple

01:58:28.350 --> 01:58:30.490
of nights, on Wednesday night.

01:58:30.490 --> 01:58:33.200
And I understand that that
came together in a way

01:58:33.200 --> 01:58:35.690
that also really
brought people together.

01:58:35.690 --> 01:58:37.330
Could you talk a little
bit more about that?

01:58:37.330 --> 01:58:38.630
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider: Sure.

01:58:38.630 --> 01:58:41.760
Yes, so a few years ago Martin
Share came to me and said,

01:58:41.760 --> 01:58:44.940
"I understand that you have
some family connections

01:58:44.940 --> 01:58:46.240
to North Carolina.

01:58:46.240 --> 01:58:48.850
Would you be interesting for
writing a piece about that?"

01:58:48.850 --> 01:58:50.590
And I jumped at the opportunity

01:58:50.590 --> 01:58:52.720
because North Carolina
has always felt

01:58:52.720 --> 01:58:56.370
like my spiritual home,
my ancestral home.

01:58:56.370 --> 01:58:58.980
My family had been
there for 13 generations

01:58:58.980 --> 01:59:02.650
and my father was the first to
leave and he worked in New York,

01:59:02.650 --> 01:59:03.950
so we lived in New Jersey.

01:59:03.950 --> 01:59:06.280
But we would spend a lot
of time during the year

01:59:06.280 --> 01:59:08.250
in North Carolina and
I really thought of it

01:59:08.250 --> 01:59:10.950
as this place where I belonged.

01:59:10.950 --> 01:59:15.170
So I was very excited to write
this piece, and I thought,

01:59:15.170 --> 01:59:16.580
what should it be about?

01:59:16.580 --> 01:59:20.490
I thought it should be
about those feelings

01:59:20.490 --> 01:59:22.760
of what does home mean?

01:59:22.760 --> 01:59:24.340
And what is a longing for home?

01:59:24.340 --> 01:59:25.640
What does that feel like?

01:59:25.640 --> 01:59:27.140
What is that about?

01:59:27.140 --> 01:59:28.440
You know, is it about family?

01:59:28.440 --> 01:59:29.740
Is it about landscape?

01:59:29.740 --> 01:59:32.810
Is it about the things
that you did there?

01:59:32.810 --> 01:59:36.390
So I decided that I would try to
write a piece about the nature

01:59:36.390 --> 01:59:41.920
of memory and longing
for a place in your past.

01:59:41.920 --> 01:59:44.770
And I had this idea that
it might be interesting

01:59:44.770 --> 01:59:49.550
to combine it with a film
component, because so much

01:59:49.550 --> 01:59:53.920
of my memory of North Carolina
was sense memory based.

01:59:53.920 --> 01:59:55.700
You know, the way things looked,

01:59:55.700 --> 01:59:57.590
the way the sunlight
cast shadows

01:59:57.590 --> 02:00:03.010
on my grandparents' patio,
the way that the town looked.

02:00:03.010 --> 02:00:05.180
The things that I
did with my family --

02:00:05.180 --> 02:00:06.870
I thought it would be
interesting to look at some

02:00:06.870 --> 02:00:09.960
of that from an abstract,
cinematic perspective

02:00:09.960 --> 02:00:12.790
and to have that
accompany the music

02:00:12.790 --> 02:00:19.400
so that it would be this kind
of dreamy exploration somewhere

02:00:19.400 --> 02:00:21.940
between memory and a dream.

02:00:21.940 --> 02:00:24.520
But one that the audience
would have some kind

02:00:24.520 --> 02:00:28.690
of reference point for
the emotionally journey

02:00:28.690 --> 02:00:30.910
that the music was exploring.

02:00:30.910 --> 02:00:33.670
So we went down to
North Carolina

02:00:33.670 --> 02:00:35.960
and shot some footage actually

02:00:35.960 --> 02:00:39.250
of my own children
recreating some of my memories

02:00:39.250 --> 02:00:42.350
and my father's memories.

02:00:42.350 --> 02:00:46.690
Yeah, so it became
a real sort of look

02:00:46.690 --> 02:00:49.980
at small-town life
in North Carolina.

02:00:49.980 --> 02:00:53.230
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: And it's been
performed already, right?

02:00:53.230 --> 02:00:54.530
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider: Yeah,

02:00:54.530 --> 02:00:57.140
they performed it several times
last year in North Carolina.

02:00:57.140 --> 02:00:58.810
And also in New Jersey.

02:00:58.810 --> 02:01:00.430
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald:
Your hometown, yes.

02:01:00.430 --> 02:01:02.280
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider: Yeah,
the other co-commissioners,

02:01:02.280 --> 02:01:05.660
the Princeton Symphony
which was the actual place

02:01:05.660 --> 02:01:09.720
of my birth and growing up.

02:01:09.720 --> 02:01:11.020
So that was neat as well.

02:01:11.020 --> 02:01:12.950
But yeah, they performed it too.

02:01:12.950 --> 02:01:14.250
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Yeah.

02:01:14.250 --> 02:01:15.640
And how did the origin
of the work --

02:01:15.640 --> 02:01:18.970
I mean, when it was finally
performed, what kind of impact?

02:01:18.970 --> 02:01:21.950
What was the significance
of all that led

02:01:21.950 --> 02:01:25.010
up to creating the piece when
it finally came to the public?

02:01:25.010 --> 02:01:27.170
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider: Well
that was what was so remarkable,

02:01:27.170 --> 02:01:29.880
was having all of these
friends and family

02:01:29.880 --> 02:01:31.620
from North Carolina
come to the premier.

02:01:31.620 --> 02:01:34.800
And they felt so
emotionally connected

02:01:34.800 --> 02:01:36.610
to the piece and what they saw.

02:01:36.610 --> 02:01:38.340
And for them it really resonated

02:01:38.340 --> 02:01:41.190
with their own memories
of North Carolina.

02:01:41.190 --> 02:01:43.580
So that was really
extraordinary, just the senses

02:01:43.580 --> 02:01:47.530
of community that was
brought about by the project.

02:01:47.530 --> 02:01:49.830
A number of the people had
participated in the making

02:01:49.830 --> 02:01:52.380
of the film, had recreated a lot

02:01:52.380 --> 02:01:55.400
of these social scenes
that we shot.

02:01:55.400 --> 02:01:59.890
So it really felt like this
galvanizing collective memory

02:01:59.890 --> 02:02:02.270
exercise in a sense.

02:02:02.270 --> 02:02:03.840
And that was really
special, yeah.

02:02:03.840 --> 02:02:05.800
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: And
we were able to perform it

02:02:05.800 --> 02:02:10.330
in the community that evoked
all of these memories.

02:02:10.330 --> 02:02:12.120
So it was very North Carolina.

02:02:12.120 --> 02:02:16.100
And we've had two performances
of it there and performed it

02:02:16.100 --> 02:02:19.070
in other locations including
our headquarter hall in Raleigh.

02:02:19.070 --> 02:02:20.370
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Right.

02:02:20.370 --> 02:02:21.670
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider:
And that's what's amazing,

02:02:21.670 --> 02:02:22.970
is actually a lot of people from
North Carolina are traveling

02:02:22.970 --> 02:02:25.180
up for this performance.

02:02:25.180 --> 02:02:26.480
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: Yeah.

02:02:26.480 --> 02:02:27.780
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider:
They feel a sense of ownership

02:02:27.780 --> 02:02:29.080
and investment in it,
which is really special.

02:02:29.080 --> 02:02:32.850
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald:
Sarah is a star.

02:02:32.850 --> 02:02:34.300
[Laughs] I just hear a
job in that right away:

02:02:34.300 --> 02:02:36.520
make me feel proud of
being a North Carolinian.

02:02:36.520 --> 02:02:38.970
And you've checked
all those boxes.

02:02:38.970 --> 02:02:41.070
It's maybe about the music,
but the music is a way

02:02:41.070 --> 02:02:42.610
to achieve the progress, right?

02:02:42.610 --> 02:02:43.910
Make me feel proud of it.

02:02:43.910 --> 02:02:46.600
I hear success and a job there.

02:02:46.600 --> 02:02:47.900
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland
Snider: Thanks.

02:02:47.900 --> 02:02:49.200
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: So I'm
thinking back to Karen's slide,

02:02:49.200 --> 02:02:52.140
the one that showed
92 out of how many?

02:02:52.140 --> 02:02:54.720
&gt;&gt; Karen Dillon: 92 out
of 20,000 products, yeah.

02:02:54.720 --> 02:02:57.860
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: So listening
to you, it sounds like we're

02:02:57.860 --> 02:03:02.570
in the 92 camp, that somehow
we've figured this out.

02:03:02.570 --> 02:03:03.870
&gt;&gt; Karen Dillon: Right.

02:03:03.870 --> 02:03:05.170
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: I mean, people
have written so many books

02:03:05.170 --> 02:03:08.260
about innovation, it must
be hard and complicated.

02:03:08.260 --> 02:03:12.640
So I'm curious, as you
go through these changes,

02:03:12.640 --> 02:03:14.060
is there any tension
around this?

02:03:14.060 --> 02:03:16.000
Or is it just you've
got it all figured out?

02:03:16.000 --> 02:03:19.140
&gt;&gt; Kevin Shuck: I think
there's inevitably tension

02:03:19.140 --> 02:03:23.440
when you go outside of the
box of a traditional art form.

02:03:23.440 --> 02:03:28.250
I think that's just kind
of taken for granted.

02:03:28.250 --> 02:03:33.430
But, well, two things about the
words both innovation and risk.

02:03:33.430 --> 02:03:35.480
I really don't like to
think that we're trying

02:03:35.480 --> 02:03:37.060
to innovate all the time.

02:03:37.060 --> 02:03:40.040
That's actually not kind
of the vocabulary we use.

02:03:40.040 --> 02:03:41.370
We're instead trying
to be creative.

02:03:41.370 --> 02:03:45.880
And I think that it's about
looking for the connections,

02:03:45.880 --> 02:03:49.540
looking for ways that music
can reach different parts

02:03:49.540 --> 02:03:50.840
of your community.

02:03:50.840 --> 02:03:53.070
In doing that, the
end result is often

02:03:53.070 --> 02:03:55.730
that your programming
is innovative.

02:03:55.730 --> 02:04:00.090
But we're not pursuing that
in and of itself as our goal,

02:04:00.090 --> 02:04:02.160
because I think that leads
you down the rabbit hole

02:04:02.160 --> 02:04:04.320
where you could be doing
things that are different just

02:04:04.320 --> 02:04:06.510
for the sake of being different.

02:04:06.510 --> 02:04:11.040
Rather than if you are
following from the standpoint

02:04:11.040 --> 02:04:13.910
of where the art takes you,
where that creativity takes you,

02:04:13.910 --> 02:04:16.740
then it leads you into
a more authentic place

02:04:16.740 --> 02:04:18.530
that might happen
to be innovative.

02:04:18.530 --> 02:04:22.890
And I think that as far
as, is there a tension --

02:04:22.890 --> 02:04:27.760
I mean, there are certainly
traditional audience members

02:04:27.760 --> 02:04:30.210
who are happy with the
music just the way it is.

02:04:30.210 --> 02:04:33.540
In talking to a lot of
people I hear this, "Well,

02:04:33.540 --> 02:04:36.170
I understand why you're
doing that," because they see

02:04:36.170 --> 02:04:39.360
that our audiences are
growing by leaps and bounds.

02:04:39.360 --> 02:04:42.770
So they see the effect of it,
they are invested in the music,

02:04:42.770 --> 02:04:44.470
they want it to be successful.

02:04:44.470 --> 02:04:46.810
So they get behind it.

02:04:46.810 --> 02:04:49.460
Even though that's not the
job I guess they're looking

02:04:49.460 --> 02:04:51.990
for the concert to
fulfill for them,

02:04:51.990 --> 02:04:54.740
we're able to bring them along,
because they see the effect.

02:04:54.740 --> 02:04:57.370
They see that it is
done in a way again

02:04:57.370 --> 02:04:58.960
which is authentic
and not gimmicky.

02:04:58.960 --> 02:05:00.900
Which again, I think if
you focus on just trying

02:05:00.900 --> 02:05:04.680
to be innovative, that's where
you can end up a lot of time.

02:05:04.680 --> 02:05:07.720
And so that's how we've
been able to manage that.

02:05:07.720 --> 02:05:09.020
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: I
would just argue though,

02:05:09.020 --> 02:05:10.320
that might be doing
the job for them.

02:05:10.320 --> 02:05:12.040
The job for them might
be, "I want to be a pillar

02:05:12.040 --> 02:05:13.960
of this community and
this is the way I feel."

02:05:13.960 --> 02:05:17.100
If you think narrowly
about what the job is,

02:05:17.100 --> 02:05:20.070
again you think innovation is
a rabbit hole, it might be.

02:05:20.070 --> 02:05:24.960
But if you think about the job
and you only add or focus on how

02:05:24.960 --> 02:05:27.680
to make that experience
better, they still feel

02:05:27.680 --> 02:05:28.980
like a pillar of the community.

02:05:28.980 --> 02:05:30.280
Maybe you've done it better

02:05:30.280 --> 02:05:31.580
because you're a
growing organization.

02:05:31.580 --> 02:05:33.090
It's not an either/or.

02:05:33.090 --> 02:05:37.150
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: So if
the job of orchestras,

02:05:37.150 --> 02:05:40.460
or among the jobs are creating
experiences that connect

02:05:40.460 --> 02:05:43.000
with people, connect
with community

02:05:43.000 --> 02:05:46.480
and move beyond the
transactional product,

02:05:46.480 --> 02:05:50.300
we're selling the concert --
so is this good for business?

02:05:50.300 --> 02:05:51.870
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: Certainly.

02:05:51.870 --> 02:05:54.080
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Because you're
running businesses too, right?

02:05:54.080 --> 02:05:55.380
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: Yeah, yeah.

02:05:55.380 --> 02:05:56.680
We're running business
and we worry a lot --

02:05:56.680 --> 02:05:58.330
I spend a lot of time
worrying about risk

02:05:58.330 --> 02:06:01.900
and limiting the risk,
the financial risk.

02:06:01.900 --> 02:06:07.820
And so we've come up
with some solutions

02:06:07.820 --> 02:06:11.030
that reduce the risk for us.

02:06:11.030 --> 02:06:15.210
So for example, everyone
wants the millennial audience

02:06:15.210 --> 02:06:19.020
and the illusive
millennial audience.

02:06:19.020 --> 02:06:23.770
And so there was a time
we would put on a concert

02:06:23.770 --> 02:06:26.350
that had hybrid music in it

02:06:26.350 --> 02:06:30.820
and our marketing department
would be in the corner stewing

02:06:30.820 --> 02:06:33.540
about selling tickets and where
are they going to come out,

02:06:33.540 --> 02:06:37.550
and let's get food trucks
and let's sell martinis.

02:06:37.550 --> 02:06:41.570
Moving away from actually
what our business is.

02:06:41.570 --> 02:06:46.380
And a couple of years ago we
decided, let's take that money,

02:06:46.380 --> 02:06:49.770
let's eliminate the tension
within the organization.

02:06:49.770 --> 02:06:54.300
Let's talk to our
musicians about a concept

02:06:54.300 --> 02:06:59.900
of giving them money to develop
a program that would be held

02:06:59.900 --> 02:07:06.220
in for example a club in
our case in downtown Raleigh

02:07:06.220 --> 02:07:07.660
that I would not go to.

02:07:07.660 --> 02:07:09.910
Well, maybe Sarah
would go to it,

02:07:09.910 --> 02:07:11.860
but most of us might not go this

02:07:11.860 --> 02:07:15.190
because we wouldn't even
know about the club.

02:07:15.190 --> 02:07:18.920
The marketing would
not darken my door.

02:07:18.920 --> 02:07:23.170
And you know, can we
be more successful

02:07:23.170 --> 02:07:26.100
at reaching an audience
that we're not reaching

02:07:26.100 --> 02:07:28.780
in a traditional performance?

02:07:28.780 --> 02:07:30.920
Close up and personal
with our musicians

02:07:30.920 --> 02:07:32.780
who have chosen the repertoire
they're going to play,

02:07:32.780 --> 02:07:34.280
who have used their
social network

02:07:34.280 --> 02:07:36.310
to bring people to the concert?

02:07:36.310 --> 02:07:38.560
And let's not charge
a ticket price.

02:07:38.560 --> 02:07:42.050
Let's have a cover charge.

02:07:42.050 --> 02:07:45.800
And so those reduce
the financial risk.

02:07:45.800 --> 02:07:48.460
Let's not put these in big giant
halls, because they don't belong

02:07:48.460 --> 02:07:49.910
in big giant concert halls,

02:07:49.910 --> 02:07:53.140
and stew about filling
all of those seats.

02:07:53.140 --> 02:07:55.980
And let's make the
connection that way.

02:07:55.980 --> 02:08:01.250
And so that's an example of
it making sense both in terms

02:08:01.250 --> 02:08:07.040
of resource and inspiration, I
posit to our musicians as well.

02:08:07.040 --> 02:08:08.840
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: And are
you seeing positive changes

02:08:08.840 --> 02:08:12.440
in attendance at the
North Carolina Symphony?

02:08:12.440 --> 02:08:13.990
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald:
Over time, we have, yes.

02:08:13.990 --> 02:08:19.080
Yes. We've grown our
ticket revenue by $1 million

02:08:19.080 --> 02:08:21.420
in this planning cycle
that we're in right now.

02:08:21.420 --> 02:08:24.100
We're at the end of a
five-year planning cycle.

02:08:24.100 --> 02:08:27.490
And that's by doing a
variety of different things,

02:08:27.490 --> 02:08:31.570
not just performing Beethoven
symphonies, but making sur

02:08:31.570 --> 02:08:33.890
that we're reaching out
to the entire community.

02:08:33.890 --> 02:08:35.780
Yeah.

02:08:35.780 --> 02:08:37.530
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Kevin,
how about you?

02:08:37.530 --> 02:08:38.830
Good for business?

02:08:38.830 --> 02:08:41.360
&gt;&gt; Kevin Shuck: Yes,
it's good for business.

02:08:41.360 --> 02:08:46.650
Since 2009 our ticket sales have
grown 66%, subscriptions 44%,

02:08:46.650 --> 02:08:49.810
contributive revenue
by similar amounts.

02:08:49.810 --> 02:08:52.100
And I think it's because when
you do this type of work,

02:08:52.100 --> 02:08:56.160
you're increasing the
number of stakeholders

02:08:56.160 --> 02:08:57.950
in your organization
and the community.

02:08:57.950 --> 02:09:00.170
So if you do one of
the collaborations

02:09:00.170 --> 02:09:01.710
like what Sandi was
talking about,

02:09:01.710 --> 02:09:06.440
which is a really key
part in these years,

02:09:06.440 --> 02:09:09.680
45 different organizations
we've collaborated with.

02:09:09.680 --> 02:09:12.050
And some of these are
what you'd expect,

02:09:12.050 --> 02:09:13.810
other performing
arts organizations,

02:09:13.810 --> 02:09:15.670
but some are what
you would not expect,

02:09:15.670 --> 02:09:17.420
like social service
organizations.

02:09:17.420 --> 02:09:21.660
Or nature and science
and youth organizations.

02:09:21.660 --> 02:09:24.730
And every time you do it, you're
going to get new ticket buyers

02:09:24.730 --> 02:09:28.170
in the door, maybe just
for that one concert.

02:09:28.170 --> 02:09:31.690
A certain portion will come
back, but even for the people

02:09:31.690 --> 02:09:35.220
that didn't come to the concert,
they now have a touchpoint

02:09:35.220 --> 02:09:36.630
for your organization.

02:09:36.630 --> 02:09:41.590
So they think that, oh, this
organization supported something

02:09:41.590 --> 02:09:46.230
that I care about,
so it's a checkmark

02:09:46.230 --> 02:09:48.790
in your column for good favor.

02:09:48.790 --> 02:09:50.650
And I think that
community goodwill can't

02:09:50.650 --> 02:09:53.710
be underestimated.

02:09:53.710 --> 02:09:57.520
The snowball effect I
think is really what it is,

02:09:57.520 --> 02:09:59.900
is that each time you
do something like this,

02:09:59.900 --> 02:10:01.370
it's another ripple in the pond.

02:10:01.370 --> 02:10:04.410
You're reaching additional
people.

02:10:04.410 --> 02:10:07.510
And sometimes we go
to a lot of effort

02:10:07.510 --> 02:10:12.040
for something we think is a good
idea, that really makes sense,

02:10:12.040 --> 02:10:15.310
and maybe the impact is not
as big as what we'd hoped for.

02:10:15.310 --> 02:10:19.420
And sometimes it goes beyond
our wildest projections.

02:10:19.420 --> 02:10:21.000
But it's a cumulative effect.

02:10:21.000 --> 02:10:25.580
And it's I think committing
to this type of approach,

02:10:25.580 --> 02:10:28.990
systematically and organically
throughout your organization

02:10:28.990 --> 02:10:32.340
which over the long
run has these benefits.

02:10:32.340 --> 02:10:33.640
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Right.

02:10:33.640 --> 02:10:36.030
Sarah, I'm not going to
ask you about business,

02:10:36.030 --> 02:10:40.860
but I am interested -- as a
creative person working a lot

02:10:40.860 --> 02:10:45.030
with orchestras, what's
the optimum for you

02:10:45.030 --> 02:10:47.350
in a relationship with an
orchestra that allows you

02:10:47.350 --> 02:10:52.030
to fully realize all of
your artistic aspirations?

02:10:52.030 --> 02:10:53.330
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland
Snider: You know,

02:10:53.330 --> 02:10:54.890
I've had a really
extraordinary experience

02:10:54.890 --> 02:10:56.850
with North Carolina
working on this project,

02:10:56.850 --> 02:10:59.260
because we've had
multiple performances,

02:10:59.260 --> 02:11:00.980
multiple rehearsals.

02:11:00.980 --> 02:11:04.310
Getting that kind of time to
get to now a conductor and get

02:11:04.310 --> 02:11:08.020
to know the members of the
orchestra, the administration,

02:11:08.020 --> 02:11:13.160
really enables the project
to go that much deeper and be

02:11:13.160 --> 02:11:14.460
that much more satisfying.

02:11:14.460 --> 02:11:16.730
I've since revised
the piece a few times,

02:11:16.730 --> 02:11:20.860
and I'll be revising it again.

02:11:20.860 --> 02:11:26.500
So yeah, I think that having
any kind of second performances,

02:11:26.500 --> 02:11:27.800
multiple performances

02:11:27.800 --> 02:11:29.660
for a composer these
days are pretty unusual

02:11:29.660 --> 02:11:30.960
in the orchestral world.

02:11:30.960 --> 02:11:35.620
So having a chance to go deeper
is really pretty extraordinary.

02:11:35.620 --> 02:11:41.840
But I think any time that an
orchestra can take a moment

02:11:41.840 --> 02:11:46.100
to really work with a living
composer is an incredible

02:11:46.100 --> 02:11:47.560
experience for everybody.

02:11:47.560 --> 02:11:49.670
I mean, it's great
for the community,

02:11:49.670 --> 02:11:52.290
it's great for composers
obviously.

02:11:52.290 --> 02:11:56.230
It's great for the orchestra
to feel connected to living,

02:11:56.230 --> 02:11:59.760
breathing music that
they can have a role

02:11:59.760 --> 02:12:01.980
in introducing to the world.

02:12:01.980 --> 02:12:04.390
I just think the more

02:12:04.390 --> 02:12:07.880
that living composers can
be introduced to orchestras,

02:12:07.880 --> 02:12:09.360
the better for everybody.

02:12:09.360 --> 02:12:11.600
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Yeah, kind of
the center of the whole thing.

02:12:11.600 --> 02:12:12.900
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider: Right.

02:12:12.900 --> 02:12:14.640
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: So Karen, you've
had about three hours to get

02:12:14.640 --> 02:12:18.460
to know the wonderful world
of orchestras [laughs].

02:12:18.460 --> 02:12:23.920
From what you've
heard, challenge us.

02:12:23.920 --> 02:12:27.350
You're an expert on this stuff,
on shifting and changing.

02:12:27.350 --> 02:12:29.270
What words of wisdom?

02:12:29.270 --> 02:12:31.670
&gt;&gt; Karen Dillon: One word of
wisdom I would sort of pass

02:12:31.670 --> 02:12:34.020
on from Clayton Christianson
-- they're not original to me.

02:12:34.020 --> 02:12:38.410
But the reason that so many
great organizations ultimately

02:12:38.410 --> 02:12:42.880
fail when faced with competition
from what he calls disruptors --

02:12:42.880 --> 02:12:46.190
small upstarts that initially
you don't see as a threat

02:12:46.190 --> 02:12:48.210
and then little by little
they gain market share.

02:12:48.210 --> 02:12:51.720
Great example is Blockbuster,
now bankrupt, and Netflix.

02:12:51.720 --> 02:12:53.390
Netflix was a disruptor.

02:12:53.390 --> 02:12:56.040
His theory is called the
theory of disruption,

02:12:56.040 --> 02:12:58.270
more famous than the
theory of jobs to be done.

02:12:58.270 --> 02:13:01.710
It's that the incumbent,
the established company,

02:13:01.710 --> 02:13:04.140
in the face of that
competition they get nervous

02:13:04.140 --> 02:13:07.070
and start making their
product better and better,

02:13:07.070 --> 02:13:09.930
more expensive, add
more layers of gold.

02:13:09.930 --> 02:13:11.810
You know, they make
it so that they want

02:13:11.810 --> 02:13:14.110
to make it more valuable
to their customer base.

02:13:14.110 --> 02:13:16.990
But what that does is it makes
them have an increasingly

02:13:16.990 --> 02:13:19.560
smaller customer base
because people start deciding,

02:13:19.560 --> 02:13:20.990
"This is good enough.

02:13:20.990 --> 02:13:22.290
Why should I spend that?"

02:13:22.290 --> 02:13:23.780
So I would just hear --

02:13:23.780 --> 02:13:25.670
I love hearing some of
these creative ideas

02:13:25.670 --> 02:13:29.910
for alternative things here, the
caution to not chase your market

02:13:29.910 --> 02:13:32.720
up further and further to
the point of losing them

02:13:32.720 --> 02:13:35.390
to a disruptor because you
think the best response

02:13:35.390 --> 02:13:37.110
to that threat is
to make ours better.

02:13:37.110 --> 02:13:38.810
Again, I would say
better in what way?

02:13:38.810 --> 02:13:40.110
Better for whom?

02:13:40.110 --> 02:13:41.410
Better for what job?

02:13:41.410 --> 02:13:43.070
Make sure that better
is always focused

02:13:43.070 --> 02:13:44.720
on what those customers want.

02:13:44.720 --> 02:13:46.400
And it's okay if it
comes in the form

02:13:46.400 --> 02:13:49.100
of disrupting yourself
with smaller ideas.

02:13:49.100 --> 02:13:50.760
I mean, you might as
well disrupt yourself

02:13:50.760 --> 02:13:52.060
and get all the revenue

02:13:52.060 --> 02:13:54.040
from both the disruption
and the existing one.

02:13:54.040 --> 02:13:57.440
So just to be careful not to
over-gild the lily in search

02:13:57.440 --> 02:14:00.360
of better when better is when
people come and hear you,

02:14:00.360 --> 02:14:02.130
however you want to be heard.

02:14:02.130 --> 02:14:03.580
Just keep that in mind.

02:14:03.580 --> 02:14:04.880
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Terrific.

02:14:04.880 --> 02:14:08.040
