Shift Festival tonight.

02:14:24.530 --> 02:14:27.080
Our program is, as I mentioned,

02:14:27.080 --> 02:14:30.730
has an unabashedly programmatic
title, The Nature of Music.

02:14:30.730 --> 02:14:32.730
Which is bringing all those kind

02:14:32.730 --> 02:14:38.820
of initiatives I was
just talking about to DC.

02:14:38.820 --> 02:14:40.930
We open with a new commission.

02:14:40.930 --> 02:14:43.470
It was commissioned
with National Endowment

02:14:43.470 --> 02:14:47.320
for the Arts money, the
Imagine Your Parks Initiative,

02:14:47.320 --> 02:14:51.570
to commemorate the centennial
of the National Parks Service.

02:14:51.570 --> 02:14:54.620
We have an adventurer-composer
who we've worked

02:14:54.620 --> 02:14:55.970
with before, Steven Lias.

02:14:55.970 --> 02:14:58.610
It will be the premier
of his work inspired

02:14:58.610 --> 02:15:00.670
by Rocky Mountain National Park.

02:15:00.670 --> 02:15:05.400
After that we have a mandolinist
from here close in Virginia.

02:15:05.400 --> 02:15:07.880
His concerto is called
From the Blue Ridge.

02:15:07.880 --> 02:15:10.770
So our goal with the
Nature of Music was not just

02:15:10.770 --> 02:15:12.860
to show off Colorado with
lots of pretty pictures

02:15:12.860 --> 02:15:15.520
of our mountains, but also that
these things are universal.

02:15:15.520 --> 02:15:18.390
So we have something from
local audiences here as well,

02:15:18.390 --> 02:15:20.130
from your backyard as well.

02:15:20.130 --> 02:15:23.320
The second half opens
up with a piece,

02:15:23.320 --> 02:15:25.460
Ghost of the Grasslands,
by Steve Heitzig.

02:15:25.460 --> 02:15:29.950
This is about the prairies, the
lesser-known half of Colorado.

02:15:29.950 --> 02:15:33.160
And interesting, percussionist
drummers like Stalks

02:15:33.160 --> 02:15:37.040
of Prairie Grass, Bison
Bones, Squeak Toys that Sound

02:15:37.040 --> 02:15:40.590
like Prairie Dogs, and then that
takes us into the grand finale

02:15:40.590 --> 02:15:43.260
which is Copelands Appalachian
Spring with something

02:15:43.260 --> 02:15:44.620
which is pretty eye-popping.

02:15:44.620 --> 02:15:48.400
Frequent Flyers Aerial Dance
Company we brought with us

02:15:48.400 --> 02:15:51.500
from Boulder do a
beautiful rendition suspended

02:15:51.500 --> 02:15:52.820
above the orchestra.

02:15:52.820 --> 02:15:54.120
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: Wow.

02:15:54.120 --> 02:15:56.040
And I have my tickets.

02:15:56.040 --> 02:15:58.060
[ Laughter ]

02:15:58.060 --> 02:16:04.310
So the North Carolina
Symphony is bringing a program

02:16:04.310 --> 02:16:06.810
that demonstrates who we are.

02:16:06.810 --> 02:16:13.660
We have two works by Robert
Ward who spent the mature part

02:16:13.660 --> 02:16:16.860
of his life in North
Carolina and was the dean

02:16:16.860 --> 02:16:21.150
of the University of North
Carolina School for the Arts

02:16:21.150 --> 02:16:22.860
and eventually became
an audience member

02:16:22.860 --> 02:16:24.160
of the North Carolina Symphony.

02:16:24.160 --> 02:16:27.090
So we bookend the performance
with two of his works.

02:16:27.090 --> 02:16:32.240
We will be joined by North
Carolina-born Pulitzer

02:16:32.240 --> 02:16:36.190
Prize-winning composer and
performer Caroline Shaw

02:16:36.190 --> 02:16:39.870
who will be the soloist
in her work, Low.

02:16:41.130 --> 02:16:46.010
And let me think -- thank you.

02:16:46.010 --> 02:16:49.310
Mason Bates -- I was going
to hand it over to you.

02:16:49.310 --> 02:16:56.350
Mason Bates work is evocative of
his time spent in the Carolinas.

02:16:56.350 --> 02:17:01.040
I believe he uses
cicada in his sounds,

02:17:01.040 --> 02:17:05.970
in his piece called
Rusty Carolina.

02:17:05.970 --> 02:17:11.200
And then the big centerpiece of
our program is our co-commission

02:17:11.200 --> 02:17:14.800
of Sarah's work, which maybe
you could tell us a little

02:17:14.800 --> 02:17:16.100
bit about.

02:17:16.100 --> 02:17:17.400
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland
Snider: Oh, okay.

02:17:17.400 --> 02:17:20.050
I felt like I gave you a lot
of information, but the name

02:17:20.050 --> 02:17:21.590
of the piece is Hierite.

02:17:21.590 --> 02:17:25.530
That's Welsh word that means a
longing for a time or a place

02:17:25.530 --> 02:17:29.360
in your past that you
can no longer return to.

02:17:29.360 --> 02:17:32.190
So yeah, I'm excited about that.

02:17:32.190 --> 02:17:34.080
&gt;&gt; Sandy MacDonald: And then
on Thursday night we'll be

02:17:34.080 --> 02:17:41.850
at the Cogod Gallery or
the auditorium, thank you.

02:17:41.850 --> 02:17:43.330
Space. Courtyard, there you go.

02:17:43.330 --> 02:17:47.860
Space. And with a program that
