02:17:47.860 --> 02:17:55.150
on Saturday night that featured
Sarah's piece Unremembered

02:17:55.150 --> 02:17:59.280
that has been traveling
the globe.

02:17:59.280 --> 02:18:04.060
And so her piece
with our orchestra,

02:18:04.060 --> 02:18:07.550
and as well a piece called
By and By, by Caroline Shaw.

02:18:07.550 --> 02:18:11.410
That program is an example

02:18:11.410 --> 02:18:13.200
of the North Carolina
Symphony getting

02:18:13.200 --> 02:18:15.840
out of a traditional concert
hall which we do frequently

02:18:15.840 --> 02:18:19.010
and performing our works
in a different space.

02:18:19.010 --> 02:18:20.310
&gt;&gt; Sarah Kirkland Snider:

02:18:20.310 --> 02:18:23.170
I think it's worth highlighting
too that something special

02:18:23.170 --> 02:18:26.710
about North Carolina Symphony
is that they like to go deep

02:18:26.710 --> 02:18:28.130
with the composers
they work with.

02:18:28.130 --> 02:18:33.340
So they do multiple pieces by a
certain set of composers rather

02:18:33.340 --> 02:18:36.750
than lots of pieces by
lots of different composers

02:18:36.750 --> 02:18:38.050
which I think is really special.

02:18:38.050 --> 02:18:41.120
Because it enables the community
to get to know artists better

02:18:41.120 --> 02:18:44.580
and feel a stronger connection
to each piece that they hear,

02:18:44.580 --> 02:18:47.120
because they have a
little more context for it.

02:18:47.120 --> 02:18:48.420
&gt;&gt; Jesse Rosen: Right.

02:18:48.420 --> 02:18:51.620
You know, earlier today
some of us right here

02:18:51.620 --> 02:18:54.060
in this library were looking
at the original manuscripts

02:18:54.060 --> 02:18:57.750
of Mozart and a lock
of Beethoven's hair

02:18:57.750 --> 02:19:01.390
and Bartok's manuscript
from the concerto orchestra

02:19:01.390 --> 02:19:02.820
Heiden Symphonies.

02:19:02.820 --> 02:19:06.320
And I couldn't help thinking
about this great sense

02:19:06.320 --> 02:19:09.570
of tradition and old stuff.

02:19:09.570 --> 02:19:11.960
And here we are hundreds
of years later,

02:19:11.960 --> 02:19:13.620
we're still playing
the same music.

02:19:13.620 --> 02:19:15.660
We're still playing
the same instruments

02:19:15.660 --> 02:19:17.590
and the same orchestra.

02:19:17.590 --> 02:19:19.780
And it reminded me -- this
will sound a little crazy --

02:19:19.780 --> 02:19:22.570
but I've been watching the
hearings for Judge Gorsuch

02:19:22.570 --> 02:19:25.570
and so the word originalist
which I didn't know before --

02:19:25.570 --> 02:19:27.550
now I know what an
originalist is.

02:19:27.550 --> 02:19:30.190
But the tension around
you know, the past

02:19:30.190 --> 02:19:33.420
and how does the past live
as you go into the future,

02:19:33.420 --> 02:19:34.730
is a question that kind of runs

02:19:34.730 --> 02:19:37.000
through so many aspects
of our lives.

02:19:37.000 --> 02:19:39.400
And I think the work
happening in orchestras

02:19:39.400 --> 02:19:40.870
of asking those same questions,

02:19:40.870 --> 02:19:43.380
we know this incredible
tradition.

02:19:43.380 --> 02:19:47.160
We learn from it, we revere
it, we're in awe of it.

02:19:47.160 --> 02:19:48.460
And yet we're also

02:19:48.460 --> 02:19:50.900
in a completely different
place and a different time.

02:19:50.900 --> 02:19:54.210
And so how do we make that
alive and real for today?

02:19:54.210 --> 02:19:57.290
And I think that's kind of the
journey orchestras have been on,

02:19:57.290 --> 02:19:59.340
along with probably
the rest of America.

02:19:59.340 --> 02:20:01.420
So anyhow, thank you
for being with us,

